<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Amish Owning More Farms / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The number of farms owned by Amish people in  
Lancaster County has increased by about 17 farms annually over the 
past 15 years, according to a new study of Amish farming. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, the proportion of farmers within the Amish  
church has declined since the mid-1980s, perhaps due to the move by 
Amish people into more cottage industries such as farm stands, bake 
shops and small tourist souvenirs, according to Conrad Kanagy, an 
associate professor of sociology at Elizabethtown College. 
</P>
<P>
	The study illuminates one of the central conflicts of Amish  
culture -- the balance between its agrarian roots and the struggle 
to make a living in an increasingly technical world. 
</P>
<P>
	``Reports of farming's demise among the Amish are exaggerated  
and inaccurate,'' Kanagy said Thursday. ``Although the proportion 
of Amish engaged in farming is declining, the actual number of 
Amish farmers and farms is increasing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Old Order Amish -- who are best known for their plain dress,  
horse-drawn buggies and eschewing of modern conveniences -- owned 
1,317 farms, or about 103,000 acres, in Lancaster County in 1997, 
Kanagy's study said. That is up from 1,200 farms, or 88,000 acres, 
in 1984. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, Old Order Amish farmers make up about 38 percent of all  
farmers in Lancaster County, a higher percentage than had been 
expected by experts. Including the Old Order Mennonites -- who dress 
in similar Plain clothing as the Amish -- the Plain groups own 57 
percent of all Lancaster County farms, Kanagy said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Part of this is because mainstream Mennonites and English as  
well are rapidly giving up farming,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Elizabethtown College study is one of the first in many  
years to examine the state of Amish farming. Experts estimated that 
Amish farm ownership is declining, often citing anecdotal evidence 
of Amish farmers-turned-businessmen. 
</P>
<P>
	The new study confirmed that presumption. Only 44 percent of Old  
Order Amish men owned farmland in Lancaster County in 1997, down 
from 53 percent in 1984. 
</P>
<P>
	The percentage of farmers has decreased while the number of  
farms has increased because the population of the Amish has doubled 
in the past 20 years to about 20,000 adults. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a lot of income coming into the Amish community  
through cottage industries,'' said Wes Newswanger, director of the 
Mennonite Information Center. ``Maybe the teen-aged boy would go 
off and get a job with the local builder and the mom might be 
making quilts or painting and selling them with their local crafts 
store.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The study also found that Lancaster County farms are smaller and  
six to seven times more profitable than other Amish communities 
around the country. Lancaster farms average about 86 acres per 
farm, making an average of $1,900 per acre. In comparison, farms in 
Holmes County, Ohio -- which is the nation's largest Amish 
settlement -- average 142 acres each and yield an average of $519 an 
acre. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is so much better because the limestone base makes it  
exceedingly rich,'' Kanagy said. 
</P>
<P>
	The study is based on tax assessment records since 1984 of  
Lancaster County landowners with more than 25 acres, which were 
coded as agricultural. That was then compared with Old Order Amish 
church directories, which are considered very accurate. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
