<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Does L.A. Really Want an NFL Team? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	As Los Angeles struggles to get back in the NFL game, three  
California cities that do have franchises are being thrown for 
losses. 
</P>
<P>
	Having the Raiders back is costing Oakland taxpayers millions.  
</P>
<P>
	San Diego has had to pony up for unsold Chargers tickets, and  
the city once planned to buy the tickets, then trash them. 
</P>
<P>
	The 49ers' plan for a new stadium stalled because of a family  
feud over ownership, and voters eventually may be asked to approve 
more public funding or risk losing the team. 
</P>
<P>
	So Los Angeles really wants a team of its own?  
</P>
<P>
	``You look at what's going on in California. Al Davis bounced up  
and down the coast, looking to maximize his investment,'' said Dave 
Synowka, a professor of sports management at Robert Morris College 
in Pennsylvania. ``He got a tremendous deal to move back, but how 
has it translated? He has alienated a lot of fans and 
politicians.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although a group of wealthy Los Angeles businessmen put together  
a plan to return the NFL to the Coliseum with mostly private 
financing, talks snagged when the league asked that $150 million in 
public funds be committed to the project. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all understand the reality of taxes in California since  
someone named Jarvis came on the national scene. But by the same 
token, this has to be a public-private partnership to succeed,'' 
NFL commissioner Paul Taglibue said earlier this year when the 
league zeroed in on the Coliseum. 
</P>
<P>
	Because California still has the grass-roots, tax-cutting spirit  
that began with Howard Jarvis years ago, any plan to use taxpayer 
money to get a team would meet stiff opposition in LA. However, a 
recent proposal to use taxes from the revenues generated by a team 
might have a chance of being approved. 
</P>
<P>
	``The NFL is coming along after well-publicized fiascos in  
Oakland, San Francisco and San Diego, and I think taxpayers are 
more alert,'' said Ron Roach, spokesman for the Sacramento-based 
California Taxpayers' Association. 
</P>
<P>
	``Someone's got to draw the line. Maybe if they do it in LA,  
they'll do it in Houston and elsewhere. You would think that the 
NFL would pay LA to put a team there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There has been no great public outcry over Los Angeles' lack of  
a franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	``In some ways, I think the LA situation is unique,'' said Allen  
Sanderson, a University of Chicago economics professor who follows 
sports business. ``California has good weather and people have a 
lot of alternatives for entertainment and recreation. If they want 
to see football, they can go to a USC or UCLA game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Oil billionaire Marvin Davis, who has talked with the league  
about building a stadium at Hollywood Park, reportedly is 
considering spending more than $1 billion of his own money to get a 
team. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanderson believes Los Angeles eventually will have a team.  
</P>
<P>
	``The NFL will blink a little, LA will blink a little, and they  
will get a team, whether it's the 32nd or the 34th franchise,'' he 
said. ``Usually negotiations are one-sided. The cartel (the NFL) 
picks a city apart and can fleece it. 
</P>
<P>
	``But LA has about as level a playing field as a city is going  
to have with the NFL. If the mayor and officials and taxpayers play 
their cards right, they might wind up getting taken to a smaller 
cleaners than other cities have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Los Angeles area has been without a team since the Rams left  
Anaheim for St. Louis and the Raiders left the LA Coliseum to 
return to Oakland, both following the 1994 season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Raiders' return has caused massive headaches for Oakland and  
Alameda County. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis and the Raiders have sued, claiming they can break their  
lease because the city and county failed to sell out home games. 
Oakland and Alameda County filed a lawsuit last year asking that 
the Raiders be bound to their lease. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of low attendance and higher than anticipated costs  
since the Raiders returned, the shortfall that will be covered by 
Oakland and by Alameda County is projected at $27.5 million for 
this fiscal year, county auditor-controller Patrick O'Connell said. 
</P>
<P>
	In San Diego, tickets have created a public relations  
embarrassment for the city, including the time the city council 
voted to buy unused Chargers tickets at $40 apiece and trash them. 
That idea was short-lived; the city still buys unused tickets, but 
donates them to military bases and other groups. 
</P>
<P>
	San Diego's contract with the Chargers contains a clause  
guaranteeing the team ticket sales of at least 60,000 per home 
game. If the gate falls short, the city purchases the remaining 
tickets and deducts the cost from stadium rent the Chargers pay -- 
one game last year cost the city $882,463 for 21,129 tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	A study predicted the guarantee will cost San Diego more than $1  
million in lost revenue for each year it's in effect, through the 
2006 season. 
</P>
<P>
	In San Francisco, the 49ers said two years ago they might move  
if they didn't get a new stadium. Voters narrowly approved a $100 
million bond toward a $500 million shopping mall-stadium complex. 
That plan has been shelved, however, because of soaring cost 
estimates and a team ownership dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of the uncertainty over the stadium, the NFL took away  
the 2003 Super Bowl planned for the new facility. 
</P>
<P>
	That turned out to be a bonus for San Diego, which has been the  
host city for two Super Bowls and now will do it again in 2003. 
</P>
<P>
	San Diego Deputy City Manager Bruce Herring would tell other  
cities -- such as Los Angeles -- that having an NFL team is worth any 
hassles. 
</P>
<P>
	``An NFL team adds a lot to a city in terms of making it a big  
league city, and esprit de corps and all that,'' Herring said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
