<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar Mostly Up; Gold Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar rose against most other major  
currencies in European trading but was lower against the yen today. 
Gold rose. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0434 in late European trading, down  
from $1.0507 Wednesday.Later, in midday trading in New York, the 
euro traded at $1.0408. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates in Eurpoe, compared with late Wednesday,  
included 103.94 Japanese yen, down from 104.22; 1.5348 Swiss 
francs, up from 1.5252; 1.4722 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4698. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.6392, up from $1.6388.  
</P>
<P>
	In midday trading in New York, the dollar bought 103.98 yen and  
the pound was worth $1.6378. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth 1.8750 German marks, up from 1.8615; 
6.2873 French francs, up from 6.2430; 2.1445 Dutch guilders, up 
from 2.0974; 1,859.60 Italian lire, up from 1,842.04. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $264.40 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$264.20 on Wednesday. In Zurich the bid price was $264.55, up from 
$264.05. Gold rose 70 cents in Hong Kong to $263.55. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $5.27 bid per troy ounce, unchanged  
from late Wednesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
