<DOCNO> APW19990923.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 15:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Soar as Investors Seek Safety / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices soared Wednesday, pushing the  
30-year bond yield below 6 percent for the first time in nearly 
four weeks, as a selloff in stocks sent investors seeking the 
safety of government-backed securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Bonds also got a push from a growing consensus among analysts  
that interest rates will remain stable for now. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 1 3/8 points,  
or $13.75 cents per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in 
the opposite direction, fell to 5.98 percent from 6.08 percent late 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The last time the yield on the long-term Treasury closed below 6  
percent was Aug. 27, when it was 5.97 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Government bonds, with a reputation as a secure investment,  
spiked higher in a ``flight to safety'' as stocks plummeted on Wall 
Street. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average fell 2 percent Thursday and has  
swooned more than 500 points, or by 4.5 percent, over the past 
three sessions. 
</P>
<P>
	Also helping bonds was increasing sentiment among traders that  
the Federal Reserve will leave interest rates stable at its Oct. 5 
meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
rose 3/16 point to 1/4 point, while intermediate maturities rose 
15/32 to 7/8 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial information 
service. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading Wednesday, yields on three-month Treasury bills  
fell to 4.79 percent, as the discount fell 0.01 percentage point 
from Wedmesday to 4.67 percent. Six-month yields fell to 5.01 
percent, as the discount fell 0.04 percentage point to 4.82 
percent. One-year yields slipped to 5.16 percent as the discount 
fell 0.05 percentage point to 4.90 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 5.31 1/4 percent from 5.25 percent late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds rose 1/8 to 112 17/32. The average yield to 
maturity of the index was unchanged at 5.89 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
