<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Launches Television Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SECAUCUS, N.J. (AP) -- The NBA will soon be playing around the  
clock on a television screen near you. 
</P>
<P>
	NBA.com TV, a 24-hour television network, will be launched Nov.  
2, the night the regular season opens. 
</P>
<P>
	``NBA.com TV represents the convergence of the Internet,  
television and basketball,'' commissioner David Stern said in a 
statement released by NBA Entertainment. ``By combining the 
immediacy and depth of information from NBA.com with current and 
historical television programming from the NBA, NBA.com TV will 
offer our fans complete, round-the-clock coverage of the league.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This will be the first time a sports league has created a  
full-time television network. Produced by NBA Entertainment, 
NBA.com TV will combine scores, news and statistics from the 
league's official Internet site, NBA.com, with live ``look-ins'' of 
games in progress, highlights, vintage NBA games and videos, as 
well as basketball-related talk shows and movies. 
</P>
<P>
	``We see this as an opportunity to tap into the rich array of  
information available on NBA.com and the vast television 
programming from NBAE's video and film library,'' Adam Silver, 
president of NBA Entertainment said. ``This is also an opportunity 
to produce and acquire new and original basketball-themed 
programming specifically for the network.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NBA.com TV will be available to more than 5.6 million homes  
through DIRECTV, the nation's largest direct broadcast satellite 
service, and in an additional one million homes with upgraded 
digital cable systems through Viewer's Choice. NBA.com TV will be 
provided at no additional charge to DIRECTV customers who subscribe 
to NBA LEAGUE PASS, Total Choice Platinum or Total Choice Gold. 
</P>
<P>
	NBA LEAGUE PASS provides all games out of a viewer's immediate  
area. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
