<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 10:01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boxer Joppy Learning Patience </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Eight months after William Joppy broke his  
neck in a car accident, he's ready to defend his WBA middleweight 
title. The waiting was the hardest part. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was an impatient person before the accident,'' Joppy said.  
</P>
<P>
	``(Then) I couldn't run, I couldn't do anything for the months  
of February and March. You just don't know how miserable I was. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now I've got a little patience. It slowed me down.''  
</P>
<P>
	Joppy faces Dominican Republic native Julio Cesar Green -- who  
became interim WBA champion while Joppy recovered -- in a 
middleweight title doubleheader Friday night at the MCI Center. WBC 
champion Keith Holmes (33-2, 22 KOs) of Washington meets Andrew 
Council (30-6-3, 20 KOs) of Lanham, Md., in the other major bout. 
</P>
<P>
	Joppy (27-1-1, 21 KOs) and Green (25-3, 17 KOs) are fighting for  
the third time. Green, despite getting knocked down twice in the 
third round, rallied to win the decision and the title from Joppy 
at Madison Square Garden in August 1997. Joppy regained the title 
on another 12-round decision in January 1998 at Tampa, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	After beating Roberto Duran in August 1998, Joppy had been  
scheduled to defend thr title against Darren Obah of Australia at 
Washington in February. Then, on the way to his Silver Spring, Md., 
home from a training session, Joppy's van was hit by another 
vehicle. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew something was wrong,'' Joppy said. ``But I didn't know  
it was as serious as it was.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Joppy had a broken vertebrae. It was not a major fracture, but  
enough to keep him out of the gym for months. He didn't have to do 
anything special for rehabilitation -- except wait. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just time,'' Joppy said. ``Every day it got better and better.  
I knew I was coming back. I believed. I didn't feel it was that 
bad. I was already in good condition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Joppy is pleased to be making his return in front of the home  
fans. Big-name promoters bypassed Washington for years, but 
promoter Don King has made the nation's capital a regular stop by 
scheduling three world title cards already this year. The District 
of Columbia City Council showed its appreciation this week by 
declaring Friday ``Don King Day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A third title fight scheduled on Friday's card, WBA junior  
welterweight champion Sharmba Mitchell against Elio Ortiz, was 
postponed after Mitchell strained a rib muscle in training. No new 
date has been set. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990923.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 06:50:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> West Va. Community Without Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JEFFERSON, W.Va. (AP) -- It has the reputation as one of the  
bleaker towns in the state and now it won't even have its 
dust-covered police car to provide local protection. 
</P>
<P>
	The cops in tiny Jefferson -- known to some locals as the  
Badlands and the site of a trio of homicides last December -- are 
sidelined. Kanawha County Prosecutor Bill Forbes last week ordered 
feuding officials in this 2.8-mile strip of bars, clubs and X-rated 
bookstores to agree how they'll hire police. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a zoo down there, as you can imagine,'' Forbes said.  
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, State Police and county sheriff's deputies will  
provide protection for the town of about 400 residents just outside 
West Virginia's capital of Charleston. 
</P>
<P>
	Jefferson, hemmed in between railroad tracks on the north, the  
scenic Kanawha River on the south and with a billboard-covered 
highway right down the middle, began grappling with trouble in 
June. 
</P>
<P>
	The town's two police officers quit when Councilwoman Kathy  
Wolfe defeated incumbent Mayor Dan Jackson in municipal elections. 
One of the officers was Jackson's nephew. 
</P>
<P>
	``They left the squad car sitting on the side of the road,''  
said Councilman John Ash, an ally of Wolfe's and her boss at 
Po-Boy's Used Tires. 
</P>
<P>
	``And it had this much dust on it,'' Wolfe said, holding her  
thumb and index finger wide apart. 
</P>
<P>
	A feud soon developed between two council factions over who will  
hire police officers. ``I kept hiring and they kept firing,'' Wolfe 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson said Wolfe refuses to work with the council.  
</P>
<P>
	``She wants to run everything her way,'' he said. ``She thinks  
she's got an iron fist.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rival council members hired a police chief, who accused the two  
new $9-an-hour officers of impersonating police. That's when Forbes 
stepped in, invoking state law authorizing him to act as the 
county's chief law enforcement officer. 
</P>
<P>
	He dismissed the impersonation charges and said town officials  
may not hire police officers unless the mayor and the council act 
together. Meanwhile, state and county authorities will provide 
protection. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't have people going out in a high-speed chase or be the  
first at the scene of a murder and screwing things up,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wolfe said she will telephone her rivals to determine ``if  
they'll meet with me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So far, that's been daunting. The two factions have been meeting  
separately, one at the fire department and the other at a meeting 
room at a local motel. 
</P>
<P>
	``How can they solve anything like that?'' asked Jo Spainhour, a  
25-year resident. ``They need to work for the people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wolfe said she wants to move on to other local issues, such as  
taxes, but Forbes said town officials must first solve their 
political problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone,'' he said, ``needs to look at the dysfunctional form  
of government down there.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
