<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton To Fight Money-Laundering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration proposed a national  
strategy to fight money laundering Thursday, an announcement given 
extra attention in light of the government's inquiry into 
allegations of a huge scheme involving Russians and a big U.S. 
bank. 
</P>
<P>
	The package of proposed new laws and rules is aimed at stanching  
the flow of billions of criminal dollars, largely drug-trafficking 
profits, through the U.S. financial system. 
</P>
<P>
	Administration officials stressed that the long-awaited  
strategy, made public a few weeks after allegations of 
money-laundering through the Bank of New York came to light, has a 
far broader scope than Russia or any one country. 
</P>
<P>
	``Money laundering is a very sophisticated crime and we must be  
equally sophisticated,'' Attorney General Janet Reno said at a news 
conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Accompanying her was Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers, who  
called the package ``an essential front in the war on narcotics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The strategy seeks to bolster international cooperation in  
investigating money laundering and to strengthen U.S. enforcement 
through tighter regulation of banks and other financial 
institutions. It includes a requirement that storefront check 
cashiers, brokerage firms and casinos notify authorities of 
suspicious activities the way banks must do. 
</P>
<P>
	The government would designate new high-intensity  
money-laundering zones, industries and financial institutions, and 
``action teams'' of law enforcement authorities and regulators 
would be formed to concentrate on those areas. 
</P>
<P>
	The package also includes proposed legislation that would add  
new international crimes, such as corruption and illegal arms 
dealing, to the activities subject to U.S. prosecution under 
money-laundering laws. Tax evasion, which may have played a major 
role in the Bank of New York case, is not included. 
</P>
<P>
	Key Republican lawmakers have endorsed the proposals. Congress  
directed the Treasury and Justice departments to submit the new 
strategy early this year, before the case involving Russians and 
the Bank of New York broke. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal investigators have been trying to unravel the Bank of  
New York case. Russian businesses and individuals -- including 
organized crime groups -- are suspected of illegally channeling as 
much as $10 billion through the bank, the nation's 15th-largest and 
said to be its oldest. 
</P>
<P>
	Several other big U.S. banks also had accounts owned by or  
linked to a company at the center of the investigation. The 
company's owner, a Russian emigrant, is married to a former Bank of 
New York executive who was fired after news of the inquiry 
surfaced. 
</P>
<P>
	No one has been charged in the investigation by law enforcement  
authorities in the United States, Britain, Russia and other 
countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Deputy Treasury Secretary Stuart Eizenstat highlighted the  
complexities, noting, ``We don't know whether it involved illicit 
money or not. ... We don't know whether this is money laundering, 
capital flight or something else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under the capital flight scenario, at least some of the money  
funneled through the Bank of New York could have come from 
thousands of small- to medium-sized Russian businesses that 
spirited funds through offshore companies to avoid enormous taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	The practice is illegal but extremely widespread in Russia,  
where taxes are punitive, rules are ever-changing and tax police 
say as many as 99 percent of businesses skirt some taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	On Capitol Hill Thursday, Deputy Secretary of State Strobe  
Talbott told the Senate Foreign Relations Committee he could not 
say with any certainty how many U.S. tax dollars, in the form of 
International Monetary Fund loans, may have been funneled out of 
Russia in money-laundering schemes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are all seeking to establish the facts,'' Talbott said.  
</P>
<P>
	``There is no question that Russia has suffered, generally, from  
the problem of capital flight,'' he said. ``Much of it goes, 
literally, into mattresses, because Russians don't trust banks. And 
much of it has fled the country.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
