<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Mixed; Dow Down 2.85 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were narrowly mixed in early trading  
today as blue-chip stocks struggled to recover from two days of 
steep losses. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones  
industrial average was down 2.85 at 10,521.22. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500  
index was down 0.13 at 1,310.38, and the Nasdaq composite index was 
up 2.38 at 2,860.54. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors found little reason today to snap up stocks, as the  
dollar continued its slide against the Japanese yen. In European 
trading, the dollar was quoted at 104.01 yen, down from 104.22 yen 
late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar's weakness against the yen has contributed to a sharp  
decline in U.S. stocks this week, pushing the Dow down nearly 300 
points in the past two sessions. A weaker dollar makes imports more 
expensive, setting the stage for inflation. It also makes foreign 
investments more alluring. 
</P>
<P>
	United Technologies held the Dow lower, falling 2 5/8 to 56, after  
announcing plans to eliminate 14,500 jobs worldwide over the next 
three years -- 10 percent of its workforce -- because of a downturn 
in the aerospace industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nasdaq's modest gains were stimulated by the merger of two  
Internet service providers, EarthLink and MindSpring. Earthlink 
rose 3 1/8 to 46 5/8 and MindSpring fell 2 3/8 to 30 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 10-to-9 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 108.79 million 
shares, slightly ahead of Wednesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index rose 1.20 to 428.73.  
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's stock market was closed for a national  
holiday. In afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 1.2 
percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 1.4 percent, and France's 
CAC-40 was up 0.6 percent. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
