<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Dolphin Scheduled for Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BILOXI, Miss. (AP) -- Former Miami Dolphins running back Irving  
Spikes is scheduled for an Oct. 4 trial on federal drug and weapons 
charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Spikes and others were indicted as the result of an FBI  
investigation into cocaine sales in Ocean Springs, Spikes' 
hometown. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal authorities charged Spikes, who played for the Dolphins  
from 1994-98, with twice selling cocaine to the target of the 
investigation. The FBI identified that individual as Derek Lamont 
Joiner and has described him as a major drug dealer. 
</P>
<P>
	Spikes also sold fake cocaine to Joiner, and tried to do the  
same thing in March, when one of Spikes' accomplices got into a 
shootout with Joiner and took $17,000 from the man, the FBI 
charged. 
</P>
<P>
	Spikes has also been indicted in Florida of drug conspiracy and  
possession with intent to sell. 
</P>
<P>
	In Mississippi, the grand jury indicted Spikes on only one of  
the four drug charges filed against him. He was also indicted for 
using a firearm in connection with drug trafficking. 
</P>
<P>
	Spikes faces the possibility of spending the rest of his life in  
a federal prison, if convicted. He remains in the Harrison County 
jail without bond. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
