<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 14:40:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Candidates' Stance on the Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Positions of the Democratic and Republican presidential  
candidates on the military: 
</P>
<P>
	 *Democrats:    	
</P>
<P>
	Bill Bradley: Says Clinton administration is increasing military  
spending too much. As senator voted against Strategic Defense 
Initiative (SDI) deployment and B-2 stealth bombers, and for 
sanctions instead of military force against Iraq. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore: Has helped negotiate arms reduction and  
nuclear stability arrangements with former Soviet states. As 
senator, voted in support of SDI and B-2s, and for cuts in smaller 
weapons programs. Backed military force in Persian Gulf War. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *Republicans:    	
</P>
<P>
	Gary Bauer: Increase military spending, expand NATO, develop  
national missile defense system, defeat ``isolationist voices'' in 
U.S. 
</P>
<P>
	Pat Buchanan: ``Retrench and rearm,'' limit foreign  
intervention, return many troops from abroad, build national 
missile defense system. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. George Bush: Increase weapons research and development  
spending by $20 billion over five years, spend extra $1 billion a 
year to raise military salaries beyond pending pay increase, build 
missile defense systems for deployment inside and outside U.S. 
</P>
<P>
	Elizabeth Dole: Increase military spending, develop national  
missile defense system. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Forbes: Build national missile defense system. Says  
military spending is too low. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Orrin Hatch: Voted against round of base closings and in  
favor of giving Congress stronger say on future of bases. Voted 
against cutting money for F-18 fighter planes. 
</P>
<P>
	Alan Keyes: Criticized U.S. intervention in Kosovo as precedent  
for ``new internationalism,'' but supported strikes against alleged 
terrorist targets in Sudan and Afghanistan. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. John McCain: Close more bases to save $4 billion, build  
national missile defense system, discard 1972 Anti-Ballistic 
Missile Treaty with Russia that stands in way of missile system, 
spend more on personnel, reject foreign or shared command of U.S. 
military operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Dan Quayle: Spend more on the military, build national missile  
defense system, discard ABM treaty. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990923.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 07:50:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mets To Field Team in Brooklyn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Mets bought a Class-A minor league  
team Wednesday and plans to relocate the club to Brooklyn for next 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets purchased the St. Catharines franchise of the New  
York-Penn League. St. Catharines has an affiliation agreement with 
the Toronto Blue Jays through the 2000 season, and the new team 
will field Blue Jays minor leaguers for its first season. 
</P>
<P>
	The team would be the first to play in Brooklyn since the  
Dodgers left following the 1957 season. It would be the second 
minor league team in New York City, joining the Yankees' Staten 
Island affiliate of the New York-Penn League. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are pleased to have a signed agreement and expect to close  
the deal around year end,'' said Dave Howard, a senior vice 
president for the Mets. ``We are very excited about the prospect of 
returning professional baseball to Brooklyn next season.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990923.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 16:10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Sept. 23, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	NASA Spacecraft Vanishes Near Mars  
</P>
<P>
	PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- A $125 million NASA spacecraft that had  
traveled 416 million miles to Mars vanished today as it was about 
to go into orbit around the Red Planet and it was feared destroyed. 
It was the second time in six years that a NASA spaceship was lost 
just as it reached Mars. The Mars Climate Orbiter, which was on a 
mission to study the planet's weather and look for signs of water, 
apparently flew too close to the Martian atmosphere and broke apart 
or burned up, the space agency said. The apparent loss, after the 
$1 billion Mars Observer probe disappeared in 1993, comes as 
Congress is threatening to cut a large portion of NASA's space 
exploration budget. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Drops 205.48 on Interest Rate Fears  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks plummeted today as investors sold heavily  
amid continued worries about higher interest rates and the strength 
of the dollar. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 205.48 to 
close at 10,318.59, bringing the Dow's decline over the past three 
sessions to 505.31 points. The Nasdaq composite index fell 108.33 
to 2,749.83, its fourth-biggest decline ever. The U.S. currency is 
lingering near its lowest levels against the yen since 1996, making 
imports more expensive and setting the stage for inflation. It also 
makes foreign investments more attractive. 

</P>
<P>
	President Vetoes GOP's $792B Tax Cut  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton vetoed the Republicans' $792  
billion tax cut bill Thursday, saying it would undermine efforts to 
shore up the Social Security and Medicare programs, to reduce the 
national debt and to improve education. ``At a time when America is 
moving in the right direction,'' the president said, ``this bill 
would turn us back to the failed policies of the past.'' 
Republicans shot back that taxes are too high and that Americans 
deserve a break. 

</P>
<P>
	Dragging Defendant Sentenced to Die  
</P>
<P>
	BRYAN, Texas (AP) -- A jury decided today that racist ex-convict  
Lawrence Russell Brewer should pay with his life for the dragging 
death of a black man, sending him to death row to join an 
accomplice in the crime. James Byrd Jr., 49, was chained at the 
ankles to a pickup truck and dragged to pieces in the East Texas 
town of Jasper last year. Brewer's former prison buddy, John 
William King, 24, is already on death row, convicted in February in 
the murder of Byrd. A third man, Shawn Allen Berry, 24, goes on 
trial next month. Prosecutors will seek the death penalty in that 
case, too. 

</P>
<P>
	China Condemns U.S. Inquiry of Spying  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- China today condemned a widening U.S. inquiry  
into allegations of nuclear espionage and insisted anew that NATO 
intentionally bombed the Chinese Embassy in Yugoslavia. Turning a 
joint news conference with Secretary of State Madeleine Albright 
into a public lecture, Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan also 
assailed the president of Taiwan, Lee Teng-hui, as a troublemaker 
for trying to promote a special state-to-state relationship with 
China. 

</P>
<P>
	Actor George C. Scott Dead at 71  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- George C. Scott, whose commanding,  
gravel-voiced demeanor brought life to Gen. George S. Patton and 
earned him an Oscar he refused to accept, has died. He was 71. 
Scott died yesterday, Pat Mahoney, wife of Scott's publicist, Jim 
Mahoney, said today. For all his success in motion pictures, Scott 
disdained moviemaking, saying it was tedious and he did it only for 
the money. ``I have to work in the theater to stay sane,'' he said. 

</P>
<P>
	Earthlink, Mindspring To Merge  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- EarthLink Network Inc. and MindSpring  
Enterprises Inc., two fast-growing providers of dial-up access to 
the Internet, are merging in a $1.4 billion stock swap to create a 
tough new rival to America Online Inc. The entity created by 
today's transaction would have 3 million subscribers when the deal 
closes early next year, eclipsing the 2.5 million users of AT&AMP;T 
online services, and the 1.8 million who connect to the Web through 
Microsoft's MSN service. But it would still be far less than AOL's 
total of 20 million subscribers. 

</P>
<P>
	Braves Sweep Mets in Atlanta  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Chipper Jones hit his fourth homer in three games  
against the New York Mets, a three-run shot in the fifth inning 
that helped the Atlanta Braves complete a sweep of New York with a 
6-3 victory today. The Braves, who began the series with a one-game 
advantage in the National League East, now lead the second-place 
Mets by four games with only nine to play. Cincinnati trails the 
Mets by only two games in the NL wild-card race. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRAD FOSS  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
