<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 01:10:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Spending Panel Deadlocks on Abortion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A dispute over antiabortion restrictions is  
again threatening major foreign-policy legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	House and Senate negotiators deadlocked late Wednesday on a  
$12.6 billion foreign aid bill when they could not agree on 
proposed restrictions on U.S. funds for international organizations 
that support abortion rights. 
</P>
<P>
	A similar dispute threatens to hold up separate legislation that  
would authorize about $1 billion in delinquent U.S. payments to the 
United Nations, some of which dates to the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest snag came a day after President Clinton told the U.N.  
General Assembly he would redouble efforts this year to end what 
has become a perennial dispute with the Republican-led Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	The foreign aid bill already was threatened by a presidential  
veto because of its deep cuts in many international programs. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration also is unhappy that negotiators rejected its  
request to provide funds for carrying out the so-called Wye River 
Middle East peace accords. 
</P>
<P>
	Not only has Congress ignored the administration's request for  
at least $500 million for Israel and the Palestinians to carry out 
the accords in the fiscal year that begins Oct. 1, but foreign aid 
negotiators also cut $100 billion that had been promised to Jordan. 
</P>
<P>
	``Money for Jordan was in the bill and it was taken out,''  
complained Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican leaders said they supported U.S. funds to support the  
peace plan, negotiated at Wye River, Md., in late 1998, but that 
spending ceilings under the 1997 balanced-budget act made it hard 
to find the money at this time. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., chairman of the Senate negotiating  
team, suggested it could be taken care of in an emergency spending 
bill expected to deal with damage from this month's hurricanes. 
Money contained in such emergency bills is exempt from the spending 
ceilings. 
</P>
<P>
	But Rep. David Obey of Wisconsin, senior Democrat on the House  
Appropriations Committee, asserted, ``Wye is in significant 
jeopardy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Steps by congressional conservatives to attach antiabortion  
restrictions to foreign policy measures have drawn vetoes from 
Clinton in the past. 
</P>
<P>
	House negotiators said Wednesday they were willing to drop  
controversial language that would deny U.S. funds to support 
organizations that lobby foreign governments to repeal antiabortion 
laws. 
</P>
<P>
	But in return, they wanted to eliminate $25 million previously  
approved by both House and Senate for the United Nation's family 
planning assistance program. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate negotiators refused to go along with the cut in funds,  
and the talks were recessed, at least for the time being. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we're right back where we've been in the past,'' said  
Rep. Sonny Callahan, R-Ala., chairman of the House negotiators, 
told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Current law already bans the use of U.S. taxpayer funds from  
going to organizations that perform abortions overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	But conservatives, led by Rep. Christopher Smith, R-N.J., have  
managed to attach an amendment to various bills that would extend 
the prohibition to organizations that merely support abortion 
rights or lobby for changes in abortion laws. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
