<HEADLINE> Soybean, Grain Futures Prices Mixed / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean and grain futures prices were mixed in  
early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade, as investors 
kept an eye on harvest conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean futures prices rose slightly after weekly export sales  
proved stronger than expected, but then turned lower. Soybean 
prices have dropped in the past week as the harvest accelerated and 
forecasts predicted ideal weather conditions through the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures opened slightly lower, despite support from strong  
but anticipated USDA weekly export sales. Wheat inched higher, 
before falling. Oats opened slightly higher. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery fell 1 3/4 cents to $2.69 a bushel;  
December corn fell 1 3/4 cents to $2.09 1/2 a bushel; December oats rose 
1 1/4 cents to $1.13 a bushel; November soybeans fell 1 3/4 cents to 
$4.83 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Pork futures advanced on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, while  
beef futures fell. 
</P>
<P>
	October live cattle fell .30 cent to $66.05 a pound; October  
feeder cattle fell .15 cent to $79.17 a pound; October lean hogs 
rose .15 cent to $45.70 a pound; February frozen pork bellies rose 
.45 cent to $60.10 a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
