<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lehman Bros. Posts 92 Percent Jump </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Lehman Brothers Holdings Inc. reported profits  
Thursday of $290 million for its fiscal third quarter, a 92 percent 
increase from last year's figure and well above analysts' 
predictions. 
</P>
<P>
	Lehman attributed the strong earnings numbers to the company's  
increased focus on its highly profitable investment banking and 
stock trading units. 
</P>
<P>
	Lehman earned $2.20 a share, 19 cents more than analysts'  
expectations of $2.01 a share. The previous high was $2.12 a share, 
posted in the second quarter of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	During the third quarter of 1998, the New York-based company  
reported net income of $151 million, or $1.10 a share. 
</P>
<P>
	``The firm is well on its way to having its most profitable year  
ever, a clear indication that our strategy of expanding key 
business franchises and broadening our international presence has 
been successful,'' Richard S. Fuld Jr., chairman and chief 
executive of Lehman, said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	But Lehman's stock fell along with the rest of the stock market  
Thursday. Shares fell $1.87 1/2 to $53.37 1/2 in trading on the New York 
Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Net revenues, which exclude interest expenses, totaled $1.36  
billion for the three months ended Aug. 31, up from $930 million in 
the year-ago period. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first nine months of Lehman's fiscal year, profits  
totaled $830 million, a 25 percent increase from the $662 million 
in the first nine months of fiscal 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine month revenues were $3.93 billion vs. $3.45 billion.  




</P>
</TEXT>
