<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 8 European Stock Exchanges To Link </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- Eight European stock markets agreed  
Thursday to join in a ``virtual'' exchange that would give 
customers a single, computerized point of access to all of their 
trading platforms. 
</P>
<P>
	In a joint statement, chiefs from the Amsterdam, Brussels,  
Frankfurt, London, Madrid, Milan, Paris and Zurich exchanges said 
the system will ``for the first time create across Europe common 
access for each exchange's customers to the alliance markets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It will be done by linking their computer systems through a  
common interface. 
</P>
<P>
	The officials, meeting in Brussels, said the system should be up  
and running by November 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Initially, the exchanges had considered merging into a single,  
unified stock market based in one European city. The new system 
will bring them closer, but through technological means. 
</P>
<P>
	George Moeller, head of the Amsterdam Exchange, said the idea of  
a single stock exchange to replace the eight exchanges is still 
``down the road.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It may be something that will be achieved if future conditions  
merit it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the new model is expected to simplify transaction  
procedures and attract new capital flows. 
</P>
<P>
	Moeller suggested the single entry point would work mainly for  
``blue chips,'' big companies such as Shell and Unilever. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bourses also agreed to harmonize their trading rules as much  
as possible as well as the schedule of trading hours and holidays. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
