<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 10:21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Members Issue Iraq Statement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The five permanent members of the U.N.  
Security Council have failed to bridge their differences on a new 
policy toward Iraq but were finishing up a joint statement today 
pledging to keep working to reach an agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	The statement by the United States, Britain, France, China and  
Russia also will reaffirm that Iraq must live up to obligations 
including the elimination of its weapons of mass destruction before 
sanctions are lifted. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a step forward,'' said China's deputy U.N. ambassador  
Shen Guofang, whose country is coordinating the statement. 
</P>
<P>
	U.N. ambassadors from the five veto-wielding countries have been  
meeting for months to try to develop a new U.N. Iraq policy that 
would lead to the resumption of inspection of Iraq's weapons 
programs. The diplomatic effort was stepped up this month, with 
senior diplomats meeting in London last week and in New York twice 
this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Iraq was to be on the agenda at a lunch today for foreign  
ministers of the five nations hosted by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi 
Annan. Chinese and U.S. diplomats said the statement would be 
issued this afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a very brief statement and in very general terms,'' Shen  
told The Associated Press. ``We tried very hard to narrow our 
differences, but finally they're still there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. deputy ambassador Peter Burleigh said ``the meetings have  
been steps forward, but there's still a distance to go before there 
can be agreement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The United States has been pressing for a resumption of weapons  
inspections in Iraq but has run into tough Russian resistance in 
reaching agreement on a resolution. France and China are holding 
out as well. 
</P>
<P>
	U.N. weapons inspectors pulled out of Iraq in mid-December  
shortly before the United States and Britain launched airstrikes 
against Iraq for its failure to cooperate with the inspections. 
</P>
<P>
	All five permanent council members agree on the need to resume  
weapons monitoring in Iraq, and to improve living conditions for 
the 22 million Iraqis living under U.N. sanctions -- but exactly 
what Baghdad must do before the council will loosen sanctions, and 
how far those restrictions should be eased, remains in dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	China, France and Russia, Iraq's closest allies on the Security  
Council, have tabled a draft resolution that would suspend all 
sanctions if Iraq cooperates with a new commission that would 
monitor its banned weapons programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Britain and the Netherlands have tabled a rival resolution,  
which the United States supports. It would suspend only the oil 
embargo on Iraq if Baghdad answers key remaining questions about 
its weapons programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf repeated  
Wednesday that his country wouldn't consider any plan that didn't 
include the total lifting of sanctions. 
</P>
<P>
	``There will be no progress except by lifting sanctions,''  
al-Sahhaf said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
