<DOCNO> APW19990923.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 13:50:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Head Says Relief for Poor Near </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers and the  
head of the International Monetary Fund both expressed optimism 
Thursday that agreement will soon be reached on how to finance 
greatly expanded debt relief for the world's poorest countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Michel Camdessus, the IMF managing director, said finance  
officials were ``within striking distance'' of a deal. One of the 
key elements of the revamped proposal is the sale of 14 million 
ounces of the IMF's gold reserves to IMF member countries, rather 
than on the open market. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale will pay for the IMF's contribution to a program  
intended to forgive $90 billion in debt held by the world's 41 
poorest nations. 
</P>
<P>
	Summers said the administration this week asked Congress for  
nearly $1 billion to finance a larger U.S. contribution to debt 
relief, hoping that will serve as a catalyst for increased 
contributions from other wealthy countries and the international 
lending agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	He told reporters at the Treasury of ``a unique opportunity, at  
the dawn of a new millennium,'' to focus on the unsolved moral 
problem of dealing with the crushing debt burdens carried by the 
world's poorest nations. 
</P>
<P>
	In previewing the upcoming meetings of the 182-nation IMF and  
its sister lending organization, the World Bank, Summers said the 
United States would proposal strengthening the IMF's ability to 
guard against misuse of its loans -- one of the allegations made 
against Russia in a widening investigation of money laundering. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the U.S. proposals, which the IMF's governing board would  
have to approve, the IMF would be directed to order independent 
audits of central banks in countries suspected of misusing loans. 
</P>
<P>
	The IMF also would get greater leeway to penalize borrowing  
countries caught lying to the agency about domestic economic 
conditions. The IMF also could impose penalties for abuse even 
after a country has stopped borrowing from the agency. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration's package comes in the wake of renewed  
criticism by Republicans in Congress that the IMF's approach to 
handling Russia, strongly supported by President Clinton, has 
failed. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the IMF meetings came amid extreme turmoil in global  
financial markets, following the August 1998 collapse of the 
Russian ruble and the near failure of a large U.S. hedge fund. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years of turbulence forced the IMF to assemble more than  
$100 billion in bailout packages for crisis countries. Now, though, 
economic prospects are looking up, with hardhit Asian nations 
beginning to pull out of steep recessions. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the good news, Camdessus said, ``There is no room for  
complacency. This is a time for pushing ahead with structural 
changes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before the IMF and World Bank meetings, finance ministers and  
central bank presidents of the world's seven largest economies -- 
the United States, Japan, Germany, France, Britain, Italy and 
Canada -- are gathering Saturday. Their hosts are Summers and 
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial markets believe the G-7 may discuss a plan to jointly  
intervene in currency markets to buy dollars to support the U.S. 
currency, which has dropped sharply in value recently against the 
Japanese yen. 
</P>
<P>
	But despite repeated attempts, Summers would not discuss what  
the G-7's joint statement might say about cooperation on currency 
matters. He repeated the administration's view that a strong dollar 
is in the best interests of the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The IMF's complex financing arrangement for debt relief would  
involve revaluation of 14 million ounces of its huge gold reserves 
from $47 per ounce, the current value on the IMF's books, to world 
market prices, now more than $250. The extra money would be 
invested; the proceeds would finance the IMF's debt relief 
contribution. 
</P>
<P>
	Camdessus said the IMF's own review had found no basis for  
accusations that IMF loans had been used. He called those charges 
``totally unjustified.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He indicated the IMF is going forward with preparations to  
extend the next installment of $4.5 billion in loans to Russia this 
year because Russia now is exceeding the IMF's economic 
requirements. 
</P>
<P>
	Camdessus was more critical of another big borrower, Indonesia.  
The IMF program with that country will remain suspended until the 
situation in East Timor stabilizes and the Indonesian government 
produces a report answering allegations that Bank Bali improperly 
transferred around $70 million from the bank to a private company 
controlled by a senior official in the ruling Golkar Party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
