<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Possible Help for Muscle Diseases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Bone marrow transplants could restore strength to  
patients with muscular dystrophy and other muscle-wasting diseases, 
researchers said. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers at Children's Hospital who infused muscular  
dystrophy-weakened mice with bone marrow cells taken from healthy 
mice found that the cells generated healthy muscle cells. 
</P>
<P>
	Those healthy cells then traveled through the blood stream and  
to some extent restored the mice's ravaged skeletal muscles, 
according to lead researchers Richard Mulligan and Louis Kunkel of 
Children's Hospital and Harvard Medical School. 
</P>
<P>
	The findings are important because adults may have a reservoir  
of these cells in their bodies that have the potential to generate 
other types of cells, said Emanuela Gussoni, a biologist in 
Kunkel's lab and lead author of the paper in Thursday's issue of 
the journal Nature. 
</P>
<P>
	In a related experiment, Gussoni and her colleagues isolated  
muscle stem cells from mice and demonstrated they could generate 
adult muscle cells as well as bone marrow cells. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Leon Charash, chairman of the medical advisory committee of  
the Muscular Dystrophy Association, said the findings were 
``exciting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The work may eventually lead to an unanticipated treatment  
approach for all the muscles ravaged by neuromuscular disease,'' he 
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990923.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 15:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Wants in on E-Commerce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Microsoft Corp., hoping to snare a bigger share  
of the growing Internet commerce market, announced a series of 
initiatives Thursday aimed at allowing consumers easier ways to 
surf and shop and giving businesses new software tools to sell 
their products. 
</P>
<P>
	Included was a new shopping service through Microsoft's msn.com  
Web site that lets consumers compare prices for everything from 
electronics to clothing to furniture and buy them on the spot. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft also said that on Sept. 30 it will launch bCentral, an  
Internet gateway site to help small businesses build Web sites and 
market to new customers. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft wants to make the Web ``an indispensable part of life  
and is doing that with software,'' said Richard Belluzzo, hired 
less than three weeks ago to help the company better challenge 
rival Web sites Yahoo! and America Online. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft officials also talked about their plans for something  
they called the ``Everyday Web,'' technology that allows consumers 
and businesses to use Internet services such as browsing, shopping 
and e-mail without a personal computer. The company has been 
building partnerships with wireless carriers to access the Web 
through handheld portable computers such as the Palm, cellular 
phones and its WebTV service. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have the experience, software and services to do things  
that other people aren't doing,'' said Brad Chase of Microsoft's 
Consumer and Commerce Group. ``What we're talking about with the 
Everyday Web is making the Web as ubiquitous as the phone, but a 
thousand times more useful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The company also announced Thursday that it plans an initial  
public offering for its Expedia travel reservations site, a move 
that will give investors the opportunity to focus on just one 
aspect of the company's business and bring in as much as $75 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	The Expedia stock offering is the latest in a series of  
maneuvers Microsoft has made to jump start its online ventures. 
</P>
<P>
	Just this week, Microsoft announced it would form a joint  
venture with Ford Motor Co. to allow users of Microsoft's CarPoint 
automotive service to ``build-to-order'' a car. 
</P>
<P>
	It was unclear how well the new initiatives would improve  
Microsoft's position in the competitive world of electronic 
commerce. 
</P>
<P>
	Several Microsoft rivals such as IBM and Sun Microsystems have  
already staked their own claims in selling e-commerce software, an 
attempt to grab a piece of consumers' estimated $12 billion in 
Internet purchases this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts called Microsoft's plans interesting but not  
earthshaking. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems the company that has the latest technology is the  
company that has the latest press release,'' said Peter Goldmacher 
of Merrill Lynch. ``It's a game of inches right now, and we'll see 
how AOL and others respond.'' 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
