<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Sept. 23, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Aussie Peacekeepers Come Under Sniper Fire  
</P>
<P>
	DILI, East Timor (AP) -- As hostile automatic gunfire crackled  
across the city for the first time since the force arrived in East 
Timor's devastated capital, Australian peacekeeping troops came 
under sniper fire in Dili today. Gunmen fired from nearby trees at 
a house commandeered by the Australians, Associated Press 
Television News reported. There were no immediate reports of 
casualties. Earlier, shots were fired near the sports stadium where 
refugees were seeking protection from pro-Indonesia militias. 

</P>
<P>
	Russian Police Defuse Large Bomb  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Police discovered an explosive device set to blow  
up in the basement of a 12-story apartment building in western 
Russia, the Emergency Situations Ministry said today. Police did 
not say whether there was a link between the device, found last 
Wednesday in the city of Ryazan, and four apartment bomb blasts 
that killed some 300 people in Moscow and two other Russian cities 
this month. Authorities were alerted by a resident of the building 
who claimed to have seen people hauling large sacks from a car with 
covered license plates, the ITAR-Tass news agency said. 

</P>
<P>
	NASA Seeks More Word on Mars Probe  
</P>
<P>
	PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- NASA's first interplanetary weather  
satellite hurtled closer to Mars early today as controllers 
anxiously awaited word that it had begun orbiting the red planet. 
The orbiter and its companion, the Mars Polar Lander, carry 
instruments that will try to discover the fate of water believed to 
have once formed rivers or lakes on the planet. Mission scientists 
say water is the key to determining whether life ever existed on 
Mars. The lander, which was launched separately, is due to arrive 
Dec. 3. 

</P>
<P>
	Council Members Agree on Iraq Policy  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The five permanent members of the U.N.  
Security Council have agreed on general principles on a policy 
toward Iraq, but could not forge a common stance that would lead to 
the resumption of arms inspections. An agreement would mark a 
modest step forward in the search for ways to resume U.N. 
inspections of Iraq's weapons programs after a halt of more than 
nine months. But the five council members -- the United States, 
Britain, France, Russia and China -- remain sharply divided on key 
issues. 

</P>
<P>
	Vets at Higher Risk for Hepatitis C  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Many veterans unknowingly harbor a  
liver-destroying virus, according to a new campaign encouraging 
veterans to seek testing and treatment for hepatitis C. An 
estimated 2.7 million Americans are infected with hepatitis C. 
Although it kills up to 10,000 Americans a year, it can lurk for 
decades without causing symptoms, so many people don't know they 
are infected until their liver is seriously damaged. Veterans may 
be at special risk. 

</P>
<P>
	Justice Dept. Sues Tobacco Ind. for Billions  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department sued the nation's  
tobacco industry yesterday to recover billions of dollars that 
federal health plans spent treating smoking-related illnesses. The 
civil suit, which also targets research and public relations 
institutes funded by the industry, alleges cigarette makers 
conspired to defraud and mislead the public about the dangers of 
tobacco. Attorney General Janet Reno said the cigarette companies 
gave profits a higher priority than public health. 

</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin Immune From Swiss Probe  
</P>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- The prosecutor in charge of investigating alleged  
Russian money laundering in Switzerland said yesterday that Boris 
Yeltsin will be immune from Swiss questioning as long as he remains 
president of Russia. Bertossa is overseeing the main Swiss 
investigation into allegations of Russian money-laundering, 
including supposed channels to the Bank of New York. Investigators 
have alleged that Russian businesses and individuals illegally 
relayed billions of dollars through the American bank. 

</P>
<P>
	South Africans Fighters Win Amnesty  
</P>
<P>
	JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- A panel probing apartheid-era  
abuses granted amnesty yesterday to several fighters on both sides 
of South Africa's apartheid-era struggle, including members of a 
black guerrilla group that targeted white farm families. The panel, 
called the Truth and Reconciliation Commission, has largely 
disappeared from the national dialogue since it issued a report a 
year ago after 2 1/2 years of hearings. 

</P>
<P>
