<HEADLINE> Ashland Raises Offer to Superfos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COVINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- Ashland Inc.'s bid to purchase Superfos  
won the support of the Danish company's chairman after the 
Kentucky-based company raised its offer. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashland boosted its offer 6.5 percent to 160 kroner a share, the  
equivalent of $22.63 a share. The new offer raises the total 
purchase price from $650 million to $690 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal is still contingent on Superfos' board recommending it  
to shareholders, Ashland said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashland initially offered $21 a share on Aug. 9 after a bid to  
buy the Danish company's U.S. paving assets was rejected. Ashland 
wants to merge the $700 million paving operation with its $1.44 
billion APAC paving and construction unit. 
</P>
<P>
	Aside from the paving business, Superfos owns packaging,  
chemicals and aerosols operations, some of which Ashland is 
expected to sell if it acquires Superfos. 
</P>
<P>
	The new deal was brokered by Superfos Chairman Kjeld Ranum and  
James R. Boyd, Ashland senior vice president and group operating 
officer over APAC and Arch Coal. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to APAC, Ashland owns specialty chemical and  
distribution companies, Valvoline car-care products, and large 
equity stakes in Arch Coal and Marathon Ashland Petroleum. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
