<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Athletics 9, Orioles 6, 1st game  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Miguel Tejada hit a tiebreaking homer in the  
eighth inning as the Oakland Athletics ended the Baltimore Orioles' 
13-game winning streak with a 9-6 victory Thursday in the opener of 
a doubleheader. 
</P>
<P>
	Matt Stairs, Ben Grieve and Mike Macfarlane also homered for the  
A's, who moved within 4 1/2 games of Boston in the AL wild-card race. 
Boston was to play Toronto on Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Albert Belle homered for the Orioles, whose 13-game streak was  
one short of the team record set in 1973. 
</P>
<P>
	The doubleheader was a makeup of two games washed out last week  
by Hurricane Floyd. The A's traveled from Oakland and will move on 
to Texas on Friday; the Orioles, who came from Texas, will play in 
Boston on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Tejada led off the eighth by hitting the first pitch from Gabe  
Molina (1-2) into the left-field seats to put Oakland up 7-6. Jason 
Giambi then singled in a run with his third hit of the game and 
another scored on a throwing error. 
</P>
<P>
	T.J. Mathews (9-4) worked 1 2-3 innings for Oakland and Jason  
Isringhausen worked the ninth for his seventh save. 
</P>
<P>
	Stairs and Grieve hit solo homers off Sidney Ponson in the fifth  
to give Oakland a 6-3 lead. Stairs' blast, estimated at 423 feet, 
was his 36th of the season and 100th of his career. 
</P>
<P>
	Baltimore pulled even in the bottom of the inning, taking  
advantage of two errors and a wild pitch by rookie Brett Laxton to 
score three unearned runs. 
</P>
<P>
	Laxton, recalled from Triple-A Vancouver before the game,  
allowed three earned runs and seven hits in 4 2-3 innings. 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Bordick doubled and Belle hit his 36th homer to give  
Baltimore a 2-0 lead in the first inning. Macfarlane then put the 
A's in front with a three-run shot in the second. 
</P>
<P>
	After Oakland loaded the bases with no outs in the third, John  
Jaha drove in a run with a grounder before Ponson struck out Grieve 
and Tejada. Bordick hit a sacrifice fly in the Orioles' half to 
make it 4-3. 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* Macfarlane's homer was his third in 213 at-bats this  
season. ... Orioles pitchers struck out a season-high 15. ... 
Ponson struck out eight but gave up three home runs. He has allowed 
a team-high 34 homers, including at least one in 20 of 26 starts. 
... Stairs became the 24th player in the eight-year history of 
Camden Yards to hit a ball onto Eutaw Street beyond the right-field 
scoreboard. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
