<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 10:50:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Blues Owner Laurie Buys Grizzlies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- The Vancouver Grizzlies, who  
entered the NBA four years ago when the league expanded into 
Canada, will be sold to billionaire Bill Laurie, owner of the NHL's 
St. Louis Blues. 
</P>
<P>
	Two league sources, speaking on the condition they not be  
identified, told The Associated Press that an agreement in 
principle has been reached to sell the team. 
</P>
<P>
	The league's Board of Governors still must approve the sale,  
which could conceivably result in the team being relocated to St. 
Louis for the 2000-01 season. The sale price was not immediately 
known. 
</P>
<P>
	The owners of the Grizzlies, Vancouver Canucks and the GM Place  
arena called a news conference for 3:30 p.m. EDT today to announce 
the sale. It comes the same day that commissioner David Stern 
arrived in town for the NBA's league meetings. 
</P>
<P>
	The Canadian Press also reported that the Grizzlies would be  
sold, citing an unidentifed source connected with the owners. 
</P>
<P>
	Laurie, a former Memphis State point guard, and his wife, Nancy,  
an heir to the Wal-Mart fortune, recently bought the NHL's Blues 
and the Kiel Center in St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	Laurie, an avid basketball fan, certainly has the financial  
resources. He and his wife agreed in April to buy the Colorado 
Avalanche of the NHL, the Denver Nuggets of the NBA and Denver's 
new Pepsi Center for $400 million US. But they lost out when a 
rival group, given a second chance to bid, offered $461 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Speculation has swirled about the future of the Grizzlies  
franchise ever since Seattle-based owner John McCaw said last month 
he was willing to sell part or all of his Orca Bay sports empire. 
</P>
<P>
	St. Louis has not had an NBA team since the Hawks left in 1968,  
but Laurie won't be able to move the Grizzlies for at least one 
season. Under NBA rules, an expansion franchise has to stay five 
years in the new city. 
</P>
<P>
	If Laurie wants to move the team for the 2000-01 season, he must  
apply to the NBA by March 1. 
</P>
<P>
	The Grizzlies have met with limited success since joining the  
NBA, never winning more than 19 games. Vancouver was 8-42 in the 
lockout-shortened 1999 season, the worst record in the 29-team 
league. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, a spokesman for Laurie confirmed he was interested  
in the Grizzlies. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's logical to assume that the Lauries would look at the  
Grizzlies as they have looked at other NBA properties,'' said Peter 
Webb, chief spokesman for Laurie's Paige Sports Entertainment. 
``It's no secret they have looked to acquire an NBA team.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
