<DOCNO> APW19990923.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 08:00:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Norway, Sweden To Merge Phone Cos. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OSLO, Norway (AP) -- Sweden and Norway reached final agreement  
today to merge their state telephone companies after repeated 
disputes had threatened the planned combination. 
</P>
<P>
	The combination of Sweden's Telia and Norway's Telenor would  
create a company worth about $18.6 billion and employing about 
51,000 people. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is with great pleasure that we can say the merger of  
Telenor and Telia will be completed in keeping with the original 
agreement,'' the Norwegian Minister of Transport and 
Communications, Dag Jostein Fjaervoll, said in a news release. 
</P>
<P>
	Company officials say the goal is to become the leading  
telecommunications company in Europe. They also say the merged 
company will be better positioned to face competition once 
telecommunications in both countries are deregulated. 
</P>
<P>
	Merger plans were announced in January. The deal includes  
partial privatization of the state-owned companies. But a final 
agreement was reportedly delayed in part due to Swedish opposition 
to Telenor leader Tormod Hermansen as chief executive of the merged 
concern. 
</P>
<P>
	The countries were under pressure to send a final contract to  
the European Union for approval by a Friday deadline after having 
asked Brussels for extra time last week. The companies now promise 
to meet EU conditions, including the sale of their cable television 
divisions. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Swedish and Norwegian owners have agreed to follow the  
terms of the agreement that was reached earlier this year,'' said 
Fjaervoll. ``Recently there have been tough negotiations, but that 
is natural in such a comprehensive and complex case.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As the agreement was announced, Telia chairman Jan Stenberg  
withdrew as proposed chairman for the new company, a Swedish 
Ministry of Trade and Industry news release stated. 
</P>
<P>
	Stenberg is head of Scandinavian Airlines System. He'll be  
replaced as Telia-Telenor's chairman by Telia's chief officer 
Jan-Aake Kark. 
</P>
<P>
	``Personally I feel that we have reached a good agreement,''  
Swedish Trade and Industry Minister Bjoern Rosengren said in a 
statement. ``It is good for Sweden and it's good for the Swedish 
tax payers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under the terms of the January deal, the Swedish government  
would initially hold 60 percent in the new company and the 
Norwegian government, 40 percent. Sometime after 2000, those stakes 
will be reduced to 33 percent as the remaining third is sold to 
investors. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990923.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 22:00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton To Fight Money-Laundering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As U.S. investigators painstakingly unravel  
the case, government officials are conceding they have more 
questions than answers in the inquiry into allegations of a huge 
money-laundering scheme involving Russians and the Bank of New 
York. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration's announcement Thursday of a new  
national strategy to fight money laundering received extra 
attention in light of the federal investigation of the Bank of New 
York case. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian businesses and individuals -- including organized crime  
groups -- are suspected of illegally channeling as much as $10 
billion through the bank, the nation's 15th-largest and said to be 
its oldest. No one has been charged in the related investigations 
by law enforcement authorities in the United States, Britain, 
Russia and other countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't know whether it involved illicit money or not. ... We  
don't know whether this is money laundering, capital flight or 
something else,'' Deputy Treasury Secretary Stuart Eizenstat told 
reporters who questioned him about the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the capital flight scenario, some of the money funneled  
through the Bank of New York could have come from thousands of 
small- to medium-sized Russian businesses that spirited funds 
through offshore companies to avoid enormous taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	The practice is illegal but very widespread in Russia, where  
taxes are punitive, rules are ever-changing and tax police say as 
many as 99 percent of businesses skirt some taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	On Capitol Hill Thursday, Deputy Secretary of State Strobe  
Talbott was quizzed on the Bank of New York case by members of the 
Senate Foreign Relations Committee. He told the panel: ``We are all 
seeking to establish the facts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no question that Russia has suffered, generally, from  
the problem of capital flight,'' testified Talbott, who had just 
returned from a mission to Moscow. ``Much of it goes, literally, 
into mattresses, because Russians don't trust banks. And much of it 
has fled the country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``If and when either our intelligence or law enforcement  
community comes into possession of specific information, we'll deal 
with the facts as they emerge,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration's new anti-money-laundering strategy is a  
package of proposed laws and rules aimed at stanching the flow of 
billions of criminal dollars, largely drug-trafficking profits, 
through the U.S. financial system. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials stressed that the long-awaited strategy, made public a  
few weeks after allegations of money-laundering through the Bank of 
New York came to light, has a far broader scope than Russia or any 
one country. 
</P>
<P>
	``Money laundering is a very sophisticated crime and we must be  
equally sophisticated,'' Attorney General Janet Reno said at a news 
conference. 
</P>
<P>
	With her was Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers, who called the  
package ``an essential front in the war on narcotics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The strategy seeks to bolster international cooperation in  
investigating money laundering and to strengthen U.S. enforcement 
through tighter regulation of banks and other financial 
institutions. Under the plan: 
</P>
<P>
	--Storefront check cashiers, brokerage firms and casinos would be  
required to notify authorities of suspicious activities the way 
banks must do. 
</P>
<P>
	--The government would designate new high-intensity  
money-laundering zones, industries and financial institutions, and 
``action teams'' of law enforcement authorities and regulators 
would be formed to concentrate on those areas. 
</P>
<P>
	--Proposed legislation would add new international crimes, such  
as corruption and illegal arms dealing, to the activities subject 
to U.S. prosecution under money-laundering laws. 
</P>
<P>
	Tax evasion, which may have played a major role in the Bank of  
New York case, is not included. 
</P>
<P>
	Key Republican lawmakers have endorsed the proposals. Congress  
directed the Treasury and Justice departments to submit the new 
strategy early this year, before the case involving Russians and 
the Bank of New York broke. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990923.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 13:10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CDC: State Health Depts. Y2K Ready </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- State health departments are ready for the  
millennium bug, the federal government reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention reported that a  
survey conducted from June through August identified no 
``significant'' vulnerabilities to the Y2K problem in state health 
department systems. 
</P>
<P>
	Some experts fear the arrival of the year 2000 could result in  
shutdowns or other malfunctions by causing some older computers to 
think it is 1900. 
</P>
<P>
	The CDC survey looked at nine areas, including medical and lab  
equipment with date-sensitive computer chips and critical 
administrative services such as admissions and access to records. 
The survey found that 90 percent of the systems still operated when 
the date changed over. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990923.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 14:20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Blue Jays' Delgado Has Broken Leg </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The Toronto Blue Jays have lost Carlos Delgado for  
the remainder of the season after the star first baseman fractured 
his right leg. 
</P>
<P>
	Delgado, 27, was injured in Wednesday night's 14-9 win over the  
Boston Red Sox when he fouled a ball off his right leg in the 
eighth inning. 
</P>
<P>
	He had 44 home runs and 134 RBIs this season and batted .272.  
</P>
<P>
	Delgado had not missed a game all season, playing in all 152 for  
the Blue Jays. He had played in 235 straight games since 1998, the 
third-longest streak in team history. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
