<DOCNO> APW19990923.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 08:43:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Russia Buries Raisa Gorbachev </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Mikhail Gorbachev bent slowly over his wife  
Raisa's coffin and gave her a last kiss on the forehead today 
before burying the woman whose vibrant personality and high style 
redefined the role of first lady of the Soviet Union. 
</P>
<P>
	The emotional moment in Moscow's elite Novodevichy Cemetery  
climaxed a difficult two months for the former Soviet president, 
who sat at his wife's bedside in a German hospital while she 
battled leukemia. She died Monday at age 67. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gorbachev's body was carried in an open coffin on the  
shoulders of six pallbearers down a walkway strewn with red roses 
in the cemetery, where dense trees block out the tumult of central 
Moscow. 
</P>
<P>
	Her forehead was wrapped in a traditional Russian Orthodox  
funeral scarf. Priests swinging censers of incense chanted a burial 
service as dignitaries including former German Chancellor Helmut 
Kohl and President Boris Yeltsin's wife, Naina, looked on. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were a real pair. She was a part of him, almost always at  
his side,'' said Kohl, who became close to Gorbachev during talks 
on the Soviet Union aiding German reunification. ``Much of what he 
achieved is simply unimaginable without his wife.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier today, a stream of prominent Russians, ambassadors and  
other foreign guests brought wreaths, bouquets and words of 
condolence to Gorbachev and other family members as they sat with 
the coffin in the Russian Cultural Foundation, which Mrs. Gorbachev 
founded. 
</P>
<P>
	A small delegation of students from the philosophy department at  
Moscow State University, where Mrs. Gorbachev used to teach, 
brought a large wreath of white roses and fir fronds. 
</P>
<P>
	Gorbachev, his daughter and two granddaughters walked behind the  
open coffin as it was carried out of the foundation to a black 
hearse for the journey to Novodevichy. 
</P>
<P>
	A large picture of Mrs. Gorbachev and a wreath from Yeltsin were  
carried in front of the coffin. A bouquet of white roses lay in the 
coffin at her feet. 
</P>
<P>
	A drawn-looking Gorbachev and his family stood watching as the  
coffin was covered and placed inside the hearse. A stream of 
limousines and buses then conveyed the mourners to the cemetery, 
where a private service preceded the burial. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of ordinary Russians strained behind police barricades  
in hopes of catching a glimpse of the funeral procession. 
</P>
<P>
	At Novodevichy, the mourners attended a private service in a  
chapel on the grounds of the convent adjacent to the cemetery. Nine 
bells rang in descending minor intervals as the service concluded. 
</P>
<P>
	While Mrs. Gorbachev was deeply admired in the West, many  
Russians disliked her for her elegant clothes, polished manner and 
prominent public role. 
</P>
<P>
	But sentiment changed when she was hospitalized in a German  
clinic on July 25 with a rare form of leukemia. She and her husband 
were inundated with letters offering support, advice and money. 
</P>
<P>
	After Mrs. Gorbachev died from the blood disease on Monday, her  
husband returned home with several boxes full of the letters. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was always enchanted by Raisa Maximovna's elegance, her  
beauty. She was a woman who could present herself in the West. She 
was respected there as an equal in government circles,'' said 
Lyubov Saldatkina, a retired auto worker who stood near the 
cultural foundation. 
</P>
<P>
	World leaders including President Clinton, French President  
Jacques Chirac and German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder sent 
condolences to the Gorbachev family. 
</P>
<P>
	The Novodevichy cemetery is Russia's most historic burial place,  
and many famous Russians -- including former Soviet leader Nikita 
Khrushchev, poet Vladimir Mayakovsky and writer Anton Chekhov -- are 
interred there. 
</P>
<P>
	Born Raisa Maximovna Titarenko in 1932, Mrs. Gorbachev is  
survived by her husband, daughter Irina Virganskaya, two 
granddaughters -- Ksenia and Anastasia -- and a younger sister, 
Ludmila Titarenko. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990923.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 08:43:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Russia Buries Raisa Gorbachev </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Mikhail Gorbachev bent slowly over his wife  
Raisa's coffin and gave her a last kiss on the forehead today 
before burying the woman whose vibrant personality and high style 
redefined the role of first lady of the Soviet Union. 
</P>
<P>
	The emotional moment in Moscow's elite Novodevichy Cemetery  
climaxed a difficult two months for the former Soviet president, 
who sat at his wife's bedside in a German hospital while she 
battled leukemia. She died Monday at age 67. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gorbachev's body was carried in an open coffin on the  
shoulders of six pallbearers down a walkway strewn with red roses 
in the cemetery, where dense trees block out the tumult of central 
Moscow. 
</P>
<P>
	Her forehead was wrapped in a traditional Russian Orthodox  
funeral scarf. Priests swinging censers of incense chanted a burial 
service as dignitaries including former German Chancellor Helmut 
Kohl and President Boris Yeltsin's wife, Naina, looked on. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were a real pair. She was a part of him, almost always at  
his side,'' said Kohl, who became close to Gorbachev during talks 
on the Soviet Union aiding German reunification. ``Much of what he 
achieved is simply unimaginable without his wife.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier today, a stream of prominent Russians, ambassadors and  
other foreign guests brought wreaths, bouquets and words of 
condolence to Gorbachev and other family members as they sat with 
the coffin in the Russian Cultural Foundation, which Mrs. Gorbachev 
founded. 
</P>
<P>
	A small delegation of students from the philosophy department at  
Moscow State University, where Mrs. Gorbachev used to teach, 
brought a large wreath of white roses and fir fronds. 
</P>
<P>
	Gorbachev, his daughter and two granddaughters walked behind the  
open coffin as it was carried out of the foundation to a black 
hearse for the journey to Novodevichy. 
</P>
<P>
	A large picture of Mrs. Gorbachev and a wreath from Yeltsin were  
carried in front of the coffin. A bouquet of white roses lay in the 
coffin at her feet. 
</P>
<P>
	A drawn-looking Gorbachev and his family stood watching as the  
coffin was covered and placed inside the hearse. A stream of 
limousines and buses then conveyed the mourners to the cemetery, 
where a private service preceded the burial. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of ordinary Russians strained behind police barricades  
in hopes of catching a glimpse of the funeral procession. 
</P>
<P>
	At Novodevichy, the mourners attended a private service in a  
chapel on the grounds of the convent adjacent to the cemetery. Nine 
bells rang in descending minor intervals as the service concluded. 
</P>
<P>
	While Mrs. Gorbachev was deeply admired in the West, many  
Russians disliked her for her elegant clothes, polished manner and 
prominent public role. 
</P>
<P>
	But sentiment changed when she was hospitalized in a German  
clinic on July 25 with a rare form of leukemia. She and her husband 
were inundated with letters offering support, advice and money. 
</P>
<P>
	After Mrs. Gorbachev died from the blood disease on Monday, her  
husband returned home with several boxes full of the letters. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was always enchanted by Raisa Maximovna's elegance, her  
beauty. She was a woman who could present herself in the West. She 
was respected there as an equal in government circles,'' said 
Lyubov Saldatkina, a retired auto worker who stood near the 
cultural foundation. 
</P>
<P>
	World leaders including President Clinton, French President  
Jacques Chirac and German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder sent 
condolences to the Gorbachev family. 
</P>
<P>
	The Novodevichy cemetery is Russia's most historic burial place,  
and many famous Russians -- including former Soviet leader Nikita 
Khrushchev, poet Vladimir Mayakovsky and writer Anton Chekhov -- are 
interred there. 
</P>
<P>
	Born Raisa Maximovna Titarenko in 1932, Mrs. Gorbachev is  
survived by her husband, daughter Irina Virganskaya, two 
granddaughters -- Ksenia and Anastasia -- and a younger sister, 
Ludmila Titarenko. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
