<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Good Weather Sinks Soybeans / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean futures sank Thursday on the Chicago  
Board of Trade in response to excellent harvest conditions, while 
grain futures were mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	Ideal harvest weather throughout the soybean belt sent soybean  
prices down by 1 1/2 percent to its lowest level this month. Investors 
said the trend was likely to continue Friday, with the harvest 
expected to accelerate this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Expectations that the corn harvest also will experience an  
active weekend also sent futures for that commodity lower, closing 
near eight-week lows. The fall harvest is expected to move west of 
the Mississippi River this weekend, with forecasts for clear 
weather throughout the Midwest boding well for field work. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat prices rallied on late commercial buying.  
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery rose 3 1/2 cents to $2.73 1/4 a bushel;  
December corn fell 2 cents to $2.08 1/4 cents a bushel; December oats 
rose 1/2 cent to $1.13 1/4 a bushel; November soybeans fell 7 1/4 cents to 
$4.78 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef futures closed slightly higher on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange, while pork futures were mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	October live cattle rose .02 cent to 66.37 cents a pound;  
October feeder cattle rose .08 cent to 79.40 cents a pound; October 
lean hogs rose .55 cent to 46.10 cents a pound; February frozen 
pork bellies fell .23 cent to 59.42 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
