<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 17:20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gert Weakens to Tropical Storm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. JOHN'S, Newfoundland (AP) -- A powerful storm hit parts of  
eastern Canada with strong winds and rain Thursday, sinking five 
boats and damaging 45 others, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tropical Storm Gert was downgraded from a hurricane earlier  
Thursday before it hit Canada's eastern coast with gale-force 
winds. The boats were sunk and damaged in Newfoundland ports. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was like something you watch in a horror movie,'' said  
Albert Young, who watched a giant wave knock three men off the 
wharf at St. Bride's, a tiny community on Newfoundland's Avalon 
Peninsula. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the men was injured, said harbormaster Aloysius McGrath,  
whose small office was leveled by water. 
</P>
<P>
	As the storm approached on Wednesday, some offshore oil rigs had  
shut down, and evacuated nonessential staff to land. 
</P>
<P>
	Gert's outer bands were dropping light to moderately heavy  
amounts of rain from Maine into eastern New Hampshire and 
Massachusetts, and storm warnings remained in effect for coastal 
Newfoundland. 
</P>
<P>
	The storm was moving northeast at about 30 mph, and was expected  
to die out as it headed toward the north Atlantic, the U.S. 
National Hurricane Center in Miami said. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in the week, the hurricane brushed Bermuda with the  
outer edge of winds up to 110 mph, whipping up waves that smashed 
seaside cottages and washed away prime stretches of beach. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
