<DOCNO> APW19990923.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 16:11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Missouri Seeks Upset of Nebraska </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBIA, Mo. (AP) -- For Missouri, it's another crack at a  
breakthrough game. For Nebraska, it's a chance to prove its No. 6 
ranking isn't based simply on reputation. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday night, Missouri (2-0) will be trying to end two  
lengthy losing streaks. The Tigers have lost 20 straight to the 
Cornhuskers (3-0), with the last victory in 1978. They've also 
dropped 35 straight to teams ranked in the Top 10, with the last 
victory in 1981. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a long time,'' coach Larry Smith said. ``It's time,  
right?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith has 12 victories over Top 10 teams during his career, with  
the last in 1992. He's 0-13 at Missouri, but has come close the 
past three games, losing by six points to No. 1 Kansas State, by 
three to No. 6 Texas A&AMP;M and by seven to Nebraska last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Missouri is a 17 1/2-point underdog heading into the Big  
12 conference opener, this game could be a lot closer. Nebraska has 
struggled offensively, and managed only 185 yards in a 20-13 
victory over Southern Mississippi last week. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cornhuskers have endured the departure of tailback DeAngelo  
Evans and a quarterback shuffle. Bobby Newcombe has been moved to 
wingback and Eric Crouch is the starter, although his numbers 
haven't been impressive. 
</P>
<P>
	Crouch was 6-for-10 for 66 yards and two interceptions last  
week. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have something to prove,'' Crouch said. ``I think it's about  
time we have a huge offensive day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then there's the recent history. Last year's game, won by the  
Cornhuskers 20-13 at Lincoln, Neb., came down to the final play. 
And in 1997, Nebraska needed freshman Matt Davison's miracle catch 
of a ball tipped first by a defender and then kicked in the air by 
teammate Shevin Wiggins, to force overtime and preserve a national 
championship season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I remember driving to the stadium two years ago and seeing how  
their fans were fired up,'' Davison said. ``They thought they could 
beat us. They gave it a good shot and almost got the job done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The game has been sold out for weeks, and a hostile reception is  
expected. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had to leave our helmets on two years ago because we were  
getting things thrown at us,'' Davison said. ``But that's what 
makes it all fun, I think.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Missouri again will alternate sophomore Jim Dougherty and  
redshirt freshman Kirk Farmer at quarterback. They have similar 
numbers thus far, with Dougherty 15-for-26 for 142 yards with one 
touchdown and an interception, and Farmer 15-for-27 for 177 yards, 
five touchdowns and two interceptions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Both are very talented players,'' Solich said. ``Both move  
very well -- not your typical quarterbacks that don't get around in 
the pocket.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990923.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 16:11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
