<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 17:20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NHL Denies Collusion on Salaries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- While a few teams continue to take hard stands  
with unsigned players, NHL president Gary Bettman denied there is 
an understanding among owners to hold the line on player salaries. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not colluding, we don't collude,'' Bettman said  
Thursday before attending a meeting of the league general managers 
at the Air Canada Centre. ``Our clubs will continue to act 
individually and make whatever judgments they think is correct.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Ottawa Senators are refusing to renegotiate holdout Alexei  
Yashin's contract, the Toronto Maple Leafs are continuing 
negotiations with no-shows Bryan Berard and Dimitri Yushkevich, and 
the Boston Bruins, in an unprecedented move, let forward Dmitri 
Khristich become a free agent rather than pay the $2.8 million an 
arbitrator set as his salary. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whenever you have individual negotiations in this day and age  
in professional sports there are going to be skirmishes because the 
players want as much money as possible,'' Bettman said. ``And it's 
their right and prerogative to want as much money as possible and 
the owners have the right to negotiate as hard as they need to make 
economic sense of their teams.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While the collective bargaining agreement between the NHL and  
the players' association doesn't expire until after the 2003-04 
season, it has come under scrutiny because of the wrangling over 
the NHL's participation in the 2002 Winter Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	The players want a longer break than two weeks, but the NHL  
wants them back to work sooner to prevent the season from going too 
long. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not something we intend to change,'' Bettman said. ``Many  
people are concerned about how late the season goes and we're not 
looking to put ourselves in a situation where it goes so late -- 
that in June everybody forgets that we went to the Olympics in 
February.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The NHL also is creating a ``collective bargaining agreement ''  
fund of $300 million at $10 million per team to prepare for 
possible labor problems in four years. 
</P>
<P>
	``If there is disharmony in 2004, you have to be as strong as  
possible,'' Bettman said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990923.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 13:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dole Tries Closing Gap With Bush </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	IOWA CITY, Iowa (AP) -- Elizabeth Dole strode into the crowded  
college ballroom, and nodded approvingly at the giant banner 
declaring simply: ``It's time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She drew cheers from her mainly young, female audience as she  
sketched out her education proposals and praised the college 
students ``who have spent literally hundreds of hours supporting my 
campaign.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm really on the move these days,'' Dole declared.  
</P>
<P>
	After a rocky start last spring, Dole saw new summertime life  
breathed into her campaign with a solid showing in an Iowa straw 
poll last month. Some analysts, however, are questioning how well 
she's capitalized on that break. 
</P>
<P>
	``If she doesn't do it soon, the momentum will fade and her  
ability to do so will diminish,'' said Ed Gillespie, a Republican 
strategist not aligned with a presidential campaign. ``She's going 
to lose the chance to strike while the iron is hot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There have been some ups and downs in Dole's bid for the  
Republican presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Entering the race she was a hot commodity, a high-powered  
political name coupled with decades of experience on the 
presidential campaign trail. Not to mention the notion of luring 
women voters to the GOP, where a gender gap has cost the party 
dearly. 
</P>
<P>
	But early troubles dogged the campaign, including a reluctance  
to chart out clear differences with rivals and set a distinct 
campaign agenda. She also fell victim to the fund-raising draw of 
Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who dried up money for other candidates 
with a mammoth financial operation. 
</P>
<P>
	While many began to count her out, Dole got a lift last month  
when she finished third in the straw poll, a showing backers said 
certified her standing as a top-tier candidate. Critics say not 
much has happened since. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been one of the strangest top-tier political campaigns  
I've ever observed,'' said University of Virginia political 
scientist Larry Sabato. ``It seems to me that her objective is more 
to stay alive than make progress.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While most Americans aren't focused on the presidential  
election, activists are and Iowa's leadoff precinct caucuses are 
barely four months away. The nomination fight in both parties is 
likely to be settled within six weeks of that test, meaning it's 
coming close to crunch time for candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	While many are critical of Dole's campaign, there are others who  
say she has scored some significant milestones. Republican 
strategist Scott Reed noted that she's assembled the financial 
resources to stay in the mix deep into the primary season, and also 
has put into place a potent organizational network. 
</P>
<P>
	``That guarantees she'll be a serious player through the initial  
tests,'' said Reed. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said there is another factor that sets Dole apart from  
the other candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	``She is the only Republican other than George W. Bush who  
consistently beats Al Gore in the polls,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, polls have not shown her closing the gap with Bush.  
</P>
<P>
	This week, she launched a series of policy speeches designed to  
define her campaign. An education speech Wednesday in Melrose, 
Mass., came a week after Bush covered many the same issues in his 
own policy speech. 
</P>
<P>
	Dole has said she needs time to complete the enormous task of  
assembling a presidential campaign, and there's some sympathy for 
that view. There's also some impatience. 
</P>
<P>
	She has occasionally been reluctant to step forward on major  
issues, and a couple of campaign aides have moved on in 
frustration. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a small window of opportunity here for her to press  
the front-runner,'' said Gillespie. ``I can understand why she 
waited until after Labor Day, but I don't think she can wait until 
Halloween.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990923.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 10:40:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Milestone Awaiting Buckeyes' Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- If Ohio State beats Cincinnati on  
Saturday, don't count on coach John Cooper blowing out 100 candles 
on a cake at midfield. 
</P>
<P>
	With a 99-34-4 record in 12 years with the Buckeyes, Cooper  
doesn't get misty when he thinks about what others call a 
milestone. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm proud and happy that I've lasted that long, hopefully, to  
win 100 games,'' he said. ``But I'm not here counting, let me put 
it that way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In his frequently up and occasionally down tenure with the  
Buckeyes, the native Tennessean has come close to winning a couple 
of national championships -- and has also come closer to being fired 
at least that many times. 
</P>
<P>
	Cooper has taken Buckeyes teams to the No. 2 spot in the final  
polls in two of the last three years, yet still hasn't captured the 
hearts of many of the fans. After the Buckeyes lost to Miami 23-12 
in the Kickoff Classic, those naysayers repeated a common refrain: 
``He can't win the big one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 62-year-old Iowa State graduate has not been forgiven for  
his 2-8-1 record against archrival Michigan and a 2-8 bowl record 
with the Buckeyes. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet his team swept both of those games last year -- the first  
time that's happened since he's been in Columbus -- and he has made 
No. 12 Ohio State a fixture in the Top 25. 
</P>
<P>
	His job was in jeopardy after several losses to Michigan and a  
couple of tough bowl defeats, including a surprise to Air Force in 
the 1990 Liberty Bowl. He flirted with leaving to take the LSU job 
a few years ago, but was lured back with a multi-year contract that 
features rollover years for victories in those ``big games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He is close to signing another contract that will pay him in  
excess of $1 million a year, including ancillary agreements that 
include TV and radio shows and other responsibilities. 
</P>
<P>
	No one questions that he has rejuvenated a program that was  
declining under Earle Bruce, who was let go in a messy firing at 
the end of the 1987 season. 
</P>
<P>
	There are still occasional academic and legal problems with his  
players, but for the most part Cooper has restored the luster 
brought to Ohio State in Woody Hayes' 28 years as head coach. Only 
Hayes, with a 205-61-10 record, has won more games with the 
Buckeyes, and only Hayes and John Wilce (16 seasons) have longer 
football tenures at the school. 
</P>
<P>
	A hundred wins may not be his goal, but he is looking at another  
round number. His career record, encompassing 23 years as head 
coach at Tulsa, Arizona State and Ohio State, is 181-74-6. 
</P>
<P>
	``I look more at the big picture,'' he said. ``I know how many  
games I've won at this point in my career. I'm thinking more and 
more about trying to win 200. Part of that is it doesn't take too 
long.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he has no desire to challenge the win totals of some of  
his peers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to hunt down (Joe) Paterno or (Bobby) Bowden or  
LaVell Edwards,'' he said. ``They've been at it a lot longer than I 
have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cooper said he hasn't contemplated retirement.  
</P>
<P>
	``I feel good. I've got good young players in the program. So  
why not?'' Cooper said. ``If I wasn't coaching, what would I do? 
I'd have to get a job.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990923.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 21:04:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Moynihan Endorses Bradley </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- New York's most prominent Democrat, Sen. Daniel  
Patrick Moynihan, endorsed Bill Bradley for president Thursday, 
saying Vice President Al Gore ``can't be elected.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 72-year-old senator, known for his quirky intellectual  
style, quoted Woodrow Wilson as saying the presidency required 
candidates ``from among wise and prudent athletes, a small class.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley was a Rhodes scholar and a player on two NBA  
championship teams with the New York Knicks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've seen this particular athlete, wise and prudent, work in  
the U.S. Senate for 18 years,'' Moynihan said. ``He is a man with 
heart and courage and stamina.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked why he wasn't supporting the vice president, the  
Democratic front-runner, Moynihan replied: ``Nothing is the matter 
with Gore, but he can't be elected.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At Gore's campaign headquarters, communications director Kiki  
Moore suggested Moynihan's imprimatur would make little difference: 
``I'm sure President Bob Kerrey appreciated (Moynihan's) support in 
1992.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But opinions varied.  
</P>
<P>
	``At this point in time, it makes a difference because Moynihan  
is a venerated figure within the Democratic Party,'' said 
Democratic consultant George Arzt. ``But over the long term, it 
usually doesn't translate into votes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``An endorsement from Moynihan in this state has got to be a  
great day for the Bradley campaign,'' said Robert McClure, senior 
associate dean of Syracuse University's Maxwell School of 
Citizenship and Public Affairs. ``Bradley is pitching himself as 
exactly the kind of intellectual, moderate progressive that Senator 
Moynihan has always been seen as.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Comptroller Carl McCall, a Gore backer, said the endorsement  
``makes a good story today. In terms of impact over the long run, 
it means very little.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley acknowledged his difficult course.  
</P>
<P>
	``I know we are up against a party establishment that has a lot  
of entrenched power,'' he said. ``But this will ultimately be 
decided by the people themselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Moynihan is the third senator to endorse Bradley, joining Paul  
Wellstone of Minnesota and Bob Kerrey of Nebraska. Bradley served 
three terms as a New Jersey senator, working with Moynihan -- who 
was first elected in 1976 -- on the Senate Finance Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore has been endorsed by more than 100 members of Congress,  
including 10 of the 19 Democrats from New York. The state's other 
senator, Democrat Charles Schumer, has not made a formal 
endorsement. 
</P>
<P>
	National polls show Gore leads Bradley, but recent surveys in  
New Hampshire and New York have shown a tight race between the two 
Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	New York is one of 14 states to pick presidential nominees on  
March 7. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to win this primary on March 7,'' Moynihan said.  
``We'll be proud of ourselves for having been here early. We can do 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Moynihan also backed first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, a Gore  
supporter, to replace him as senator when he retires at the end of 
2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about the conflict of supporting Mrs. Clinton but not  
Gore, Moynihan said simply: ``I think she can be elected senator.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton would not comment on whether Moynihan's endorsement  
of Bradley was awkward for her, saying only that she strongly 
supports Gore but is grateful for Moynihan's backing for her own 
aspirations. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990923.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 21:04:52 </DATE_TIME>
