<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Davenport, Seles Advance in Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Top-seeded Lindsay Davenport swept past Anna  
Smashnova of Israel 6-0, 6-1 today to advance to the quarterfinals 
of the Toyota Princess Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Three-time defending champion Monica Seles, the second seed,  
also advanced with a 6-1, 6-0 victory over Swiss qualifier 
Miroslava Vavrinec. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first singles match both for Seles and Davenport, who  
had first-round byes. 
</P>
<P>
	The fifth-ranked Seles, seeking her sixth singles title in the  
tournament, faces fifth seed and No. 14 Amelie Mauresmo of France 
in the quarterfinals. The second-ranked Davenport takes on 
sixth-seeded Conchita Martinez. 
</P>
<P>
	Davenport dominated the play against Smashnova and needed only  
35 minutes for the victory, losing only the first game in the 
second set. 
</P>
<P>
	``All of a sudden, she hit a couple of good serves and hit them  
a little harder than she had served. I was really disappointed,'' 
Davenport joked. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was happy I played so well considering I didn't get in till  
late Tuesday night and there was a lot of jet lag from 
California,'' she said of her tedious journey coming to Tokyo after 
winning the Fed Cup final Sunday against the Russian team in 
Stanford, California. 
</P>
<P>
	Davenport and Seles led the U.S. team, which also included  
sisters Venus and Serena Williams. 
</P>
<P>
	Seles said she was tired and happy to have had an easy match.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'll just try to have a good night's sleep and get ready for  
tomorrow's match,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	In other second-round matches, third-seeded Julie Halard-Decugis  
breezed past Nicole Pratt of Australia 6-1, 6-0; No. 4 Amanda 
Coetzer of South Africa rallied from a set down and 1-3 in the 
second set to beat Maureen Drake of Canada 4-6, 6-3, 6-4. 
</P>
<P>
	Ai Sugiyama, the eighth seed, won the final five games in  
beating American Jane Chi 6-2, 6-4. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
