<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 13:40:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dems Edgy About Bradley Strength </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Bill Bradley's growing strength in the polls  
has Democrats edgy about the political implications of a rough 
nomination fight, with some saying for the first time that Vice 
President Al Gore could be beaten. 
</P>
<P>
	Carolyn Boyce, vice chairman of Idaho Democrats, said Gore will  
be forced to spend precious campaign money to fend off a challenge 
from Bradley, while GOP front-runner George W. Bush is building up 
a huge campaign fund for the general election. 
</P>
<P>
	``It diverts money and Democratic money is so limited,'' said  
Boyce, who was in town Thursday for a meeting of the Democratic 
National Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The DNC is a stronghold of Gore support, but some in their ranks  
concede a tough primary fight could be costly. In a stark contrast 
to the DNC's spring meeting, when Bradley was just beginning to 
make inroads against the vice president, party regulars were saying 
Thursday that Gore is a vulnerable front-runnner. 
</P>
<P>
	One Southern chairman said he had seen a ``sea change'' since  
spring and he worried Gore's campaign was unprepared for a stiff 
challenge from Bradley. 
</P>
<P>
	Edward Marcus, state chairman of the Connecticut Democratic  
Party, acknowledged the uneasiness among some party officials. 
</P>
<P>
	``People who are neophytes tend to get shaken up,'' he said.  
It's less worrisome for ``those who have been around for a while.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This is good for the party. I'm seeing a lot of people getting  
energized who were not involved in the past. I think part of that 
is due to Bill Bradley, who is touching people who might be coming 
back to the party,'' said Iowa party chairman Rob Tully. ``It will 
be a close race, but it will make Gore a better candidate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore had a much stronger presence than Bradley at the DNC  
meeting. He had staff in every meeting, a political table set up 
near the registration desk and scheduled a meet-and-greet breakfast 
for Friday. Gore can't afford to lose support within the DNC; 
Bradley has never depended upon it, and hopes instead to draw less 
active Democrats and independents to his campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	A contested primary season could be useful for Gore -- up to a  
point, said Gore supporter Charles Rangel, a New York congressman 
who has noted Gore needs to do more to reach out to fellow 
Democrats and unify the party. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley, a former New Jersey senator, has shown strength in the  
polls in several states with early primaries. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've seen enough surveys to suggest that something is going on  
out there,'' said political analyst Stuart Rothenberg, who 
cautioned it's way too early to focus on point margins. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley has also demonstrated the ability to raise money. Gore  
had $9.4 million in the bank at the end of June, and Bradley had 
$7.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley and Gore are neck-and-neck in recent polls in New  
Hampshire and New York. Party activists are taking note of polls 
showing Bradley doing better than Gore in matchups against Bush, 
partially due to Bradley's appeal with independents. 
</P>
<P>
	Many key primary states have no recent poll results on the  
presidential race and are unlikely to resume polling on that 
question until middle or late fall, state pollsters say. 
</P>
<P>
	While Bradley has shown signs of making it a race in parts of  
the Northeast, some political veterans note that Gore has the 
support of much of the political establishment nationwide and from 
traditional Democratic groups. 
</P>
<P>
	``Gore has the support of most Democratic officeholders,'' said  
Merle Black, an Emory University political scientist. ``He would 
have the party establishment behind him in the South as well as the 
support of most black officeholders.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley got the endorsement Thursday of Sen. Daniel Patrick  
Moynihan of New York, the third senator to do so. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked why he preferred Bradley over Gore, Moynihan responded  
simply, ``Nothing is the matter with Gore, but he can't be 
elected.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore, by comparison, has compiled endorsements from more than  
100 members of Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley trailed Gore by a 50 percent-to-32 percent margin among  
nationwide Democrats and independents who lean Democratic in a CBS 
News poll out Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Recent polls by Gallup and the Pew Research Center for the  
People &AMP; the Press suggest Gore's support is strongest among 
registered Democrats, blacks and women. Bradley runs closest to 
Gore among independents, men and the better educated. 
</P>
<P>
	Polls this early in the political process often don't reflect  
what will happen, especially for Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1971 and 1975, the early polls gave no indication that  
eventual nominees George McGovern and Jimmy Carter would win. In 
September 1987, Michael Dukakis was among the candidates, but not 
the Democratic leader in the Gallup poll. In the fall of 1991, 
Gallup had no clear front-runner. However, Gore is the first 
Democrat to run for the nomination as a sitting vice-president 
since 1968. 
</P>
<P>
	The increased strength shown by Bradley may be more of a  
statement against Gore than for Bradley, said Andrew Kohut, 
director of the Pew poll, who notes some Americans are tired of the 
Clinton administration. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most people aren't too familiar with Bill Bradley,'' said  
Kohut. ``Our surveys show that most people, including Democrats, 
are not paying too much attention.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990923.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 15:50:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Rises Against the Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar rose slightly against the Japanese  
yen on Thursday for the first time in four days, but traders were 
cautious ahead of this weekend's meeting of the Group of Seven 
industrialized nations. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 103.95  
Japanese yen, up just slightly from 103.93 late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders braced for the G-7 meeting on Saturday, where many hope  
that Japan will be able to enlist help from its economic partners 
in curbing the yen's rise. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan has intervened in currency markets several times this  
summer in an attempt to slow the yen's gains, but without success. 
Japanese officials believe that the yen has strengthened too much 
and could harm the country's fledgling economic recovery. A rising 
yen makes it harder for Japanese exports to compete on world 
markets. 
</P>
<P>
	But traders aren't confident that the United States would be  
willing to support a new currency policy. 
</P>
<P>
	William McDonough, president of the New York Federal Reserve  
Bank, said that he was not concerned about the level of the dollar 
versus the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	``The level of the U.S. Dollar is not a problem for the U.S.  
economy,'' he said in a speech Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0440, down from  
$1.0448 late Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.5362 Swiss francs, down from  
1.5369, and 1.4711 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4702. The British 
pound rose to $1.6407 from $1.6284. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Thursday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8734 German 
marks, up from 1.8719; 6.2831 French francs, up from 6.2780; and 
1,854.66 Italian lire, up from 1,853.16. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
