<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ovarian Implant Called Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- An experimental ovarian tissue transplant has  
worked and allowed a prematurely menopausal woman to ovulate and 
have a normal menstrual period, a doctor said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	International experts praised the work, saying it could give  
women with ovarian cancer another chance to have a child. The 
American Cancer Society estimates that 25,200 women will be 
diagnosed with ovarian cancer this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``This case indicates that we are on the cusp of safe, reliable  
transplantation of human ovarian tissue,'' said Larry Lipshultz, 
president of the American Society for Reproductive Medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Kutluk Oktay performed the procedure in February at New York  
Methodist Hospital on a 30-year-old woman in the hopes of reversing 
symptoms of menopause brought on by the removal of her ovaries. 
</P>
<P>
	The organs were taken out for medical reasons, although the  
specifics were not made public. 
</P>
<P>
	The woman had some of her ovarian tissue preserved through  
freezing after her second ovary was removed two years ago. Her 
first ovary was removed when she was 17. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors used miniature instruments and robotic equipment to  
implant the tissue through three tiny holes in the patient's 
pelvis. 
</P>
<P>
	Four months after the procedure, Oktay gave the woman fertility  
drugs to test ovarian function. The woman developed an egg, 
ovulated, and had a normal menstrual period, Oktay said. 
</P>
<P>
	Oktay will be presenting his work next week at a meeting of the  
American Society for Reproductive Medicine in Toronto. He said 
ovarian tissue transplants could give new hope to young girls and 
women who face the loss of their ovaries to cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's probably the best news they can have,'' Oktay said.  
``After they hear they have cancer, there is someone telling them 
they may have hope for the future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. James Drife, a London-based professor of gynecology, said  
Oktay's operation was an important step forward. 
</P>
<P>
	``My gut feeling is that this development wouldn't really create  
a stampede of women saying, `let's finish our careers then have 
children in the last 20 to 30 years of our lives,''' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
