<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> BP Exploration Pleads Guilty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) -- BP Exploration (Alaska) Inc. agreed  
Thursday to pay $22 million to settle charges that one of its 
contractors illegally dumped hazardous waste at a North Slope oil 
field. 
</P>
<P>
	The plea agreement entered in U.S. District Court in Anchorage  
calls for the company to pay a $500,000 criminal fine and $6.5 
million to settle civil charges. It will also spend $15 million to 
establish an environmental management system throughout its U.S. 
operations during a five-year probation period. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal prosecutors said the company failed to immediately  
notify state and federal authorities when it learned that Doyon 
Drilling Inc., one of its contractors, had dumped waste oil, paint 
thinner, solvents and other hazardous chemicals into oil shafts at 
the Endicott oil field. 
</P>
<P>
	The company acknowledged it failed to adequately supervise  
Doyon's activities and pleaded guilty to a single felony count of 
violating federal environmental reporting requirements. 
</P>
<P>
	Doyon pleaded guilty last year to 15 counts of violating federal  
oil pollution laws and paid a $1 million fine. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of barrels of waste were dumped from January 1993 to  
September 1995, prosecutors said. Company officials said they heard 
allegations of dumping on Aug. 31, 1995, but didn't report them for 
two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	BP officials said they first conducted an internal investigation  
and alerted the Environmental Protection Agency when the company 
confirmed that violations had occurred. Company officials said they 
mistakenly thought federal environmental laws allowed them to 
determine whether the allegations were credible before reporting 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert C. Bundy, U.S. Attorney for Alaska, said he expected the  
case would send a message to other companies in the oil industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``You cannot contract away your environmental responsibility,''  
Bundy said at a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Bundy praised BP for what he called an extraordinary degree of  
cooperation with the investigation. Federal prosecutors are 
continuing their investigation in the case, but would not say 
whether additional criminal or civil charges were expected. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the money to be paid out under the settlement  
agreement, BP said it has already spent $5 million to improve its 
environmental management within Alaska during the criminal 
investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	The $15 million national environmental management system will  
cover all of BP's operations in the United States and the Gulf of 
Mexico. The program will include hiring an environmental monitor 
and regular audits of the company's environmental practices. 
</P>
<P>
	The intent is to make sure that employees and contractors  
understand environmental regulations and are properly trained in 
waste disposal, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are ultimately responsible for what occurs in our oil  
fields and these improper disposals would not have occurred if the 
systems that we had in place were working as well as we believed. 
We've learned from this mistake and have taken steps to prevent a 
recurrence,'' BP spokesman Ronnie Chappell said. 
</P>
<P>
	BP maintains no environmental damage occurred from the dumping  
at its Endicott field, but federal prosecutors say some of the 
material reached the surface. 
</P>
<P>
	There were no plans to try to determine the extent of the  
pollution or to clean up the shafts where the waste was dumped 
because it would be too expensive and could cause further 
environmental damage. 
</P>
<P>
	``What's done is done,'' Bundy said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
