<HEADLINE> Germany Conglomerate To Split </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DUESSELDORF, Germany (AP) -- German conglomerate Mannesmann said  
Thursday it plans to split its fast-growing telecommunications 
business from its engineering and automotive divisions in a bid to 
boost profits. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement sent Mannesmann shares soaring on the Frankfurt  
stock exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	By creating two independent companies with separate identities,  
Mannesmann's business strategy ``can be powered in an even stronger 
and more focused manner,'' a company statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mannesmann's board of directors made the proposal to the  
supervisory board Thursday, the company said. A decision was 
expected early next year. 
</P>
<P>
	After the announcement, Mannesmann shares rose sharply. They  
closed at 152 euros ($145.60), up 7.9 percent from Wednesday's 
close. 
</P>
<P>
	Mannesmann said the separated companies will be financed  
separately from 2001. By the end of next year, it plans to install 
separate executive boards to manage them. 
</P>
<P>
	Mannesmann said it also aims to list the two companies  
separately on European capital markets in 2001 and wants both 
companies to be components of Germany's DAX 30 blue chip index. 
</P>
<P>
	Mannesmann, which has its headquarters in Duesseldorf, reported  
revenue of $22.34 billion in 1998. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
