<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Floyd Causes Hospital Water Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENVILLE, N.C. (AP) -- Eastern North Carolina's largest  
hospital has tapped into its rehabilitation swimming pool to keep 
toilets flushing and water flowing in the aftermath of Hurricane 
Floyd. 
</P>
<P>
	Fire department water trucks are sucking water in the pool and  
circulating it through the plumbing system at Pitt County Memorial 
Hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think a flood is the worst disaster a hospital could sustain  
because it affects all areas of a hospital and all parts of the 
infrastructure,'' the hospital's Dr. John Meredith said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The hospital was disconnected from the city's water system on  
Tuesday, after nearly a week of on and off service. Flooding has 
crippled the city's water treatment plant. Fire trucks and water 
tankers have been bringing water to the rehab pool and department 
pumper trucks then relay the greenish water into hospital pipes. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the system has enabled the 731-bed hospital to continue  
operating, the temporary solution has created its risks. 
</P>
<P>
	A gasoline truck refueling the fire trucks exploded Wednesday  
night. About 1,000 gallons of gasoline ignited, but no one was hurt 
and the hospital was not damaged. Firefighters on the scene 
extinguished the flames in minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	Bottled water is still being used for drinking, while doctors  
and nurses have used alcohol to sterilize their hands. The hospital 
has limited surgeries to urgent and emergency cases to conserve 
water, postponing others. 
</P>
<P>
	Russell Gibbs, senior administrator of the hospital's operations  
department, estimates several hundred thousand gallons of water 
since Tuesday morning have gone into the 80,000-gallon swimming 
pool -- described as roughly half the size of an Olympic-size pool -- 
and then into the hospital's water system. 
</P>
<P>
	Gibbs said the hospital likely will return to the city system  
later this week. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
