<HEADLINE> Casino Regulators OK Trump Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) -- Regulators have approved plans by  
casino mogul Donald Trump to close and demolish his money-losing 
Trump World's Fair Casino to make way for a new Atlantic City 
mega-resort. 
</P>
<P>
	The Casino Control Commission on Wednesday gave Trump permission  
to proceed with demolition of the World's Fair, which is located 
between historic Convention Hall and Trump Plaza on the Atlantic 
City boardwalk 
</P>
<P>
	Gambling will cease at World's Fair at midnight on Oct. 3, but  
guests who have booked rooms that night can stay over and check out 
the next day, according to Joseph Fusco, executive vice president 
of Trump Hotels &AMP; Casino Resorts Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Slot machines, gaming tables and other equipment will be removed  
over the following four to six weeks and demolition will occur 
sometime after that, he said. Demolition alone will cost between $3 
million and $5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Trump hasn't disclosed specific plans for the new casino, but  
his company said in July that clearing the 12-acre site ``will give 
us the flexibility to develop the kind of world-class signature 
property that has made the Trump Organization the dominant 
developer in New York.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The new casino hotel, which could have up to 4,000 rooms, would  
cost about $750 million -- an amount that might force Trump to 
partner with investors or another casino company. 
</P>
<P>
	Construction could begin in early 2001, said Trump Hotels chief  
executive Nicholas L. Ribis. 
</P>
<P>
	Trump World's Fair, a 21-story structure originally built as a  
Playboy casino-resort, was bought by Trump for $63 million in 1989. 
He ran it as a non-casino hotel, Trump Regency, before pumping $48 
million into renovations and reopening it in 1996 as Trump World's 
Fair. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite that, it has been losing about $10 million a year. The  
casino is considered an extension of Trump Plaza and operates under 
its license. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
