<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Flood Victims Return to Ruin, Mud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROCKY MOUNT, N.C. (AP) -- Some of the thousands of people who  
were driven out by Hurricane Floyd's floodwaters a week ago finally 
went home Thursday and found ruin at every turn: soaked carpeting, 
ruined keepsakes, mud everywhere. 
</P>
<P>
	In a neighborhood near the Tar River in Rocky Mount, Jackie  
Bailey salvaged china from a cabinet that had crashed to the floor 
of her mother's home. Everything was caked in muck, but none of the 
china broke. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're probably going to bulldoze this,'' she said. She bent  
over a warped photo of her father that had fallen off the wall, 
where mildew already was forming. 
</P>
<P>
	Down the road, Bailey's husband, Mickey, was hosing brown grime  
from tables and chairs hauled from Bob Melton's barbecue 
restaurant, which has stood on the banks of the Tar for 75 years. 
Water reached the roof earlier this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``We knew there would be flooding. We didn't know it would be  
the flood of the millennium,'' said Bailey, who owns the building. 
He said Bob Melton's owners feel almost dutybound to reopen because 
the restaurant is a city institution. 
</P>
<P>
	``They'll figure if Bob Melton's can come back, they all can,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	A week after the storm dumped 20 inches of rain here, more than  
700 roads remained flooded, the death toll rose to 42, and 
thousands were still in shelters. The eaves of homes poked through 
floodwaters in Princeville, a community of 1,900 founded 130 years 
ago by freed slaves. 
</P>
<P>
	National Guard helicopters continued to airlift bottled water  
and supplies to stranded communities across the soggy, 
18,000-square-mile region. 
</P>
<P>
	The 42nd confirmed death was Spec. Leon Reece Penland Jr., a  
National Guardsman killed Wednesday when his Humvee overturned. 
</P>
<P>
	Though waters were receding across much of eastern North  
Carolina, in Kinston, the bloated Neuse River was cresting at 28 
feet, twice its flood stage. 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Wiggins, an emergency room technician at Lenoir County  
Memorial Hospital, peered across the street at his parents' home in 
Kinston, where floodwaters slapped at the top step. His parents had 
evacuated earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the only house I have,'' he said. ``That's the one you  
come back to when you don't have anywhere else to go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Displaced families moved into a trailer village that opened  
Wednesday outside Rocky Mount, and another temporary community is 
planned near Greenville. Between the two, some 1,000 families will 
have homes, and state officials said more villages may open in 
other cities. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Gov. Jim Hunt went to Washington to lobby for more  
federal disaster aid. Losses are expected to surpass Hurricane 
Fran's $6 billion in 1996, with farm losses accounting for more 
than $1 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is the worst flood in the history of our state and maybe  
this country,'' Hunt said. ``We absolutely cannot recover without a 
great deal of help from our government.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
