<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton To Veto GOP Spending Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Eager to confront Republicans over the issue  
of schools, President Clinton is promising to veto a GOP-written 
$316 billion measure financing education, health and labor 
programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton issued his threat Thursday after Republicans pushed the  
bill through a House Appropriations subcommittee by a party-line 
8-6 vote. Though the bill's $35.6 billion for education is only 
$1.5 billion less than Clinton proposed, its cuts for more 
teachers, literacy training and adult education drew the 
president's objections. 
</P>
<P>
	``It fails to give public schools the resources to succeed, and  
does nothing to demand accountability for results,'' Clinton said 
in a written statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation is the biggest of the 13 annual spending bills  
for the coming fiscal year, only four of which Congress has sent to 
the White House. GOP leaders already plan to send Clinton 
legislation to keep agencies functioning for three weeks after Oct. 
1, when fiscal 2000 begins. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate was hoping to complete its $97 billion spending bill  
for veterans, housing, environment and space programs. It is among 
seven spending bills facing veto threats, this one because it falls 
short of Clinton demands for some environmental and other programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's veto threat on the labor-health bill was unusual  
because it was issued in his name and at only the subcommittee 
level. The action reflected how happy Democrats are to engage the 
GOP over education. Polls show the public trusts Democrats more 
than Republicans to deal with schools. 
</P>
<P>
	House Appropriations Committee Chairman Bill Young, R-Fla.,  
acknowledged that negotiations with the White House are likely 
before the bill takes its final shape, calling it ``the beginning 
of a process, and the process will require some adjustments as we 
go along.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, Republicans defended the measure, saying they paid for  
it while honoring their pledge to not use Social Security surpluses 
in the coming fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are committed, all of us, to stop bleeding Social Security  
reserves,'' said Rep. John Porter, R-Ill., chairman of the 
subcommittee that approved the bill. ``That takes some 
discipline.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans have adopted a number of bookkeeping devices to let  
them claim they would leave Social Security alone. This includes 
delaying billions in spending until 2001, declaring $1.4 billion in 
a decades-old home-heating aid program for the poor to be an 
``emergency,'' and reclaiming $3 billion in unspent welfare funds 
from the states -- a move that governors lambasted. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the measure covers automatically paid benefits like  
Medicaid. Of the remainder -- money for every other federal 
education, health and labor program -- the GOP would provide $89.4 
billion. That is $2.2 billion less than Clinton requested, and $300 
million less than is being spent this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure equals or exceeds Clinton's requests for educating  
handicapped students, treating AIDS patients and the Job Corps. But 
it also cuts the president's plans for after-school programs, job 
training for teen-agers and Head Start. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would provide $17 billion for biomedical research at  
the National Institutes of Health, $1.1 billion more than Clinton 
requested. It also would outspend Clinton for community health 
centers, and maternal and child care grants to states. 
</P>
<P>
	But it would trim Clinton's requests for the Occupational Safety  
and Health Administration. And it would combine favorite Clinton 
programs for hiring new teachers, training teachers and improving 
local education standards into grants that states could use as they 
choose, but with $400 million less than the president requested for 
the three initiatives. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile:  
</P>
<P>
	--House-Senate bargainers edged toward a compromise that would  
keep production of the F-22 stealth fighter alive but might not let 
the Air Force purchase any next year. 
</P>
<P>
	--Negotiators from the two chambers remained at odds over foreign  
aid and agriculture spending bills. 
</P>
<P>
	--The Senate voted 89-10 to approve a $14 billion measure  
financing the Interior Department after oil-state senators, by 
51-47, won language blocking the Clinton administration from 
raising royalties that oil companies pay to drill on federal lands. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
