<DOCNO> APW19990923.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 10:06:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Students Protest in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Thousands of university students  
rampaged in more than a half-dozen Indonesian cities today, 
clashing with police in protests against a new law giving the armed 
forces sweeping emergency powers. 
</P>
<P>
	Local news media, including radio station Sonora, reported three  
demonstrators were killed in Jakarta, but there was no confirmation 
from authorities or local hospitals. 
</P>
<P>
	A total of 53 people were injured, the SCTV network reported. At  
least four were rushed to the hospital with bullet wounds. 
</P>
<P>
	The protesters claim the new law will strengthen the military's  
already powerful role in domestic politics, and threaten the giant 
country's move toward democracy. 
</P>
<P>
	The clashes sent the Indonesian currency into a dive on fears of  
renewed anarchy. The rupiah lost 4.3 percent of its value against 
the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	Police fired rubber bullets and beat students with clubs in two  
Jakarta protests. An estimated 6,000 students and their supporters, 
many carrying sticks, clashed with police outside parliament, 
starting early in the afternoon and going into the evening. 
</P>
<P>
	Police also fired tear gas into a sea of angry demonstrators,  
who set several vehicles on fire. At least five police officers 
were burned when they were hit by firebombs in Jakarta. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 4,000 protesters flooded into the streets in the country's  
second-largest city, Surabaya, and more than 200 rallied on the 
resort island of Bali. 
</P>
<P>
	At the governor's office in the violence-wracked province of  
Aceh, 300 students smashed windows and fought with police. Similar 
protests were also taking place in Semarang, Ujung Pandang and 
Yogjakarta. 
</P>
<P>
	Just hours earlier today, Indonesia's parliament unanimously  
approved the law giving the armed forces wide-ranging emergency 
powers, triggering the violent reaction. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure allows the military to ban protests, take over the  
telecommunications system and mail service, and curb freedom of 
expression if a state of emergency is proclaimed. Even before the 
new law, the military held a dominant role in governing this 
country of 210 million people. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bill will be enacted not to serve the interests of the  
military but to safeguard the unity of the nation,'' said Gen. 
Wiranto, head of the Indonesian armed forces. 
</P>
<P>
	Even before its passage, the law had sparked days of protest in  
Jakarta and elsewhere in Indonesia. 
</P>
<P>
	University students, who led the movement that toppled President  
Suharto in May 1998, claim the new measure threatens Indonesia's 
fledgling democratic rule and gives the military too much power. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first protest today, 500 students rallied at Jakarta's  
Moestopo University in the southern part of the city. In a second 
protest, 6,000 students marched on parliament to protest the new 
law. They were blocked by riot police, and then started throwing 
rocks, pieces of wood and everything else they could grab. 
</P>
<P>
	Demonstrations in Jakarta continued into the night, with  
protesters and police blocking key downtown avenues and exchanging 
volleys of rubber bullets and Molotov cocktails. 
</P>
<P>
	One person was carried away wrapped in a white sheet, but it was  
not known whether the person had died. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990923.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 10:06:24 </DATE_TIME>
