were burned when they were hit by firebombs in Jakarta. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 4,000 protesters flooded into the streets in the country's  
second-largest city, Surabaya, and more than 200 rallied on the 
resort island of Bali. 
</P>
<P>
	At the governor's office in the violence-wracked province of  
Aceh, 300 students smashed windows and fought with police. Similar 
protests were also taking place in Semarang, Ujung Pandang and 
Yogjakarta. 
</P>
<P>
	Just hours earlier today, Indonesia's parliament unanimously  
approved the law giving the armed forces wide-ranging emergency 
powers, triggering the violent reaction. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure allows the military to ban protests, take over the  
telecommunications system and mail service, and curb freedom of 
expression if a state of emergency is proclaimed. Even before the 
new law, the military held a dominant role in governing this 
country of 210 million people. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bill will be enacted not to serve the interests of the  
military but to safeguard the unity of the nation,'' said Gen. 
Wiranto, head of the Indonesian armed forces. 
</P>
<P>
	Even before its passage, the law had sparked days of protest in  
Jakarta and elsewhere in Indonesia. 
</P>
<P>
	University students, who led the movement that toppled President  
Suharto in May 1998, claim the new measure threatens Indonesia's 
