<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dividend Sets New Record in Alaska </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) -- Alaskans consider themselves different  
from other Americans, and this year that difference pays a record 
$1,769.84. 
</P>
<P>
	That's the amount more than 575,000 residents will receive as  
their share of earnings from the Alaska Permanent Fund, a savings 
account set up more than two decades ago to preserve a portion of 
the state's oil-field revenue. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue Commissioner Wilson Condon revealed the dividend amount  
Wednesday. The payout is the highest in the program's 18-year 
history, and it represents the eighth straight year that the amount 
has increased. 
</P>
<P>
	Anyone who has collected every dividend since the inception of  
the program in 1982 will see their grand total rise to more than 
$16,500 with this year's addition. 
</P>
<P>
	Just over $1 billion will be distributed in dividends, also a  
record, according to the state Department of Revenue. Those who 
lived in the state for all of 1998 are eligible for the money. 
</P>
<P>
	Alaskans will have cash in hand beginning in early October. For  
many, a spending frenzy begins: holidays in Hawaii, new cars and 
snowmobiles, Christmas shopping sprees. Others save or use the 
money to retire debt. 
</P>
<P>
	In rural areas the dividend is among the major annual sources of  
cash and buys necessities like hunting rifles and fishing nets. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you're talking about total personal income in the state,  
(the dividend) is a big player,'' said Neal Fried, a state labor 
economist. ``It's bigger than almost any industry payroll. ... It's 
bigger than the oil industry payroll.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A prolonged stock market boom has driven up the value of the  
fund to $26.4 billion as of this week, more than double what it was 
seven years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The dividend amount is roughly calculated as 10.5 percent of the  
fund's net income over the last five years divided by the number of 
eligible Alaskans. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
