<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 08:15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IRS Urges Swift Tax Law Extensions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With President Clinton poised to veto the $792  
billion Republican tax cut bill, the Internal Revenue Service is 
urging Congress to move swiftly to extend expiring tax provisions 
so forms can be drafted for next year. 
</P>
<P>
	IRS Commissioner Charles Rossotti met Wednesday with Rep. Bill  
Archer, chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee, to stress 
that tax law changes effective for the 2000 filing season needed to 
be on the president's desk by Oct. 7. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's pretty much the drop-dead date,'' Rossotti said.  
``Printing the forms -- you've got to have some lead time to do 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Archer, R-Texas, said he would attempt to comply by moving  
forward on a tax package -- possibly as early as Friday -- that would 
extend several expiring provisions at a one-year cost of roughly $3 
billion. These ``extenders'' are part of the larger $792 billion 
tax cut, but unlike that bill they have broad bipartisan support. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to move it as quickly as we can,'' Archer said.  
</P>
<P>
	Also Wednesday, Senate Finance Committee Chairman William Roth,  
R-Del., asked GOP leaders to reserve $4 billion of the projected 
$14 billion fiscal 2000 non-Social Security surplus for the 
extenders package and for Medicare costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton is expected to veto the larger GOP tax bill on Thursday  
at the White House, and it remains unclear whether Republicans and 
Democrats can agree on a compromise other than the extenders. 
Archer, however, said those provisions should move on their own. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would prefer to keep it as simple as possible,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The driving forces behind the package are a research and  
development tax credit favored by high-tech companies and 
manufacturers and a provision ensuring that millions of 
middle-class taxpayers don't fall subject to the higher alternative 
minimum tax if they take personal credits on their income tax 
returns such as the $500 per child credit and education credits. 
</P>
<P>
	``We promised these benefits to middle-income families and we  
should not let AMT interfere with these credits,'' Roth said in a 
letter to Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss. 
</P>
<P>
	Other provisions include extension of credits aimed at  
encouraging businesses to hire workers from certain targeted groups 
and to provide jobs for former welfare recipients. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Democrats generally support these items, some disagree  
with Archer's plan to use projected budget surplus dollars to pay 
for them. Rep. Charles Rangel of New York, top Democrat on the Ways 
and Means Committee, said he will propose an alternative that 
raises the necessary revenue by closing several corporate tax 
loopholes. 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP version, Rangel said, is a ``threat'' to Social Security  
because it could tap into money earmarked for that retirement 
program, saying, ``No attempt is being made to pay for it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rangel said his version also would extend and expand an expiring  
school construction bond program that expires on Dec. 31. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990923.0129 </DOCNO>
