<HEADLINE> Search for Escaped Killer Grows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COUNCIL GROVE, Kan. (AP) -- A man escaped from a county jail  
hours after he was sentenced to nearly 42 years for shaking a young 
boy to death, a getaway that came while the sheriff's department 
was busy with a traffic accident. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott Adam escaped Tuesday from a jail exercise yard by climbing  
a 10-foot chain-link fence topped with razor wire in this small 
town 50 miles southwest of Topeka. 
</P>
<P>
	Adam, 24, pleaded guilty to second-degree murder in the October  
1998 death of 16-month-old Timothy Post, the son of his former 
girlfriend. 
</P>
<P>
	Officers searched for him Tuesday night, but tracking dogs lost  
his scent and the search, said Sheriff R.J. Meierhoff. The search 
continued Wednesday with tracking dogs and aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
	The escape came while the sheriff's department, whose offices  
are located in the building that houses the jail, was responding to 
a traffic accident. Meierhoff said the department has five officers 
and some at the jail were sent to the accident. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were in the process of dispatching units to an accident, so  
it was a little lax then,'' he said. ``We got a little busy because 
of the car accident.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the time of the boy's slaying, Adam was on parole after  
serving time for the 1993 stabbing death of a Kansas State 
University student. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
