<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 04:40:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Falcons Handle Life With No Jamal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SUWANEE, Ga. (AP) -- The Atlanta Falcons are slowly coming to  
grips with the idea of life without Jamal Anderson. The NFC 
champions can only hope Chris Chandler won't be out much longer. 
</P>
<P>
	On the same day Anderson hobbled into the training complex,  
dragging along the injured right knee that will keep him out for 
the season, Chandler returned to the practice field with the hope 
of playing Sunday against the St. Louis Rams. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any time you miss a game, there's always pressure to get back  
in there,'' said Chandler, who didn't play in Monday night's loss 
to Dallas because of a strained hamstring. ``But yeah, it's a 
little more important now to get back on the field.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Chandler returns, he won't be handing off to the guy who  
set an NFL record with 410 carries and a franchise mark with 1,846 
yards rushing. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's upsetting, particularly with the way things are going for  
us as a team this season,'' Anderson said Wednesday, referring to 
an 0-2 start after leading the Falcons to an improbable Super Bowl 
last season. ``To go down like I did was terrible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With Anderson finished for the year after suffering a torn  
anterior cruciate ligament on his third carry against the Cowboys, 
there is even more need for Chandler to make a hasty return to the 
lineup. 
</P>
<P>
	No. 2 quarterback Tony Graziani has yet to make it through an  
entire game during his three years in the NFL, getting pulled early 
in the third quarter at Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	``It feels a lot better than it felt last week,'' said Chandler,  
who looked a bit stiff, but took part in most of the drills. ``I'm 
very optimistic that if it continues to improve, I'll be good 
enough to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Falcons talked bravely about carrying on without the player  
who defined their ball-control offense. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson carried an inordinate amount of the load last season,  
allowing Atlanta to lead the NFL in time of possession and keep its 
defense well rested. Counting 27 pass receptions, he had a direct 
hand in 44 percent of the Falcons' 993 plays. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jamal did some great things for this team last year, and we  
were expecting him to do great things this year,'' receiver Terance 
Mathis said. ``Now, we've got to rally together and help each other 
out. If you're not blocking, not running routes, not catching the 
ball, you're not going to be successful no matter who's running the 
ball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the most part, the runner will be Byron Hanspard, a former  
2,000-yard rusher at Texas Tech who missed all of last season with 
a knee injury. He'll be supported by Ken Oxendine, a seventh-round 
draft pick in 1998 who has rushed for 50 yards in his career. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody needs an opportunity to see what they can do when a  
starter goes down,'' coach Dan Reeves said. ``I have tremendous 
confidence in Byron. I have tremendous confidence in Ken. Are they 
Jamal Anderson? No. But can they run certain plays well? Yes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest question concerning Hanspard is the state of his  
left knee. In the final exhibition game of 1998, he tore the ACL 
and patella tendon, requiring surgery and a full year to 
recuperate. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still don't think he is 100 percent,'' Reeves said. ``Each  
week that he can go through and gain more confidence in that knee, 
the better football player he is going to be. We will see.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After Anderson went down Monday -- crumpling to the ground after  
trying to make a cut with no one around him -- Hanspard ran a 
career-high 19 times for 76 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything is fine,'' he said. ``God has completely healed my  
knee. Yes, there's always room for it to get stronger, but I've not 
had any setbacks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hanspard won the Doak Walker Award as the nation's top college  
running back in 1996, when he had 2,084 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I need to carry the ball 33 times a game, I won't have a  
problem with that,'' Hanspard said. ``I've got to step up and be 
the man. That comes naturally for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson is expected to undergo surgery in a couple of weeks. He  
plans to be fully recovered by the start of offseason workouts. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm setting a timetable to be 100 percent by December,'' he  
said. ``If not then, it won't be much longer than that. I'm already 
making bets with the trainers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, the Falcons will have to play with a weakened  
hand the rest of this season. They placed Anderson on injured 
reserve and signed 5-foot-7 Winslow Oliver, who was waived by 
Carolina at the end of training camp and won't be mistaken by 
anyone for the player he's replacing on the roster. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are the kind of things that cause the true character of  
your team to come out,'' defensive tackle Travis Hall said. ``When 
you lose one player, is that your team? I think we can rebound.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
