<DOCNO> APW19990923.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 09:00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FBI Faults Justice Over Fund Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A bitter FBI-Justice Department conflict over  
tactics in a campaign fund-raising investigation is getting aired 
publicly before a Senate committee, and the panel's chairman 
indicates there's more to come. 
</P>
<P>
	After FBI agents and the former lead prosecutor in the probe  
criticized each other at a hearing Wednesday, Sen. Fred Thompson, 
R-Tenn., threatened additional hearings to learn why 27 pages of 
notes -- focusing on the dispute -- were ripped from an agent's 
notebook. The notes remain missing. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney General Janet Reno said today, ``We have just got to  
check and see just what happened ... but I don't know of any basis 
for concluding there is an obstruction of justice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Three agents assigned to the probe of illegal fund-raising in  
President Clinton's re-election campaign -- and a retired FBI 
supervisor -- told the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee that 
Justice Department prosecutors impeded their work in the 
investigation of presidential friend -- and Democratic donor -- Yah 
Lin ``Charlie'' Trie. 
</P>
<P>
	Countering the testimony, Laura Ingersoll, a Justice Department  
attorney who was the first lead prosecutor in the investigation, 
criticized the agents' work. She has since been replaced in the 
probe, but remains with the Justice Department. 
</P>
<P>
	FBI agent Roberta Parker testified that during the height of the  
dispute over tactics in the summer of 1997, she turned her personal 
notebooks over to FBI superiors because Thompson's panel and a 
House committee sought information on the rift. When the notes were 
returned, she said, the 27 pages were missing -- and could only have 
been torn the spiral-bound book. 
</P>
<P>
	The testimony spotlighted the bitter internal disagreements in  
the investigation of donations to the 1996 Clinton-Gore campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Disagreement over the investigation caused friction between Reno  
and FBI Director Louis Freeh. Reno eventually rejected the 
director's conclusion that an independent counsel should be 
appointed. 
</P>
<P>
	Disputing Reno's oft-quoted assertions of a vigorous  
investigation, FBI agent Daniel Wehr told the committee that 
Ingersoll told the agents they should ``not pursue any matter 
related to solicitation of funds for access to the president. The 
reason given was, 'That's the way the American political process 
works.' I was scandalized by that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, federal election and bribery laws make it a crime for  
officials to accept money or contributions in return for government 
decisions, but not in return for spending time in the official's 
presence. 
</P>
<P>
	Wehr, Parker and agent Kevin Sheridan are still assigned to the  
investigation and worked on the case of Trie, who pleaded guilty to 
campaign finance violations. Besides the three agents, the 
committee heard from Ivian C. Smith, the retired agent who headed 
the Little Rock, Ark., FBI office. 
</P>
<P>
	The four contended that Ms. Ingersoll prevented the FBI from  
executing search warrants to stop destruction of evidence and 
micromanaged the case beyond all reason. 
</P>
<P>
	But Ms. Ingersoll testified there was ``no smoking gun'' in  
documents the FBI discovered in the trash of Trie and a business 
associate -- records which, the agents concluded, should have been 
the basis for search warrants of the subjects' residences. 
</P>
<P>
	Explaining her rejection of the search warrant request in the  
summer of 1997, Ms. Ingersoll said, ``Nothing we saw indicated to 
us'' that there was ``anything incriminating'' in the documents. 
</P>
<P>
	She said the FBI's proposed search warrant affidavit lacked any  
description of how the records were relevant. 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't know what the documents were. The agents didn't  
bring us what these documents actually were. I would have wanted 
them (the search warrant justifications) to be fuller and more 
complete. The search warrant affidavit was far from being finalized 
... to be presented to a magistrate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson, who led the committees' campaign finance inquiry in  
1997, appeared upset by Ms. Ingersoll's answers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not talking about trying to electrocute someone,''  
Thompson said. ``We're talking about getting ... to an independent 
magistrate. It does not have to be a smoking gun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Parker testified that Ms. Ingersoll told the agents the  
department ``would not take into consideration'' evidence involving 
President Clinton's legal defense fund and obstruction of the 
Senate's investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith, the retired FBI supervisor, told the committee he was  
``quite astounded at the type of documents being destroyed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The committee released a memo by Smith, dated Aug. 4, 1997, to  
Freeh that bitterly complained about the prosecutors. He expressed 
``a lack of confidence'' in department attorneys, adding, ``I am 
convinced the team at DOJ leading this investigation is, at best, 
simply not up to the task.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The impression left is the emphasis on how not to prosecute  
matters, not how to aggressively conduct investigations leading to 
prosecutions,'' the memo said. 
</P>
<P>
	Reno said the current head of the campaign finance task force,  
David Vicinanzo, ``is phasing out'' of the job and officials are 
discussing his replacement, but she denied the task force is 
winding down. ``The investigatory mechanism is still ongoing and we 
will follow every lead,'' Reno said today. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990923.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 16:20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rite Aid To Close Utah Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Rite Aid Corp. plans to close a Utah  
distribution center in mid-2000, cutting 500 jobs, the company 
announced Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials for drugstore chain said they are shifting their West  
Coast distribution network to a new, 1-million-square-foot facility 
in Lancaster, Calf. The new building will serve almost 1,000 
stores, including the 450 now reached by the Ogden facility that's 
been closed. 
</P>
<P>
	Rite Aid managers met with their 500 Ogden employees Thursday to  
explain the planned shutdown and present them with severance 
packages, which include incentives for people who agree to work 
until they are released from their positions. 
</P>
<P>
	The shutdown will begin in March 2000 and continue into the  
middle of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Rite Aid, based in Camp Hill, Pa., has posted a disappointing  
financial performance in the past year, including a 39 percent drop 
in quarterly earnings reported in March. 
</P>
<P>
	Some analysts have predicted the company will sell several  
hundred of its West Coast stores, which, along with the Ogden 
distribution center, were acquired from Thrifty Payless in 1996. 
Overall, Rite Aid has 4,000 stores in 30 states. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
