<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senior PGA's Baiocchi Seeks Victory  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MASON, Ohio (AP) -- Hugh Baiocchi is still looking for his first  
victory of 1999 as he begins defense of his title in the Kroger 
Senior Classic on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had a pretty good year last year with wins here and at  
Indianapolis, but since then I've been kind of out and about,'' 
said the South African, who spent his career playing the PGA 
European Tour. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been in the final threesome on a few occasions,'' said  
Baiocchi, who is 18th on the money list. ``But last week I didn't 
hit the ball very well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He tied for 20th at Dallas, where Tom Watson won his first  
Senior Tour championship. When Baiocchi got to The Golf Center 
north of Cincinnati, he spent two hours on the practice tee with 
his caddy and a video camera. 
</P>
<P>
	``I picked up on a couple of things, and maybe that will help,''  
Baiocchi said. 
</P>
<P>
	But he figures he's a long shot to repeat as champion.  
</P>
<P>
	``There's enough pressure in the game without putting that on  
myself, although having won on the course once makes you know it's 
a course that suits your game,'' Baiocchi said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I was to repeat, it would be something that would really  
surprise me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Kroger Classic has never had a repeat winner.  
</P>
<P>
	This is the 15th consecutive week of competition for Baiocchi,  
and the grind is taking a toll. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel a little mentally tired,'' he said. ``I'm going to play  
one more week, and then I certainly will need a break. 
</P>
<P>
	``But then, all it takes is a couple of birdies early in the  
round to get the adrenalin going and the juices flowing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baiocchi is among five South Africans on the senior tour, and  
two have won the Kroger Classic. But Baiocchi doesn't travel in the 
same circle as Simon Hobday, the 1993 winner known for his drinking 
and storytelling. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a wonderful fellow -- we played golf together 30 years ago  
-- but he's a party guy,'' Baiocchi said. ``We don't have similar 
interests.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baiocchi won last year's Kroger Classic in a playoff when the  
final day was rained out and five players were tied at 133 after 
two rounds. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
