<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Victim in L.A. Attack Goes Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A 5-year-old boy rode a fire truck home from  
the hospital Thursday, six weeks after he almost died when he was 
shot in a gunman's assault at a Jewish community center. 
</P>
<P>
	Benjamin Kadish wore a helmet and a badge that said ``Junior  
Firefighter'' as he rolled up to the balloon-decorated walkway of 
his West Hills home in the San Fernando Valley. 
</P>
<P>
	``He gave the horn a blast and the siren to announce to the  
neighborhood that he was home,'' fire Capt. Steve Ruda said. 
</P>
<P>
	Benjamin had been hospitalized since the Aug. 10 attack that  
wounded three boys, a teen-age girl and a woman at the North Valley 
Jewish Community Center. 
</P>
<P>
	White supremacist Buford O. Furrow surrendered to the FBI in Las  
Vegas the day after the attack. He faces attempted murder charges 
in that attack and is charged with the murder of a 
Filipino-American postman the same day. 
</P>
<P>
	Benjamin was the most seriously wounded and the only one still  
hospitalized. 
</P>
<P>
	``He had no blood pressure, no pulse'' and was in ``the most  
critical condition you could possibly be in,'' recalled Dr. Charles 
Deng, an emergency room physician at Providence-Holy Cross Medical 
Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Although he may require additional surgery, authorities said the  
boy is making a remarkable recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we're finally starting to come out of a dream, but the  
dream is actually good now,'' said his father, Charles Kadish. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
