<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> J. Bush Pushes Vouchers to Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation can save failing public schools  
while giving parents the option of pulling their children out of 
them, Florida Gov. Jeb Bush told a congressional budget panel 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``There should be zero tolerance for failure,'' said Bush, whose  
state is the first to provide vouchers that can be used for private 
and parochial schools. ``Parents who have their children in these 
failing schools ought to be given other options.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``And there must be meaningful and undiluted accountability. We  
should not just write off failing schools as someone else's 
problem,'' Bush told the House Budget Committee -- which was accused 
by some groups as using the hearing to float a federal voucher 
plan. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ya'll up here call them vouchers. I don't like the ``V'' word  
because the ``V'' word is used in politics,'' Bush said, touting 
his ``opportunity scholarships,'' which pay for students at some 
low-performing schools to attend private or parochial schools. 
</P>
<P>
	Though similar proposals died in the Senate, the House has  
always found a majority willing to entertain the idea of federal 
public funds for private schooling. 
</P>
<P>
	But Education Secretary Richard Riley on Thursday blasted the  
idea: 
</P>
<P>
	``There's the belief that all you have to do to fix public  
schools is to leave them behind and subsidize private education 
instead, that there is some kind of parallel universe of superior 
private schools ready to take on the job of educating 46 million 
public school students,'' Riley said in his testimony. ``Well I'm 
here to tell you that there is no such parallel universe. The only 
way to fix the public schools is to fix the public schools, not to 
abandon them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Rush Holt, a New Jersey Democrat, criticized Republican  
funding of education: ``The House leadership has had a rhetorical 
support of education, but there has been little in the way of 
actual support. You need only look at this year's flat funding for 
the education budget.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, who chairs the budget panel, said  
plans like Florida's. '' are able to rescue the public education 
system, by giving a failing school the resources -- and time -- 
necessary to right itself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under the state law Bush signed in June, schools are graded on  
an A-to-F scale based mostly on students' state test results in 
reading, math and writing. Students in schools graded F for two out 
of every four years are to qualify for vouchers of up to $4,000 to 
attend qualifying public, private, or religious schools. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, 78 schools with 61,000 students, got F's. But just  
two previously troubled schools were chosen for the voucher plan. 
Bush said that the 134 children who used the vouchers had a range 
of skill levels, debunking the theory that vouchers take the best 
students from public schools. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reaction to our plan has been fun to watch,'' said Bush,  
adding that failing schools get funds for after-school programs, 
class-size reduction and extended-year schooling. ``You have 
dramatic reform in schools where children have not been learning as 
well. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's brother, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, a presidential  
hopeful, also created a stir in the education community when he 
proposed giving federal money for poor children directly to their 
parents. Parents unsatisfied with their schools could use the money 
for tutoring, or toward a public or private education. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeb Bush noted he also gives those schools that get an A grade  
incentives up to $100 per student to spend as they see fit, but 
some education and civic groups also blasted the plan, charging it 
violates church-state separation laws and takes needed public funds 
from public schools. 
</P>
<P>
	As for a pending lawsuit by the NAACP and the state teachers'  
union aimed at eliminating the program, Bush said, ``I'm not a 
lawyer. I'll leave that to the lawyers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the hearing Thursday, Bush also asked Congress to free states  
from he called cumbersome federal regulations attached to education 
funding. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have 7 percent of the budget coming from Washington, yet  
40 percent of the staff is trying to comply with your wishes,'' he 
said. ``That's 40 percent of staff that is not focused on making 
sure every child gets a year's worth of knowledge in a years' 
time.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
