<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> A's, Orioles Split Doubleheader  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Albert Belle hit four doubles and Derrick May  
homered in a five-run fourth inning as the Baltimore Orioles beat 
the Oakland Athletics 12-4 Thursday night to gain a split of their 
doubleheader. 
</P>
<P>
	In the opener, Miguel Tejada hit the last of Oakland's four home  
runs, a tiebreaking shot in the eighth inning, and the A's ended 
the Orioles' 13-game winning streak with a 9-6 victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Matt Stairs and Randy Velarde homered in the nightcap for the  
A's, who moved within 4 1/2 games of Boston in the AL wild-card race. 
Toronto beat the Red Sox 7-5. 
</P>
<P>
	Stairs, Ben Grieve and Mike Macfarlane homered in the opener for  
Oakland. 
</P>
<P>
	Belle hit his 36th home run in the opener and for an encore tied  
a major league record with four doubles in a game for a second 
time. But Baltimore failed in its bid to tie the franchise record 
of 14 straight wins, set in 1973. 
</P>
<P>
	There was one bit of good news for the Orioles: Cal Ripken  
underwent back surgery in Cleveland, and general manager Frank Wren 
said he expected the third baseman to be on the field for opening 
day in April. 
</P>
<P>
	The doubleheader was a makeup of two games washed out last week  
by Hurricane Floyd. The A's traveled from Oakland and will move on 
to Texas on Friday; the Orioles, who came from Texas, left for 
Boston after the doubleheader. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles broke open the nightcap by scoring five unearned  
runs in the fourth inning after an error by third baseman Olemedo 
Saenz. Belle hit a two-run double and May followed with a three-run 
drive to right off Omar Olivares (15-11). 
</P>
<P>
	After Stairs hit his 37th homer off Matt Riley in the fifth to  
make it 7-4, Baltimore added an unearned run in its half following 
a throwing error by Jimmy Haynes. Belle doubled in a run in the 
sixth and Calvin Pickering hit a two-run homer for an 11-4 lead. 
</P>
<P>
	Brady Anderson hit his 24th homer for the Orioles in the  
seventh. 
</P>
<P>
	Baltimore starter Matt Riley left with two outs in the fifth  
after issuing his seventh walk and was replaced by Doug Johns 
(6-3), who blanked the A's through the seventh. 
</P>
<P>
	Tejada led off the eighth inning of the opener by hitting the  
first pitch from Gabe Molina (1-2) into the left-field seats to put 
Oakland up 7-6. Jason Giambi then singled in a run with his third 
hit of the game and another scored on a throwing error. 
</P>
<P>
	T.J. Mathews (9-4) worked 1 2-3 innings for Oakland and Jason  
Isringhausen got three outs for his seventh save. 
</P>
<P>
	Oakland's Brett Laxton, recalled from Triple-A Vancouver before  
the game, allowed three earned runs and seven hits in 4 2-3 
innings. 
</P>
<P>
	Baltimore starter Sidney Ponson gave up six runs on 10 hits in 4  
2-3 innings. 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* Oakland finished 34-18 against the AL East and won the  
season series from Baltimore 7-5. ... Macfarlane's homer was his 
third in 213 at-bats this season. ... Ponson, who has struck out 
eight, has allowed at least one home run in 20 of 26 starts. ... In 
the first game, Stairs became the 24th player in the eight-year 
history of Camden Yards to hit a ball onto Eutaw Street beyond the 
right-field scoreboard. It was his 100th career homer. ... Belle 
also had four doubles on Aug. 29 against Detroit. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
