<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Valujet Mechanic Facing New Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- A mechanic charged with allowing mislabeled oxygen  
canisters to be loaded onto a Valujet flight that crashed, killing 
110 people, is on the run and facing new charges, authorities said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	SabreTech Inc. mechanic Mauro Valenzuela has been charged with  
contempt of court for failing to comply with his conditions of 
pretrial release. 
</P>
<P>
	``Valenzuela is presently a fugitive. A warrant has been issued  
for his arrest,'' U.S. Attorney Thomas E. Scott said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Valenzuela, former SabreTech mechanic Eugene Florence and Daniel  
Gonzalez, SabreTech's former vice president of maintenance, are 
charged with conspiracy and making false statements. 
</P>
<P>
	All three were indicted in July. They have pleaded innocent.  
</P>
<P>
	Investigators allege SabreTech took oxygen canisters from  
another ValuJet plane, mislabeled them as empty, packed them up and 
delivered the carton to ValuJet's ramp, where it was loaded aboard 
the May 1996 flight. 
</P>
<P>
	The canisters ignited in the cargo hold of the DC-9,  
transforming the jet into an airborne inferno that nose-dived into 
the Everglades northwest of Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	The three men -- who could face up to 55 years in prison each and  
fines as high as $2.7 million, if convicted -- were permitted to 
remain free on bond. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no response Thursday night to a message left for  
Valenzuela's Miami attorney, Norman Moscowitz, seeking comment. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
