<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NASA Loses Contact With Mars Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- NASA's first interplanetary weather  
satellite failed to re-establish contact with Earth early today 
after it was supposed to complete an engine procedure to place it 
in orbit around Mars. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mars Climate Orbiter, one of two probes scheduled to arrive  
at the red planet this year to study the weather and search for 
evidence of water, should have regained contact with Earth at 2:26 
a.m. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're ... not quite sure what's happening,'' said project  
manager Richard Cook of NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory, a 
half-hour after the signal was to be received on Earth. 
</P>
<P>
	The probe was behind the planet -- and out of radio contact --  
during most of the 17-minute engine firing that should have placed 
it in orbit. Contact should have been established by 2:30 a.m. at 
the latest. 
</P>
<P>
	Mission organizers were scrambling to regain contact and said  
several features aboard the probe were designed to reconnect it 
with Earth in case of a computer shutdown or other common 
spacecraft problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this point, we're still confident we're going to see the  
spacecraft signal in the next few hours,'' Cook said. 
</P>
<P>
	The orbiter and its companion, the Mars Polar Lander, carry  
instruments designed to discover the fate of water believed to have 
once formed rivers or lakes on the planet. Mission scientists say 
water is the key to determining whether life ever existed on Mars. 
</P>
<P>
	The lander, which was launched separately, is due to arrive Dec.  
3. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1,387-pound orbiter was to have fired its main engine early  
today, slowing the spacecraft to 9,840 mph from its interplanetary 
cruising speed of 12,300 mph. Within about a half-hour, the craft 
was to signal that it was not zooming past Mars or plunging to the 
surface. 
</P>
<P>
	The signal takes 11 minutes to cross the 121.9 million miles to  
Earth. 
</P>
<P>
	The craft is supposed to establish an elliptical orbit and then,  
over 45 days, dip into the planet's thin atmosphere and use the 
drag to make its course more circular. 
</P>
<P>
	By mid-November, the probe was to be in a 262-mile-high orbit  
and ready to relay data between Earth and the Mars Polar Lander 
when it arrives a few weeks later. 
</P>
<P>
	Both probes are part of a $327.5 million mission collectively  
known as Mars Surveyor '98, NASA's latest in a series of relatively 
inexpensive robot probes. The orbiter rocketed into space last Dec. 
11 and its sibling probe was launched Jan. 3. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, Mars Pathfinder and its rover, Sojourner, explored the  
geology of the planet and found some evidence that water may once 
have flowed. The Mars Global Surveyor, which arrived later that 
year, mapped the surface and found more signs of once-flowing 
water. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mars Climate Orbiter is equipped with two instruments that  
will be turned on after the probe has finished relaying data from 
the lander. Observations will continue for 687 days -- a full 
Martian year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mars Color Imager will take wide- and medium-angle snapshots  
of the planet's atmosphere similar to an Earth-based weather 
satellite. Another instrument called the Pressure Modulator 
Infrared Radiometer will measure temperatures, dust, water vapor 
and clouds from the Martian surface to above the horizon. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990923.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 12:00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> This Foursome Has Different Meaning  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BROOKLINE, Mass. (AP) -- A man in green pants and Ryder Cup  
souvenir cap was asked what the term foursome means in golf 
competition? 
</P>
<P>
	He turned his head with a puzzled look, and said: ``It's four  
guys, four people, playing a round of golf.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``What else would it mean?'' asked his companion as they watched  
a practice round Thursday on the eve of the Ryder Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Well, the foursome, according to the rules of golf, means two  
teams of two players taking alternate shots with the same ball on 
each hole. The team with the best score wins the hole. 
</P>
<P>
	Such competition was extremely popular in 19th century Britain,  
and there still are courses there where the only option is to play 
in a foursome competition or as a single. 
</P>
<P>
	When golf came to the United States, personal scores were  
preferred and the foursome lost favor, eventually coming to mean a 
group of four golfers. 
</P>
<P>
	But in the Ryder Cup it retains its official meaning and is a  
key to two of the five rounds of competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike the medal competitions of total score over four rounds on  
the pro tour, the Ryder Cup is match play, figured by holes rather 
than total. 
</P>
<P>
	The foursome matches bring the added pressure of hitting a good  
shot so that your partner has a good opportunity on the next. Team 
captains must figure in personalities in setting a foursomes team 
as much as playing styles. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that with the foursomes it's a little more important  
for there to be cohesion between two players,'' U.S. team member 
Justin Leonard said. 
</P>
<P>
	But one never knows if the mix is right on any day.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is one of the beauties and difficulties about trying to  
put together teams because there had been successful teams in the 
past who did not complement each other from a personality or a 
golfwise standpoint,'' Ben Crenshaw, captain of the U.S. team, 
said. ``It's a terribly hard and complex thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of the basic strategic difficulties is selecting who tees  
off on the first hole, for that person will tee off on all the 
odd-numbered holes for the day, and his partner will go first on 
the even-numbered holes. One consideration is to determine which 
set of holes seems to favor a long hitter like Tiger Woods. 
</P>
<P>
	``That plays as much a part as who goes together as anything,''  
Crenshaw said. 
</P>
<P>
	European players generally have more experience at foursomes and  
match play, and this week they practiced alternate shots more than 
the Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	But they all face the same kind of tension.  
</P>
<P>
	``Motivation is not a problem,'' European team captain Mark  
James said. ``I've got to demotivate them so their heads don't 
explode.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The foursomes will be played by four teams from each side Friday  
and Saturday mornings. They will be followed in the afternoons by 
four-ball competitions, whereby two-man teams compete hole by hole; 
the person with the best score on the hole wins it for his team. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, 12 singles matches will be played.  
</P>
<P>
	Ties on any hole are discounted. Scoring for all matches are in  
terms of the number of holes won and those left to play. For 
example, saying a player won 3 and 2 means he was up three holes 
with two to play and could not be tied or beaten. A match is said 
to be ``dormie'' when a player or team is up by as many holes as 
are left to be played. 
</P>
<P>
	One point is awarded for the winning team or individual in each  
competition, with half points to each side when a tie occurs. 
</P>
<P>
	A total of 28 points is available. Europe must only get 14 to  
retain the Cup. The Americans need 14 1/2 to take it away. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
