<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Deficit Plan Spurs Fed Debate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton's controversial 1993 deficit  
reduction program provoked extensive debate among Federal Reserve 
policymakers over what the central bank's response should be, 
according to transcripts made public for the first time Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The transcripts show that Federal Reserve Chairman Alan  
Greenspan conducted a telephone call the day after Clinton unveiled 
his $499 billion program in his maiden speech to Congress on Feb. 
17, 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan, a Republican first appointed to the Fed by Ronald  
Reagan in 1987, was attacked by members of his own party at the 
time for lending valuable support to the new administration's plan 
to attack soaring budget deficits with $246 billion in tax 
increases and $253 billion in spending cuts over four years. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans called the tax increase the biggest in history and  
warned it would push the country into a recession. 
</P>
<P>
	Before Clinton's address, Greenspan had made generally favorable  
comments about the president's resolve to tackle the deficit. He 
lent more support by agreeing to sit next to first lady Hillary 
Rodham Clinton in the House gallery as the president delivered the 
speech. 
</P>
<P>
	The newly released transcripts show Greenspan was careful to  
clear the exact language he would use in discussing specifics of 
the president's program in an appearance Feb. 19 before the Senate 
Banking Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The telephone conference call went on for 16 pages in which a  
number of Fed board members and presidents of regional banks 
offered advice. 
</P>
<P>
	The transcripts show Greenspan assuring his Fed colleagues that  
he would continue to adhere to an approach where he would endorse 
Clinton's overall goal of reducing the budget deficit without 
getting into specifics of how the program should be structured 
between spending cuts and tax hikes. 
</P>
<P>
	``It strikes me that what is evolving here is something that  
could be quite politically bitter and I think it's crucially 
important that we remain basically noncommittal on these various 
issues'' of how the program is structured, Greenspan told his 
colleagues. 
</P>
<P>
	At another point in the conference call, Greenspan expressed  
doubts over whether Clinton's program would be able to pass 
Congress even though both the House and the Senate were then 
controlled by Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	While Greenspan said the program had a chance in the House, he  
said it was likely that Southern Democrats might end up voting 
against Clinton in the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	In the end, the program, considered the major domestic  
achievement of Clinton's first term, passed both houses of Congress 
by a single vote, with no Republicans supporting the measure. 
</P>
<P>
	The transcript of the Feb. 18, 1993, conference call was  
released as part of hundreds of pages of transcripts that were 
released on Thursday of the closed-door discussions of the Federal 
Open Market Committee, the Fed's key policymaking group, composed 
of Fed board members in Washington and the 12 regional bank 
presidents. 
</P>
<P>
	The FOMC meets privately eight times a year for scheduled  
meetings with telephone conference calls conducted in between 
meetings. Summaries of FOMC deliberations are released about six 
weeks after each meeting. Under a reform pushed through Congress by 
a former House Banking Committee chairman, retired Rep. Henry 
Gonzalez, D-Texas, the full transcripts of the meetings are 
released after about five years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990923.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 14:20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Davis Cup Semis Set for Weekend </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Lleyton Hewitt's inaugural Davis Cup year has been one surprise  
after another. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a dream,'' Hewitt said. ``In Zimbabwe (in April) I  
was the hitting partner the whole time. Then there was an injury on 
the team and in Boston I won both my singles matches, so I was 
happy to get away with that. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now there is another injury on the team and Pat (Rafter) is  
out, so I have to step up again, and take a bit of a leadership 
role.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With both Rafter and Mark Philippoussis missing with injuries,  
the 18-year-old Hewitt will lead the Australians against Russia at 
Brisbane, Australia, this weekend in the Davis Cup semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
	The other semifinal, at Pau, France, will pit Belgium against  
France. The winners will meet for the Cup in late November. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, Hewitt will open the best-of-5 series against  
Russia's Marat Safin, 19, in a battle of teen-agers. The second 
match will send Australia's Wayne Arthurs against Yevgeny 
Kafelnikov, who is ranked No. 2 in the world. 
</P>
<P>
	Arthurs, at 29, will be one of the oldest players ever to make a  
Davis Cup debut for Australia. Until now, Arthurs never had been on 
a Davis Cup squad, even as a practice player. 
</P>
<P>
	The doubles on Saturday will send Mark Woodforde and Sandon  
Stolle against Kafelnikov and Andrei Olhovskiy, with the reverse 
singles to be played Sunday, with Hewitt facing Kafelnikov and 
Arthurs playing Safin. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not taking Safin easily,'' Hewitt said. ``It's going to be  
a very tough match. Marat is a bit of a loose cannon once he gets 
out there. If everything is working, he plays well, but he can also 
play a couple of loose games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The France-Belgium match begins Friday with Sebastien Grosjean  
of France playing 19-year-old Xavier Malisse, followed by Frenchman 
Cedric Pioline against Filip Dewulf. 
</P>
<P>
	In Saturday's doubles, Olivier Delaitre and Fabrice Santoro face  
Malisse and Christophe van Garsse, with Sunday's reverse singles to 
follow. 
</P>
<P>
	French captain Guy Forget decided to use the same hard court in  
Pau that was used for the 3-2 quarterfinal win against Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	Pioline is ranked 16th in the world and Grosjean is 30th,  
whereas Belgium's top player, Malisse, is ranked only 98th. 
</P>
<P>
	France knows that rankings don't count for much in Davis Cup  
play. Two years ago, France traveled to Belgium as the Davis Cup 
champion, only to lose 3-2. 
</P>
<P>
	And in the 100th year of the event, Belgium already has upset  
the Czech Republic and Switzerland to earn a berth in the 
semifinals for the first time ever. 
</P>
<P>
	Only the 16 nations that comprise the World Group compete for  
the prestigious cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Also being played this weekend are eight qualifying round  
matches: Czech Republic at Uzbekistan, Germany at Romania, South 
Africa at Britain, Finland at Italy, Netherlands at Ecuador, Spain 
at New Zealand, Sweden at Austria, and Zimbabwe at Chile. 
</P>
<P>
	The winners advance to the World Group for next year's  
competition. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
