<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Details of Vetoed Tax Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Details of the 10-year, $792 billion Republican tax cut package  
vetoed Thursday by President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
 *INCOME TAX 
</P>
<P>
	--A reduction of 1 percentage point in all marginal income tax  
rates between 2001 and 2005. The bottom 15 percent rate would have 
fallen to 14.5 percent in 2001 and 14 percent in 2003, followed by 
a 1 percentage point reduction in all other rates in 2005. Cost: 
$283 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	--To ease the ``marriage penalty'' paid by millions of two-income  
couples, the standard deduction would have been gradually doubled 
over a five-year period, beginning in 2001, for those who do not 
itemize. Also, the income subject to the bottom tax bracket would 
have risen for couples who file jointly in 2005. Cost: $119 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
 *CAPITAL GAINS 
</P>
<P>
	--Individual capital gains rates for most investments held at  
least one year would have been reduced from 20 percent to 18 
percent, or from 10 percent to 8 percent for people paying the 
bottom income tax rate, effective retroactive to Jan. 1, 1999. 
Cost: $32 billion.	
</P>
<P>
 *ESTATE TAX 
</P>
<P>
	--Would have phased out and eventually repealed the taxes on  
inheritance and gifts beginning in 2003, with full repeal in 2009. 
Cost: $65 billion.	
</P>
<P>
 *EDUCATION and HEALTH CARE 
</P>
<P>
	--Health insurance premiums would have been fully deductible  
beginning in 2002 for those who pay more than 50 percent of those 
premiums. In 2000, would have created a new personal exemption 
(worth $2,750 in 1999) for people who care for an elderly relative 
at home. Cost: $42.5 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	--Tax-exempt contribution limits to IRA-like education savings  
accounts would have been expanded from $500 to $2,000 and included 
elementary and secondary school expenses. Interest on prepaid 
tuition accounts for public and private schools would have been tax 
free. Cost: $15 billion. 
</P>
<P>
 *RETIREMENT 
</P>
<P>
	--Contribution limit to all individual retirement accounts would  
have risen from $2,000 to $5,000 a year, from 2001 to 2006. In 
2002, the annual income limit would have gone from $150,000 to 
$200,000 for married couples to contribute to a Roth IRA and to 
convert a traditional IRA into a Roth IRA. Cost: $15 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	--Would have allowed an unspecified deduction for the cost of  
prescription drug insurance for Medicare recipients, contingent 
upon passage of separate Medicare reform bill. No cost estimate. 
</P>
<P>
	--Contribution limits on 401(k) accounts would have increased  
from $10,000 to $15,000 and time accelerated for 100 percent 
vesting in employer-matched pension plans from 5 years to 3 years. 
Cost: $15 billion	
</P>
<P>
 *URBAN ILLS 
</P>
<P>
	--Would have created 20 ``renewal communities,'' including four  
in rural areas, where a variety of tax breaks would have applied 
for businesses that create jobs, clean up former industrial sites 
and take other actions. Cost: up to $2 billion. 
</P>
<P>
 *CORPORATE 
</P>
<P>
	--Research and development tax credit would have been extended  
for five years. Cost: $13.1 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	--Work opportunity and welfare-to-work tax credits would have  
been extended for 2.5 years. Cost: $1.3 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	--Wind and biomass electric credit would have been extended for  
four years and a new poultry waste credit created. Cost: $534 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	--Would have allowed tax break for transfer of money set aside by  
nuclear plants for cleanups and other costs. Cost: $1.1 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	--Reforestation tax break for timber industry would have been  
increased. Cost: $277 million. 
</P>
<P>
	--The 10 percent excise tax on certain fishing tackle boxes would  
have been repealed. Cost: $30 million. 
</P>
<P>
	--The 50 percent limit on corporate tax benefits for overseas  
sales of military equipment would have been repealed. Cost: $1.1 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	--Would have made a variety of international tax law changes,  
including elimination of 35 percent foreign tax credit limit for 
gas and oil extracted overseas. Cost: $1.6 billion. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
