<DOCNO> APW19990923.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 21:10:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Religion in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Theologian Jane Redmont is striding down Fifth  
Avenue at a quick clip as the words come out: ``To get a spiritual 
life, we need to slow down and take some deep breaths.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She knows both the hectic pace of modern life and what she sees  
as a broadly felt yearning to find spirituality. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of us in the contemporary world feel assaulted by the  
speed, the economic pressures, the competition -- and the feeling 
that 'I have to pull myself up by my own bootstraps, make it on my 
own,' '' she said in an interview. ``We're feeling very fragmented, 
and there's a desire to pray with our whole selves, with our heads 
and our hearts, as well as our bodies, our senses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And how, pray tell, does one do that?  
</P>
<P>
	Planting a garden, making love, kneading bread, dancing,  
singing, or even just sitting, breathing and meditating -- all of 
these can be spiritual acts, says Redmont, whose new book, ``When 
in Doubt, Sing,'' explores myriad ways of ``praying'' in the 
angst-filled modern world. 
</P>
<P>
	Her book describes the inner adventures of hundreds of ordinary  
people she spoke with, a spiritual mosaic including mellow 
Californians, Benedictine monks, Zen practitioners, urban 
professionals and small-town Midwesterners. 
</P>
<P>
	The title celebrates music as prayer, which she says helped her  
survive depression. 
</P>
<P>
	Redmont, a 47-year-old Roman Catholic theologian, writes of  
being at a church service ``praying and crying.'' Friends sitting 
on either side noticed, ``reached out and held my hand, wrapped an 
arm around my shoulder, did not ask, simply held me and continued 
to pray, and sing. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was room in the pew for suffering and friendship, for  
praise and lament -- no need to check any part of our lives at the 
door. In this communal acknowledgment, before God, there was hope, 
inside the tears.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Redmont views America's new spiritual landscape from an eclectic  
past. She's a convert to Catholicism, born in France of American 
Jewish parents, agnostics who raised her as a Unitarian 
Universalist. Her brother Dennis is The Associated Press bureau 
chief in Rome. 
</P>
<P>
	A lay minister with a master's from Harvard Divinity School, she  
is finishing a doctorate at the Graduate Theological Union in 
Berkeley, Calif. She worships at a mostly African-American Catholic 
church in nearby Oakland. 
</P>
<P>
	``Prayer in daily life'' -- the book's subtitle -- can be found,  
she says, in countless ways: in the Christian, Jewish or Muslim 
faiths, among others, or through practices like yoga, meditation 
and ritual touch. 
</P>
<P>
	But, she writes, one shouldn't reword the 23rd Psalm as, ``The  
Lord is my shrink, I shall not want.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Simple traditional rituals remain powerful. We're attached to  
``the prayers of grandmothers,'' as one woman in the book calls 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	After the school massacre in Littleton, Colo., the first large  
public gathering was an outdoor Sunday prayer service. It offered 
emotional balm for the victims' families and friends before they 
asked the tough questions about how guns get into children's hands. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need each other, whether it's a group or a large cathedral  
or a small parish or an ashram or a mosque. Find yourself a 'we,''' 
Redmont says. At the precarious edge of the 21st century, ``there's 
an incredible loneliness out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Her theme finds support in others' research and practices.  
</P>
<P>
	Princeton University sociologist Robert Wuthnow, an authority on  
trends in American spirituality, says ``more people in the United 
States pray than actually believe firmly that God exists. Prayer is 
a search, an expression of faith, but also an admission of doubt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Redmont says prayer has other purposes, too. She cites a  
challenge many feel today to ``pray with the actions of our 
lives.'' The late Swiss theologian Karl Barth believed one should, 
so to speak, hold the Bible in one hand and the newspaper in the 
other, she says. 
</P>
<P>
	In Boston, she participated in this ``laying on of hands'' at an  
AIDS healing service. ``An enormous grace of this tragedy is that 
it has taught us how to love in new ways,'' she says. 
</P>
<P>
	While some seeking a spiritual life have returned to religious  
institutions, others shun them, instead finding sacred space in 
activities as simple as listening to music. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are things Mozart has done for me that no amount of  
sermonizing could do,'' Redmont says. 
</P>
<P>
	And the spiritual value of simply walking at a comfortable pace  
while quietly listening to one's thoughts evokes a Japanese 
theologian's phrase: ``There's an immense hunger for 'the 
three-mile-an-hour God.''' 
</P>
<P>
	But there's also a more tangible kind of spiritual hunger,  
according to Harvard theologian Harvey Cox. ``People are looking 
for a kind of usable tradition. And sometimes they just kind of 
give up because it seems too confusing... .'' 
</P>
<P>
	Redmont's contribution, he says, is that ``she is able to  
combine a very serious rootedness in a particular tradition, Roman 
Catholic, with a genuine openness and appreciation for a very wide 
range of styles of spirituality -- without blending them all. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think of her as being very much on the frontier as to how  
things are developing in the religious sphere of the world. She's 
really Catholic and really ecumenical, and it enriches both of 
those sides of her.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
