<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Eulogizes Labor's Kirkland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton eulogized labor leader Lane  
Kirkland as ``a true American hero'' who challenged political 
divisions in his fight for workers' rights at home and abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	``He defied the labels of liberal and conservative,'' Clinton  
said of Kirkland, who was president of the AFL-CIO from 1979 to 
1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Kirkland died of lung cancer last month at age 77.  
</P>
<P>
	Clinton spoke at a memorial service held at Georgetown  
University on Thursday along with Kirkland admirers from across the 
political spectrum -- from Henry Kissinger to Sen. Edward Kennedy, 
D-Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	Kirkland was ``filled with the faith that everyday people can  
change the world,'' said current AFL-CIO president John Sweeney. 
</P>
<P>
	Polish labor reformer Lech Walesa, also in attendance, spoke of  
the importance of the material and moral support that U.S. unions, 
under Kirkland's leadership, gave to Polish workers who ultimately 
won their fight against a communist regime. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would have been impossible without Lane Kirkland,'' Walesa  
said, speaking through a translator. 
</P>
<P>
	Kirkland, who also reunited the major U.S. unions during his  
presidency of the AFL-CIO, clung to the principle that ``the role 
of the trade unions was to try to keep the big guys from kicking 
the little guys around,'' Clinton said, adding, ``Believe me, I got 
my fair share of lectures about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1994, Clinton awarded Kirkland the Presidential Medal of  
Freedom, the nation's highest civilian honor. On Thursday, 
Kirkland's wife Irena accepted on his behalf a similar accolade 
from the Polish government: the Order of the White Eagle. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton told Kirkland's family, ``I am grateful to you for this  
giant of a man, a true American hero, a man who stood up for the 
little guy. I hope all of us can be faithful to his admonition to 
do the same.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
