<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NH Reform Party Cancels Convention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) -- The New Hampshire Reform Party has  
postponed the convention it scheduled here this weekend, 
complaining that advisers to Patrick Buchanan are trying to take it 
over. 
</P>
<P>
	Party spokesman John Talbot said Saturday's convention in  
Manchester was put off indefinitely because Buchanan's advisers 
have been getting too much into the act. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan is said to be thinking about forsaking the GOP and  
seeking the Reform Party's presidential nomination. He won the 
Republican Primary four years ago in New Hampshire, the state with 
the earliest primary. But he has lagged in the polls this time 
around. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been working closely with representatives of the  
Buchanan camp to assure him he will be treated fairly,'' Talbot 
said. ``Unfortunately, some of Mr. Buchanan's senior advisers have 
seen this convention as an opportunity to try to put individuals of 
their choosing into state leadership positions of the Reform Party 
of New Hampshire.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We think it is too soon in the nominating process for any one  
candidate's people to control state leadership positions in our 
organization. It would not be fair to other individuals who might 
seek our party's nomination,'' Talbott added. 
</P>
<P>
	The purpose of the state party is to elect candidates to state  
and local offices and build the party rather than ``seeking to 
elect a single presidential candidate,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Others mentioned as potential Reform Party presidential nominees  
are party founder, Ross Perot, real estate tycoon Donald Trump of 
New York and Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura, highest-elected official 
in the party. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
