<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 16:20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Political Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Democratic National Committee's new  
designated leader has some choice words to describe his Republican 
rivals: ``Decent people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Philadelphia Mayor Edward Rendell officially accepted his  
nomination as general party chairman Thursday by promising a civil 
approach to the 2000 elections. 
</P>
<P>
	``Republicans aren't bad people,'' he said. ``They're decent  
people -- good Americans -- and want the same things for this country 
as we do. We disagree how to reach those goals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton offered him the job Wednesday night and the  
full DNC is expected to sign off Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	He has good reason to sweet-talk Republicans. His city will host  
the 2000 Republican national convention, and Rendell said he will 
maintain his commitments to the GOP -- including raising money for 
their convention. 
</P>
<P>
	He called himself a good friend of GOP chairman Jim Nicholson.  
</P>
<P>
	Rendell also may seek statewide office in 2002 in Pennsylvania,  
an increasingly conservative state where voters may not appreciate 
partisan rhetoric. 
</P>
<P>
	State reporters pressed him about how he would balance his  
duties as mayor. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one in Philadelphia will be shortchanged,'' said Rendell,  
whose term expires in January 2000. And as party chairman, the 
mayor said he will be in a better position to lobby Washington on 
behalf of Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	Rendell was hired to raise money, a response to mounting  
concerns that Republican front-runner George W. Bush's fund-raising 
prowess will bury the Democratic presidential nominee. Roy Romer, 
the party's top spokesman and current general chairman, was moved 
to the 2000 convention staff to make room for Rendell. 
</P>
<P>
	The mayor said his fund-raising goal was to collect ``as much as  
we can legally raise.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Rendell said he will not take sides in the presidential  
nomination race. 
</P>
<P>
	Too late.  
</P>
<P>
	He endorsed Vice President Al Gore long before being considered  
for the party post. 
</P>
<P>
	Trying to make amends as the party boss, Rendell called former  
New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, Gore's only rival and a good friend. 
Yet he was quick to defend Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	Told that Sen. Patrick Moynihan of New York not only endorsed  
Bradley on Thursday but said Gore couldn't get elected president, 
Rendell said Moynihan was ``dead wrong.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Democratic activists have gotten some bad news about rural  
voters. They're turning Republican. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Gersh, a leading party pollster, told DNC members that  
Democratic House candidates were backed by just 38 percent of rural 
voters in 1998, down from 52 percent in 1990 and 48 percent in 
1996. 
</P>
<P>
	The figure was even lower than 1994, a bad year for Democrats,  
when the party's House candidates received 43 percent of the rural 
vote. 
</P>
<P>
	If Democrats had done as well in rural America in 1998 as they  
did in 1994, Republicans would have lost control of the House, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans are appealing to rural voters' concerns about  
declining values in America, Gersh said 
</P>
<P>
	``Democrats tend to do better in rural (areas) ... when voters  
are worried about the economy as opposed to these cultural issues 
that are really vexing to the Democratic Party in rural areas,'' he 
said. ``I think we have suffered from this cultural divide that is 
occurring in this country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In an afternoon-long conference on the topic, the Rev. Jesse  
Jackson said the party needs to make sure more Wall Street 
investment goes to rural America. ``Our mission is to build 
vehicles to transport capital from Wall Street to Appalachia to the 
Delta, to the Bread Basket, and to the fields of Southern 
California. Rural America has money, markets and talent -- but these 
assets are not seen by the national financial community.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	With all the emphasis on 2000, some Democrats are wondering if  
the DNC is paying attention to the handful of 1999 elections -- 
including governor's elections in Kentucky, Mississippi and 
Louisiana. 
</P>
<P>
	Joe Andrew, in charge of the DNC's day-to-day operations, said  
as much money will be spent on the 1999 contests as was spent in 
1995 -- the year before the last presidential election. 
</P>
<P>
	Party officials said more than $1 million was spent on the  
contests in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Though some Democrats say there is little sign yet that the DNC  
is spending as much, Andrew said, ``So far, we have spent the same 
amount as we did in 1995.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	One sign of how much Vice President Al Gore has the DNC in his  
corner: Gore supporters are circulating a party resolution slapping 
down his rival's gay-rights proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	The resolution, which party members meeting in Washington will  
vote on Saturday, essentially disapproves of former New Jersey Sen. 
Bill Bradley's proposal to expand the 1964 Civil Rights Act 
protections to gays and lesbians. Critics warn that opening that 
law to amendment now would give the Republican-led Congress a 
chance to gut its protections against racial, gender and religious 
discrimination. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley is waging an insurgent's challenge to Gore for the 2000  
presidential nomination. On gay rights, Gore supports the narrower 
-- more achievable, he says -- Employment Non-Discrimination Act, or 
ENDA, pending in Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	A draft resolution pushed by Gore supporters at Thursday's DNC  
meetings read: 
</P>
<P>
	``The DNC reaffirms its support of the Civil Rights Act of 1964  
and for ENDA and would urge that the 1964 Civil Rights Act, which 
is the benchmark for all other civil rights bills, not be reopened 
for debate or amendments.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley campaign spokesman Eric Hauser called it ``an  
unfortunate political tactic designed to divide the party.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Bill Bradley's commitment to racial justice is absolute and  
there is nothing that he would ever allow to undermine protections 
for African-Americans,'' Hauser said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
