<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 07:50:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Clash Leave Bench Vacancies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In the long Senate dispute over confirmation  
of President Clinton's nominees to be federal judges, there are 
hostages on both sides now. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats blocked approval of a nominee sponsored by Sen. Orrin  
Hatch, the Republican chairman who presides over the process. They 
insisted that Republicans agree to action on two long-stalled 
appeals court nominees, too. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither side would yield, all three were blocked at the impasse,  
until Senate leaders can agree on a way out. 
</P>
<P>
	So the judging of judges is itself stalled.  
</P>
<P>
	That happened as a bipartisan reform panel complained about  
partisan wrangling in the selection of judges, and said ``it is 
time to lower the temperature of the debate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, it may be going up.  
</P>
<P>
	Behind it is the opposition of GOP conservatives to Clinton  
judges they deem too liberal and likely activists on the bench. 
There has been grumbling on the right that Hatch is too willing to 
lead Clinton nominees through the Judiciary Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The Constitution Project task force on judicial selection urged  
an end to partisan wrangling over judges, and said the whole 
process should be streamlined to avoid extended vacancies on the 
bench. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch said the vacancy rate is 7.6 percent, lower than the  
average. There are 64 judgeships unfilled, and 44 Clinton 
nominations awaiting Senate action. 
</P>
<P>
	They may be waiting for a while. After his nominee was blocked  
Tuesday, Hatch said he was disappointed that the Democrats ``would 
refused to avoid a filibuster of one of the nominees of its own 
administration.'' The nominee, Ted Stewart, was Hatch's choice. 
</P>
<P>
	When Clinton did not nominate him for a Salt Lake City opening,  
Hatch, chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee, stopped holding 
hearings on judicial nominees early this year. He resumed them on 
Clinton's assurance that Stewart, a former Hatch aide, would be 
nominated, as he was on July 27. The committee approved it three 
days later. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the Democrats will not let the Senate vote on Stewart  
without a GOP guarantee there also will be votes on Richard Paez 
and Marsha Berzon, long-held nominees to be appeals court judges in 
California. Paez, first nominated in 1996, and Berzon, named early 
in 1998, have been approved by the committee, but Senate votes are 
being blocked by the anonymous objections of some Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	On party line votes, each side blocked the other from lifting  
the threat of filibusters against the nominations. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch then said he had intended to have the committee hold more  
confirmation hearings this fall, but may not. ``We shall have to 
re-examine the best way to move forward on judicial nominees so 
that we eliminate the double standard,'' he said after the 
Democrats blocked Stewart. 
</P>
<P>
	The Democrats contend the double standard is in the opposite  
direction, that Stewart was moved ahead of 30 nominees awaiting 
confirmation. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House joined the debate on Wednesday, with Clinton's  
spokesman saying the Senate should vote people up or down without 
``preferential treatment for one candidate that they have a 
particular interest in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Press Secretary Joe Lockhart the White House wants to ``work  
through this impasse expeditiously.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That is what the broader dispute is about. Clinton has  
complained at Senate delays he blames for a ``mounting vacancy 
crisis'' in federal courts. Hatch counters that his committee is 
handling nominations fairly and thoroughly. 
</P>
<P>
	Seventeen judges have been confirmed by the Senate this year.  
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Patrick Leahy of Vermont, the senior Democrat on the  
Judiciary Committee, says confirmation delays are dismal and 
getting worse. He said the average time from nomination to 
confirmation of 65 judges in 1998 was more than 230 days. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Constitution Project study showed Clinton delays, too,  
saying the administration has taken an average of 315 days after 
judgeships open to choose nominees to fill them. 
</P>
<P>
	That task force endorsed timetable goals: 180 days for  
presidents to choose judicial nominees, then 60 days for the Senate 
to act. 
</P>
<P>
	But reform studies come and go, with little or no impact.  
</P>
<P>
	Beyond the current snarl, there is no likelihood of a speedup in  
the Senate process in 2000, before the election that could put a 
Republican president in charge of choosing judges. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Walter R. Mears, vice president and columnist  
for The Associated Press, has reported on Washington and national 
politics for more than 30 years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
