<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 14:40:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grace Battling for '90s Hit Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Lou Boudreau. Richie Ashburn. Roberto Clemente.  
Pete Rose. Robin Yount. And in a few weeks, maybe, Mark Grace. 
</P>
<P>
	With 1,742 hits so far in the 1990s and 10 games left, Grace has  
a chance to join the Hit King and the four Hall of Famers on that 
list of decade hits leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to get it. I'd like to get the most hits, the most  
doubles. That'd be nice,'' said Grace, who trailed Rafael Palmeiro 
of the Texas Rangers by one hit before Thursday's games. ``Robin 
Yount was the '80s, Pete Rose the '70s -- that's some pretty good 
company.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's certainly not a group Grace expected to join. He was the  
Chicago Cubs' 24th-round draft pick in 1985, not exactly the place 
where teams find the future of their franchises 
</P>
<P>
	But he won the Midwest League batting title in 1986, hitting  
.342. The next year, he was the Eastern League's MVP with a 
league-high 101 RBIs. On May 2, 1988, he was called up to the Cubs. 
</P>
<P>
	``They probably thought I'd help them in A ball for a couple of  
years and then send me back to San Diego or something,'' Grace 
said. ``My expectations were, `Hey, here's my opportunity and I've 
got to take advantage of it.' Twenty-fourth-rounders don't get the 
breaks that the high picks get. We've got to make our own breaks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had to make it happen and make it happen fast,'' he said.  
``I just drove myself to do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Grace may not have the gaudy numbers of Tony Gwynn, and he  
doesn't have the talent of Ken Griffey Jr. What he does have is 
amazing consistency and a work ethic that constantly drives him. 
</P>
<P>
	He got his 2,000th hit on Aug. 2. He's hitting .300 for the  
ninth time in 11 seasons. He has 1,232 singles and 360 doubles in 
the 1990s, both second-highest in the decade. He's won four Gold 
Gloves. He's only the second Cub to be the opening-day starter at 
the same position for an entire decade. 
</P>
<P>
	On the mornings after a night game, he's one of the first Cubs  
to make the trek across the field to the batting cages. He's 
usually one of the last to leave the clubhouse, sitting around with 
a few teammates to rehash the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's nothing I'm doing that other guys probably aren't  
doing. I just love to play,'' Grace said. ``What drives me is 
competing. The best players in the world, you get to play against 
them every day and that's what drives me. I want to be one of the 
best of the best. That's it, pretty much, in a nutshell.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So what does make Grace such a good hitter? He's got a natural  
swing, teammate Gary Gaetti said. And like Gwynn and Wade Boggs, 
who both reached 3,000 hits this season, Grace watches the ball 
longer than most players, Cubs manager Jim Riggleman said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They stay inside the ball a long time to evaluate ball and  
strike,'' Riggleman said. ``They make good decisions about what to 
swing at and what not to swing at.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Riggleman calls the decade hits record as significant as  
the home run or batting titles, Grace's run at the '90s mark has 
been overshadowed by The Great Home Run Race, Part II. With the 
Cubs so far down in the standings it's not even worth talking 
about, most fans go to games just to see if Sammy Sosa will hit 
another home run. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mark is tied for the most hits in the decade and people aren't  
sticking around to see if he's getting that hit,'' Riggleman said. 
``I don't think that they're quite aware of the magnitude of this 
feat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Added teammate Glenallen Hill, ``I can't put it into words. To  
actually get a major league hit is tough. To put together the most 
hits in the 1990s is just incredible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Equally incredible is that Grace has managed to do it all in one  
uniform. While Sosa may be the heart of the Cubs these days, Grace 
is their soul. He's Mr. Cub of the '90s, right down to the Wrigley 
Field ivy painted on his Harley-Davidson. 
</P>
<P>
	He's played for six managers and watched dozens of teammates  
come and go. He played with Greg Maddux, Rick Sutcliffe, Andre 
Dawson, Shawon Dunston and Ryne Sandberg. Only equipment manager 
Yosh Kawano has been with the Cubs longer. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a little, small fraternity that I'm in, and there's  
some awfully, awfully good players in that fraternity: Gwynn, (Cal) 
Ripken, (Barry) Larkin, Chuck Finley, (Craig) Biggio,'' Grace said. 
``It's not so much one team, it's this team. This is my home. This 
is where I belong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And maybe soon, he'll belong with Boudreau, Ashburn, Clemente,  
Rose and Yount. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
