<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Head Says Relief for Poor Near </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The head of the International Monetary Fund  
said today the 182-nation lending agency is ``within striking 
distance'' of agreement on expanding debt relief to the world's 
poorest countries. 
</P>
<P>
	In a wide-ranging news conference, IMF Managing Director Michel  
Camdessus also defended his agency's handling of billions of 
dollars of loans for Russia, saying that ``nothing has been 
discovered which justifies these allegations'' of Russian 
corruption and money laundering. 
</P>
<P>
	Camdessus met with reporters as his agency and its sister  
lending institution, the World Bank, prepare for their annual 
meetings next week. In advance of those discussions, Treasury 
Secretary Lawrence Summers and Federal Reserve Chairman Alan 
Greenspan will be hosts for a gathering Saturday of finance 
ministers and central bank presidents of the world's seven largest 
economies -- the United States, Japan, Germany, France, Britain, 
Italy and Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	The IMF-World Bank annual meetings are taking place in a vastly  
different environment than a year ago when the sudden collapse of 
the Russian ruble and the near failure of a large U.S. hedge fund 
threatened to trigger a global recession. 
</P>
<P>
	But with the IMF boosting its forecasts for economic growth,  
Camdessus said a major goal of this year's discussions will be to 
continue fighting to implement global financial reforms aimed at 
making future crises less likely. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no room for complacency. This is a time for pushing  
ahead with structural changes,'' Camdessus said. 
</P>
<P>
	Camdessus said he hopes the IMF and major donor countries will  
agree on increasing to $90 billion the debt relief made available 
to 41 of the world's poorest nations, many of them in Africa. 
</P>
<P>
	The complex financing arrangement would involve revaluation of  
14 million ounces of the IMF's huge gold reserves from $47 per 
ounce, the current value on the IMF's books, to world market 
prices, currently more than $250. The extra money would be invested 
and the proceeds of that would be used to finance the IMF's 
contribution to the $90 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are within striking distance'' of an agreement which could  
be announced at the conclusion of discussions on Monday, Camdessus 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	As to allegations of widespread money laundering and corruption  
in Russia, Camdessus said the IMF's own review of its loan program 
with Russia had uncovered no irregularities. 
</P>
<P>
	While the IMF is continuing its review, he indicated the agency  
is prepared to extend the next installment of $4.5 billion in loans 
to Russia this year, since the country is currently exceeding the 
economic requirements the IMF imposed as a condition for getting 
the money. ``Russia is a program that works,'' Camdessus said. 
</P>
<P>
	Camdessus was more critical of another big borrower, Indonesia,  
sayng the IMF program with that country will remain suspended until 
the situation in East Timor stabilizes and the Indonesian 
government produces a report answering allegations of corruption at 
the Bank of Bali. 
</P>
<P>
	``We hope the authorities will soon release the documents (on  
the Bank of Bali) and allow us to continue with our work,'' 
Camdessus said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said that the  
United States had won approval from other nations for creation of a 
new Group of 20 -- consisting of rich nations and developing 
countries who will meet regularly to review economic reform 
proposals. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to creation of the new group, the G-7 officials are  
expected to review a recent sharp drop in the value of the dollar 
in relation to the Japanese yen, including a discussion of whether 
the G-7 countries should intervene jointly in currency markets to 
bolster the U.S. currency. 
</P>
<P>
	The IMF, issuing an updated economic forecast, predicted the  
global economy will expand by 3 percent this year and 3.5 percent 
in 2000, but it cautioned that a sudden plunge in either the U.S. 
stock market or the dollar could derail this forecast. 
</P>
<P>
	World Bank President James Wolfensohn told reporters Wednesday  
that IMF and World Bank officials have already launched an effort 
to coordinate their activities more closely to respond to criticism 
during the past two years when the lending institutions worked to 
assemble more than $100 billion in support during the global 
currency crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a major step forward and our contribution to reforming  
the international financial architecture,'' Wolfensohn said. ``It's 
also an answer to people who say we should be merged or fired or 
closed down.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
