<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Price Stabilization Proposed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Costa Rican President Miguel Angel Rodriguez  
urged steps to stabilize oil prices Thursday, saying wide 
fluctuations serve the interests of neither producers nor 
consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	In a speech to the Organization of American States' permanent  
council, Rodriguez suggested that the OAS take a lead role in 
achieving this goal. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodriguez spoke in the presence of other leaders from Central  
America and the Caribbean. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is necessary that the major oil producers adjust their oil  
production quotas to avoid the possibility that prices become 
prohibitively high for many countries without provoking an 
unreasonable price decrease.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He recommended creation of a system of ``bands'' within which  
prices could fluctuate. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the price closed in on the upper limit, the producers would  
automatically increase production, and it would be cut back if the 
price neared the lower limit,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodriguez expressed concern that price increases resulting from  
production cuts by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting 
Countries seriously damaging the economies of small, poor 
countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``These countries should unite to work for the common good and  
offer help to those which are most needy and not accumulate 
fleeting fortunes at the cost of misery for many,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
