<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> A&AMP;M Was Right Choice for Receiver </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLLEGE STATION, Texas (AP) -- Chris Taylor had a choice: he  
could go to Rice and continue playing quarterback, or he could go 
to Texas A&AMP;M and switch to wide receiver, a position hardly 
prominent at a school known for defense and running backs. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, he chose the Aggies and spectacular results followed.  
</P>
<P>
	He's been on a tear since catching an 81-yard touchdown pass  
that helped the Aggies beat Nebraska last season and he's off to a 
dramatic start this season as a key figure in No. 5 A&AMP;M's sudden 
passing success. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a lot to be said about confidence,'' offensive  
coordinator Steve Kragthorpe said. ``He made that big play at 
Nebraska and his confidence level took off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Taylor has caught nine passes for 235 yards in two games this  
season. He has two TD catches, including a school record 96-yarder 
last week against Tulsa. 
</P>
<P>
	``Since that game at Nebraska, my confidence has skyrocketed,''  
Taylor said. ``Before, I had doubts that I was cut out to be a 
receiver. After that, the confidence took off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Aggies' (2-0) newfound offensive weapon will get its biggest  
test Saturday against Southern Mississippi (2-1), which uses a 
scrambling and confusing defense that almost got the Golden Eagles 
an upset of No. 6 Nebraska last week before losing 20-13. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know that Southern Mississippi is good,'' Taylor said.  
``Any team that can hold Nebraska within seven points in Lincoln 
has to be good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Taylor was an all-around athlete at Madisonville High School. He  
played defensive back, quarterback, running back and kicker. He 
lettered in football, baseball, basketball and track and was a 
state qualifier in the 100-meter dash. 
</P>
<P>
	The Aggies were most attracted to his combination of speed and  
pass-catching ability. 
</P>
<P>
	``The big thing in me coming to A&AMP;M was being close to home with  
Madisonville just 40 minutes away,'' Taylor said. ``I could have 
stayed at quarterback and gone to Rice but I came to A&AMP;M. I don't 
get hit as much now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Quarterback Randy McCown has benefited from the Aggies'  
bolstered passing attack and the addition of receivers like Taylor, 
Chris Cole and Bethel Johnson. Even 265-pound fullback Ja'Mar 
Toombs has two catches this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Chris is a deep threat for us,'' McCown said. ``Our receiving  
corps as a whole has improved. They all want to be the best of that 
group so they're really competing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Aggies offense is ranked second in the nation, a big  
improvement over last season and their improved receiving has been 
a major factor. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd give us a B-minus for last week,'' McCown said. ``It  
sounds goofy with us being ranked No. 2, but I'm not going to say 
we've arrived. We are still not where we need to be on offense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Southern Mississippi's defense has allowed only 40 points in  
three games and held Nebraska to 185 total yards. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
