<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Trade Sanctions Affect U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- American companies are getting a reputation as  
unreliable exporters as a result of trade sanctions that were 
imposed on India and Pakistan after they tested nuclear devices, 
according to a government report. 
</P>
<P>
	The sanctions were triggered in May 1998 after both countries  
conducted underground nuclear tests in violation of international 
agreements. 
</P>
<P>
	The sanctions have had relatively little impact on either  
country or American exports, the U.S. International Trade 
Commission said in a report to be released today by the House Ways 
and Means Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton has temporarily waived restrictions on the use  
of various federal aid, including credits and guarantees for the 
sale of agricultural products. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, according to the trade commission's report, the  
sanctions still ``have contributed to an increased perception of 
U.S. companies as unreliable international suppliers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Embassy in New Delhi reported that the sanctions  
``continue to have a negative impact on U.S. business in India as 
U.S. companies are reluctant to pursue business opportunities 
because of uncertainty over sanctions,'' the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is more proof that unilateral sanctions aimed at other  
countries often have a boomerang effect on U.S. workers and our 
economy,'' said Rep. Phil Crane, R-Ill., ``In this case it was the 
Farm Belt, but who knows what U.S. industry will be next?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The sanctions have cost India $320 million, Pakistan $57 million  
and the United States $161 million, the commission said. 
</P>
<P>
	The study is being released at the same time House and Senate  
negotiators have been debating legislation that would allow the 
sale of food and medicine to Cuba for the first time in four 
decades and make it harder for a president to impose future 
embargoes. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters of trade sanctions say they represent the only weapon  
that the United States has to influence rogue nations. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Lincoln Diaz-Balart, R-Fla., is fighting the trade  
liberalization, saying it would signal a ``basic lack of commitment 
to fight terrorism.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There is more to America than the drive to make money at any  
cost,'' said Diaz-Balart. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
