<P>
 *Methodists back Boy Scouts' appeal    	
</P>
<P>
	NASHVILLE (AP) -- The Commission on United Methodist Men is  
supporting an appeal to the Supreme Court of a New Jersey ruling in 
August that the Boy Scouts of America must allow openly homosexual 
leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission is the liaison with scouting for the United  
Methodist Church, the nation's second-largest Protestant 
denomination. It sponsors 11,738 scout troops, packs and crews. 
</P>
<P>
	The Methodist commission contends that the scouts should have  
the right to choose leaders without government interference. 
</P>
