<P>
 *Mistake could mean deportation    	
</P>
<P>
	CORYDON, Ind. (AP) -- When Frank Audia was a student at a  
Minnesota Bible college, faculty members urged everyone to vote at 
election time. So Audia registered and voted twice in 1994 
elections. 
</P>
<P>
	But he was not a U.S. citizen.  
</P>
<P>
	Now, the 27-year-old youth pastor at Trinity Assembly of God  
Church in Corydon could be returned to his native El Salvador. 
Under federal law, Audia committed a crime worthy of deportation 
even though he says he did not know he was acting illegally. 
</P>
<P>
	Audia came to the United States at age 10 with his mother, went  
to school and attended college at North Central University in 
Minnesota. He was classified as a permanent resident before 
applying for citizenship in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview for citizenship with an Immigration and  
Naturalization Service examiner in Indianapolis, Audia said he had 
voted. Last October, two years after he applied for citizenship, 
the INS told him his request was being denied and, under a 1996 
law, he would face deportation. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Baltimore gets two Lutheran agencies    	
</P>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Two worldwide Lutheran agencies are now  
headquartered in Baltimore. 
</P>
<P>
	Lutheran World Relief and Lutheran Immigration and Relief  
Service, which employ about 70 people, moved into new quarters from 
New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Catholic Relief Services, one of the largest nongovernmental  
agencies providing food and emergency help, moved its world 
headquarters to Baltimore from New York several years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Lutheran World Relief grew out of a church movement in 1945 to  
help Lutherans left homeless by World War II. The agency now works 
in 50 countries each year, with local partners training people to 
produce food, dig wells and restore the environment. It also has a 
continuing effort to rid the world of land mines. 
</P>
<P>
	Jonathan Frerichs, a spokesman for Lutheran World Relief, said  
the agency hopes to launch joint projects with Catholic Relief 
Services. The two agencies already have worked together in North 
Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	Lutheran Immigration and Refugee Service helps people seeking  
asylum, former refugees and children unaccompanied by their 
parents. 
</P>
<P>
	Both agencies are supported by the Evangelical Lutheran Church  
in America and by the Lutheran Church-Missouri Synod. 
</P>
<P>
