<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yankees 5, White Sox 2  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Roger Clemens won consecutive starts for the  
first time in nearly three months and Tino Martinez hit a two-run 
homer as the New York Yankees clinched no worse than a tie for a 
playoff berth with a 5-2 win Thursday night over the Chicago White 
Sox. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees, who have won eight of nine since a four-game losing  
streak, need one more win or an Oakland loss to make the postseason 
for the fifth straight year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees took a five-game lead in the AL East over Boston,  
which lost 7-5 to Toronto. New York's magic number to win the 
division for the third time in four years is six. 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens (14-9), who has struggled with inconsistency in his  
first season in New York, put together his third straight quality 
start (six or more innings, with three or fewer earned runs) for 
the first time this season. 
</P>
<P>
	He followed up a two-run, seven-inning performance against  
Cleveland by allowing two runs and six hits in 6 1-3 innings. It 
was the first time since June 23-29 that he won back-to-back 
starts. 
</P>
<P>
	Mariano Rivera pitched the ninth for his 43rd save in 47  
chances. Rivera has not allowed a run in his last 24 appearances 
(25 2-3 innings) and has converted 20 straight save opportunities. 
</P>
<P>
	Bernie Williams had four hits and Derek Jeter went 2-for-4 to  
raise his average to .351 as the Yankees swept a three-game series 
at home against the White Sox for the first time since May 28-30, 
1993. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees jumped out to a 4-0 lead against Jim Parque (9-14),  
who lost his eighth straight decision. Parque allowed four runs and 
seven hits in five innings and hasn't won in 13 starts since July 7 
against Kansas City. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeter doubled with one out in the first and scored on Williams'  
single. Paul O'Neill added an RBI single in the second and Martinez 
hit his 26th homer in the third. 
</P>
<P>
	The White Sox scored two in the fifth on RBI singles by Brian  
Simmons and Greg Norton to make it 4-2. With runners on second and 
third and one out, Clemens came back to strike out Ray Durham and 
Darrin Jackson. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott Brosius, starting for the first time since leaving the  
Yankees on Sept. 13 for his father's funeral, went 2-for-3 with an 
RBI single in the seventh. 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* Clemens won his 247th game, tying Joe McGinnity and Jack  
Powell for 40th place on the career list. ... O'Neill has 22 RBIs 
in his last 11 games. ... Williams tied a career high with his 
108th run. ... The White Sox turned an odd double play in the 
fourth inning. O'Neill hit a hard shot up the middle that deflected 
off shortstop Mike Caruso's glove and rolled to second baseman Ray 
Durham, who touched second and threw to first for the double play. 
... Chicago's Magglio Ordonez played DH instead of outfield because 
of stiffness in his back and was replaced by a pinch-hitter in the 
fifth inning. ... The Yankees won the season series 7-5. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
