<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Farm Aid Tied Up Over Cuba, Dairy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Farmers counting on cash from Congress to  
balance their books this year may have to wait awhile. Their 
insistence on trading with Cuba and a squabble among dairy 
producers has tied up work on a multibillion dollar package of farm 
aid. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican leaders had agreed to provide $8 billion in  
farm-income assistance and disaster relief, with the money to be 
included in a must-pass agricultural appropriations bill. 
</P>
<P>
	But a House-Senate conference committee writing the final  
version of the legislation abruptly ended their discussions 
Wednesday and did not resume work Thursday because of a stalemate 
over the Cuba and dairy issues. 
</P>
<P>
	House GOP leaders have told the budget negotiators they do not  
want the dairy issue in the bill and will not let the legislation 
out of the House if it weakens the 40-year-old trade embargo on 
Cuba. On Thursday, they offered to add $700 million to the farm 
bailout if the Cuba and dairy matters were omitted, according to a 
congressional source who spoke on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're both big (issues). They're both difficult,'' said Rep.  
Bill Young, R-Fla., chairman of the House Appropriations Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The farm bailout would include $5.5 billion in direct payments  
to growers as compensation for a second year of depressed commodity 
prices and additional money for special crops and weather-related 
losses. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are waiting for Congress to get some hands on cash so  
they can pay their bills,'' said Tom Giessel, a Kansas wheat 
farmer. ``Farmers spend a tremendous amount of money. These local 
economies depend upon that flow and right now there's a real 
bottleneck.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Farm groups are pushing Congress to allow the sale of food and  
medicine to Cuba, but some conservatives and Florida lawmakers say 
they secured a commitment from GOP leaders to block it. 
</P>
<P>
	The dairy dispute involves an Agriculture Department overhaul of  
milk pricing set to take effect Oct. 1. Lawmakers in the South and 
East want to use the spending bill to block the new system and get 
congressional authority for regional price-setting agreements. 
</P>
<P>
	The negotiations on the spending bill were suspended Tuesday  
after farm-state members of the conference committee won a series 
of preliminary votes that indicated they might prevail on the Cuba 
sanctions. 
</P>
<P>
	Young denied rumors being circulated among lawmakers that House  
leaders were threatening Thursday to replace members of the 
conference committee or else add anti-Cuba lawmakers. ``That might 
have been thrown out by somebody as an option but there was no 
serious thought given to that,'' Young said. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither side on either issue gave any sign of giving ground  
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously what we have is a stalemate,'' said Jose Cardenas,  
Washington director for the Cuban American National Foundation, 
which backs the trade embargo. Farm groups ``are holding the whole 
thing hostage to some very dubious economic potential.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Jo Ann Emerson, a Missouri Republican pushing the Cuba  
trade measure, said ``the issue of sanctions is critical. ... We 
desperately have to have every market open to our producers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The deadlock killed any chance, however slim, that Congress  
could get the farm aid spent before the 1999 fiscal year ends next 
Thursday. That would have made it easier to balance the 2000 budget 
without dipping into the Social Security surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	This was not the first time the spending bill has been delayed.  
Work on the bill was halted in late June when Senate Democrats 
tried to attach some controls on HMOs. 
</P>
<P>
	Midwest Democrats are blaming Republicans for the latest holdup.  
They downplayed the importance of the dairy issue -- milk producers 
in their states generally support the USDA's new pricing system -- 
and insisted the main problem was on Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have a few right-wing ideologues in the House aiming at  
Castro and hitting our farmers,'' said Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
