<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Conn. Treasurer Guilty in Scheme </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- A former state treasurer pleaded guilty  
Thursday to accepting an estimated $106,000 in kickbacks -- some of 
which turned up in his failed election campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Silvester was paid ``finders fees'' by the financial firms  
that he selected to invest the state's pension funds. 
</P>
<P>
	``He used his authority as state treasurer to invest money not  
solely in the best interest of the funds, but to guarantee wealth 
for himself, his friends and his colleagues,'' U.S. Attorney 
Stephen Robinson said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Silvester, 37, who lost a November election 17 months after  
being appointed to the post, pleaded guilty to racketeering and 
money laundering charges and faces up to 40 years in prison and a 
$750,000 fine. 
</P>
<P>
	His brother Mark Silvester, 50, pleaded guilty to conspiracy to  
solicit and accept corrupt payments and could get five years. His 
brother-in-law, Peter Hirschl, 43, pleaded guilty to conspiracy to 
launder money and faces up to 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	All three were released on $10,000 bond. Sentencing was  
scheduled for March 20. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Silvester admitted he had his brother divvy up some of the  
money and dole it out to political supporters. Those supporters 
then used the money to write $1,500 campaign contribution checks, 
prosecutors said. Prosecutors said Mark Silvester used his share of 
the kickbacks to buy a powerboat and paint his home. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Silvester's attorneys said he would have no comment.  
</P>
<P>
	``He has betrayed the public trust, he has betrayed the  
Republican party and he has betrayed people that have run on the 
ticket with him,'' said Gov. John G. Rowland, who appointed 
Silvester to his position after the previous treasurer resigned. 
</P>
<P>
	The financial firms involved were not named in the indictment  
because the investigation is ongoing, Robinson said. He would not 
comment further. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
