<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 13:10:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sen. Faces Harassment Allegations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HELENA, Mont. (AP) -- In 1994, as the sexual harassment scandal  
that forced Bob Packwood from the Senate heated up, Sen. Max Baucus 
stepped forward to endorse a bill that would make Congress subject 
to the same workplace laws as businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is high time for Congress to play by the same rules it sets  
for other Americans,'' the Montana Democrat said in support of what 
would become the Congressional Accountability Act. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, five years later, his former top aide is about to use that  
law to accuse Baucus himself of sexual harassment. 
</P>
<P>
	Christine Niedermeier is expected to file a grievance with  
Congress this week alleging the four-term senator fired her as 
chief of staff for shunning more than a year of sexual advances. 
Baucus has vehemently denied any sexual harassment. 
</P>
<P>
	A grievance could lead to Ms. Niedermeier's receiving damages  
for lost wages and getting her job back. If the case goes to court, 
she could also demand punitive damages. 
</P>
<P>
	The allegations came out after Baucus fired Ms. Niedermeier in  
August for what he said was a brutal management style that made 
work intolerable for his staff. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Niedermeier, 47 and single, said Baucus never touched her  
improperly. But she said the 57-year-old married man began hitting 
on her shortly after she went to work for him in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Baucus would comment frequently on her appearance in front of  
others, and quiz her about her boyfriends and her dates, she said. 
He asked her to take weekend trips together and compared her with 
his wife, Wanda, Ms. Niedermeier said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last October, she said, the senator asked her to accompany him  
on a trip to San Diego around her birthday. She refused and he was 
disappointed, later questioning her about her personal life, she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was expressing a form of jealousy that I spent my birthday  
with someone else,'' she said. ``I was first embarrassed and 
blushed, then I tried to make light of it. I gave him every 
possible signal I could to let him know I wasn't interested.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baucus has refused to comment on the particulars of  
Niedermeier's allegations but said: ``Let me state, unequivocally, 
that I have never, under any circumstances, sexually harassed 
Christine Niedermeier.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baucus said he fired Ms. Niedermeier after being confronted with  
a revolt by staff members fed up with her belittling and abusive 
treatment. He said 36 of 39 staffers signed a petition complaining 
about her. Several employees threatened to resign. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reason I let her go was basically because of the way she  
was mistreating my staff,'' Baucus said. ``I'm angry that she has 
abused my staff for such a long period of time and in such a 
harmful and hurtful way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Former Baucus employees flooded reporters with horror stories  
about working for Ms. Niedermeier and praise for Baucus. And 38 
female former employees signed a letter defending Baucus as a ``man 
of highest integrity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I resigned because of Ms. Niedermeier,'' said Jan Metzmaker,  
former field director for one of Baucus' offices in Montana. ``It 
was way too stressful. It was too difficult to work for her and be 
sane and have a family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Baucus, an anthropologist, painter and writer who is the  
senator's second wife, has been married to him for 16 years. She 
has dismissed Ms. Niedermeier's accusations and stood by her 
husband. 
</P>
<P>
	``If there was any doubt in my mind at all, it would be creating  
problems, but it's not,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The law Ms. Niedermeier is expected to invoke was passed in  
early 1995 in the middle of the scandal over allegations that 
Packwood had sexually harassed more than two dozen women, many of 
whom had worked in his Senate office. The Oregon Republican 
resigned in late 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Baucus apparently never commented publicly on the  
scandal, he did vote for public hearings by the Senate Ethics 
Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, he said he supports the complaint process  
created by the law and dared Ms. Niedermeier to use it. ``If she 
believes that I sexually harassed her, then she should lay her case 
out on the table -- and under oath,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Niedermeier, a two-time congressional candidate in  
Connecticut, said she is willing to do that to salvage her 
reputation. She said her delay in filing a complaint is due to 
reservations about the confidential nature of the Senate process, 
not a reluctance to speak under oath. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one would ever want to lie about this,'' she said. ``Why  
would I want to lie about something that would damage, if not 
destroy, my career?'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
