<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kohler Settles Labor Dept. Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KOHLER, Wis. (AP) -- Kohler Co. has agreed to pay $886,500 to  
more than 2,000 women who were refused jobs because they were too 
short. 
</P>
<P>
	The plumbing fixture company agreed to settle a Labor Department  
lawsuit accusing Kohler of gender discrimination for a company 
practice of hiring only workers who were at least 5 feet 4 inches 
tall. 
</P>
<P>
	The rule was intended to make sure employees could handle  
physical labor, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The height restriction was not gender-specific; it's just that  
women tend to be shorter,'' Kohler spokesman Ed Allmann said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the effect was to keep women out of higher-paying jobs and  
thus qualified as discrimination, said Bernard E. Anderson, 
assistant labor secretary and head of the Employment Standards 
Administration. 
</P>
<P>
	The $886,500 in back pay, benefits and interest covers more than  
2,000 women who applied for machine operator positions and other 
jobs at Kohler between January 1994 and December 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the agreement, Kohler will hire 111 of the applicants and  
fund a three-year study on making jobs safer and eliminating 
barriers to women. 
</P>
<P>
	``The company did not have a policy on height requirements,  
however remnants of outdated past practices at one plant 
unfortunately had remained in place pertaining to heavy 
manufacturing areas,'' said Laura Kohler, a vice president at the 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	``Improvements in manufacturing processes lessened the need for  
minimum height considerations,'' she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
