<HEADLINE> Defendant Cleared in Agent Slaying </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- The first of three Mexican nationals  
charged in the slaying of a U.S. Border Patrol agent was acquitted 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	On the second day of deliberations, jurors cleared Manuel Gamez  
in the death of Alexander Kirpnick, who was shot to death in a 
remote canyon area near Nogales on June 3, 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Gamez, 28, could have gotten the death penalty if convicted.  
</P>
<P>
	The jury did find Gamez guilty of four charges related to  
marijuana smuggling. He faces up to 30 years in prison at 
sentencing. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other suspects -- Bernardo Velarde Lopez and Luis Enrique  
Arenas Hernandez -- await trial on the same seven charges as Gamez, 
which include murdering a federal officer, murdering an officer 
during a drug crime and conspiracy to import marijuana. 
</P>
<P>
	Velarde and Arenas will not face execution because the Mexican  
government extradited them on the condition they be spared the 
death penalty. 
</P>
<P>
	Kirpnick, 27, was shot through the temple and died hours later  
at a hospital after he and his patrol partner tried to chase down a 
group of suspected drug smugglers. 
</P>
<P>
	Gamez was arrested the same day while walking along a trail. He  
told authorities he was paid $400 to smuggle a marijuana-filled 
duffle bag across the border and ran when he saw someone he thought 
was an immigration agent. 
</P>
<P>
	Gamez said he heard a shot about 40 seconds after he started  
running and he was not the shooter. 
</P>
<P>
	``We felt all along he was innocent,'' said Victoria Brambl,  
Gamez's attorney. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
