<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Prices Fall Further in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Consumer prices fell 6.1 percent in August,  
compared with the same month a year earlier, but spurred a sorely 
needed spurt in consumer demand, the government said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong's prices have dropped for 10 consecutive months as the  
territory seeks ways to boost its economy, which slumped in the 
Asian crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices fell 5.5 percent in July. The government attributed much  
of the latest decline to a fall in private housing rents. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong consumers also paid less for eating out and for  
supermarket goods. Clothing and shoe prices fell a dramatic 25.6 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Lower prices contributed to an 8 percent decline in the value of  
retail sales in July, compared with July 1998, to $2 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	But cheaper prices boosted consumer demand, with retail volume  
rising 1 percent. It was the first increase since September 1997, 
before the Asian crisis hit the territory, the Census and 
Statistics Department said in a statement. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990923.0227 </DOCNO>
