<HEADLINE> NY Man on Trial for Punching Horse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A man has gone on trial for allegedly punching a  
police horse during a protest rally. 
</P>
<P>
	James Hornacek, 35, of Hazlet, N.J., denies that he hit the  
horse Daily News One during a June 1998 protest rally. The 
electrician claims the 19-year-old gelding came at him while he was 
marching and that he merely put his hands up to protect himself. 
</P>
<P>
	He is charged with obstructing government administration,  
disorderly conduct and attempting to injure a police animal. The 
charges carry a maximum one year in jail. 
</P>
<P>
	Hornacek was among thousands of construction workers trying to  
march to a construction site where non-union workers reportedly 
were on the job. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said that when mounted police moved in to stop the  
demonstrators from impeding traffic, Hornacek refused to move. 
Instead, Hornacek punched the horse in the nose and repeatedly hit 
it in its hindquarters. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
