<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft To Spin Off Expedia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	REDMOND, Wash. (AP) -- Microsoft announced Thursday that it is  
spinning off its Internet travel reservation service, Expedia, as a 
separate company, and that it had filed with the Securities and 
Exchange Commission for an initial public offering of stock. 
</P>
<P>
	The spinoff is the latest move by the software giant to  
capitalize on the Internet. It will give investors a chance to 
focus on just one aspect of Microsoft's business and could bring in 
as much as $75 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, Microsoft announced a joint venture with Ford  
that will upgrade Microsoft's CarPoint automobile sales site on the 
Web to allow consumers to order specific new Ford cars and trucks. 
</P>
<P>
	Expedia is one of the leading travel sites on the Internet,  
allowing customers to book airline tickets, hotel rooms and other 
travel needs. 
</P>
<P>
	Since going online in October 1996, Expedia has had gross  
bookings of more than $700 million by more than 860,000 customers, 
the SEC filing said. 
</P>
<P>
	Expedia Inc. said in the filing that the worldwide travel  
industry ``is especially well-suited to benefit from increased 
Internet and electronic commerce adoption.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It cited a Forrester Research finding that travel has already  
become the largest online retail category with estimated 
transactions of $7.8 billion in 1999, and growth forecast to reach 
$32 billion in 2004. 
</P>
<P>
	Following the stock offering, Expedia will become a separate  
company but will have a contractual relationship with Microsoft, 
which will be its majority owner. Money raised in the stock 
offering will be used for working capital and general purposes, the 
SEC filing said. 
</P>
<P>
	Analyst Scott McAdams, president of McAdams Wright Ragen in  
Seattle, said the stock offering could be another way to reward -- 
and retain -- employees who might be tempted by huge stock gains at 
other Internet companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think one of the challenges for Microsoft has been to keep  
the talent from being hired away by other dot-com companies in the 
Northwest and elsewhere,'' McAdams said. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft stock is valuable, but ``it's not in the stratosphere  
like a lot of Internet companies are,'' McAdams said. 
</P>
<P>
	Expedia had revenues of $38.7 million and losses of $19.6  
million for the fiscal year ended in June. Such losses are common 
for Internet startups, which still attract investors convinced they 
are buying a stake in the future. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Microsoft can spin off Expedia and get a very fat  
evaluation on it, it'll be cheap currency to grow their business 
with,'' McAdams said. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the Expedia spinoff, Microsoft on Thursday  
released details of how it plans to revamp MSN.com Web gateway with 
a new online shopping service and a Web site to help small 
businesses use the Internet to attract new customers. 
</P>
<P>
	MSN, which began life in the mid-1990s as the Microsoft Network,  
has been frequently modified as technology and competition changed 
business on the Web. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft shares fell $4.87 1/2 to $91.18 3/4 Thursday as part of a  
sharp selloff on Wall Street, fueled in part by a warning from 
Microsoft President Steven Ballmer that technology stocks are 
overvalued, including those of his own company. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
