<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Aug. Federal Deficit $2.51 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The federal government recorded a budget  
deficit of $2.51 billion in August but the government is still on 
track for posting a big surplus this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Treasury Department said Wednesday that last month's budget  
deficit was smaller than the $11.17 billion deficit reported in 
August 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	In August, government outlays totaled $128.8 billion, while  
receipts totaled $126.3 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Government receipts from individual income tax payments in  
August came to $60.7 billion, following $59.9 billion the month 
before. Corporate income tax payments totaled $3.7 billion last 
month, compared with $3.4 billion in July. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first 11 months of fiscal 1999, which began Oct. 1,  
1998, the government has posted a surplus totaling $66.60 billion, 
up from the $31.82 billion surplus for the same period last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration, in its midyear economic forecast,  
projected that the surplus, which totaled $69.2 billion in 1998, 
will climb to $98.8 billion in the current fiscal year, which ends 
Sept. 30, and $142.5 billion in 2000. Congressional accountants had 
predicted a surplus of about $120 billion for all of 1999, but 
recently said it would fall ``a few billion short'' of that 
estimate. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the government enjoyed its first budget surplus since  
1969. Assuming administration projections for this year come 
through, this will be the first back-to-back surpluses since Dwight 
Eisenhower was president in 1956 and 1957. 
</P>
<P>
	The July surplus of $25.16 billion was not revised by the  
government, the Treasury Department said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
