<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NY Mayor Nixes Money for Exhibit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Brooklyn Museum of Art may lose $7 million  
in city funding unless it cancels an upcoming exhibit featuring 
mutilated pigs, a dung-splattered painting of the Virgin Mary and a 
portrait of a child killer. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor Rudolph Giuliani vowed Wednesday to cut off annual support  
for the museum if it goes ahead with October's exhibit. 
</P>
<P>
	``If somebody wants to do that privately and pay for it  
privately, well, that's what the First Amendment is all about,'' 
said Giuliani, a Republican who is considered a potential U.S. 
Senate candidate for 2000. ``But to have the government subsidize 
something like that is outrageous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The mayor is the latest -- and loudest -- voice in a a  
wide-ranging crowd opposing the upcoming ``Sensation: Young British 
Artists From the Saatchi Collection.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The collection -- 90 pieces by 42 different artists -- was already  
under fire from Catholic groups and animal rights activists. 
</P>
<P>
	The Catholic League was incensed by Chris Ofili's ``The Holy  
Virgin Mary,'' a painting of the religious icon splattered with 
elephant dung. The People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals were 
upset by the exhibit ``This Little Piggy Went to Market, This 
Little Piggy Stayed Home,'' which features a dissected pig floating 
in formaldehyde. 
</P>
<P>
	Likely to anger others was Marcus Harvey's painting ``Myra,'' a  
13-foot rendering of a British child killer created from children's 
hand prints. 
</P>
<P>
	The museum has acknowledged that ``Sensation'' is R-rated, and  
said no one under 16 will be admitted unless accompanied by a 
parent. The exhibit is scheduled to open Oct. 2. 
</P>
<P>
	The much-hyped collection drew 300,000 visitors when it debuted  
at London's Royal Academy in 1997; three academy members resigned 
in protest when it opened. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to cutting off monthly funding, the city also  
suspended talks on a proposed $20 million capital expansion project 
for the museum. 
</P>
<P>
	Last June, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled that the federal  
government can opt not to subsidize art it considers indecent. That 
flap, involving the National Endowment for the Arts, began over 
funding of homoerotic images by photographer Robert Mapplethorpe 
and Andres Serrano's photograph of a crucifix immersed in urine. 
</P>
<P>
	Museum director Arnold Lehman, in today's New York Times, said  
``it is the museum's job to support the right of artists to express 
themselves freely.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New York Civil Liberties Union head Norman Siegel sided with the  
museum, calling Giuliani's threat to yank funding ``heavy-handed 
and inappropriate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Once the government, using public funds, punishes artists to  
suppress unpopular views, we are heading down a dangerous First 
Amendment road,'' Siegel said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
