<HEADLINE> CEO Arrested in Vietnam Sex Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- An electronics executive was arrested on  
charges he paid the family of a 13-year-old Vietnamese girl more 
than $150,000 to have sex with her in Vietnam, federal authorities 
said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael David Rostoker, 41, of Boulder Creek, was taken into  
custody at San Francisco International Airport on Wednesday as he 
was about to board a flight for Vietnam. 
</P>
<P>
	Rostoker, an engineer and patent attorney, is president and CEO  
of Microelectronics Research Inc., of San Jose. 
</P>
<P>
	Also arrested was Tri Roy Cole, 40, of San Jose. He was being  
held for investigation of aiding and abetting Rostoker. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities allege Cole, originally from Vietnam, arranged the  
liaison between Rostoker and the girl in exchange for an 
undetermined amount of money. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said Rostoker traveled on ``numerous occasions'' to  
Vietnam this year to have sex with the minor. Rostoker was in the 
process of arranging false papers for the girl so he could bring 
her into the country to live with him, authorities said. 
  	   	
</P>
