<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Police Defuse Large Bomb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Police discovered an explosive device set to blow  
up in the basement of a 12-story apartment building in western 
Russia, averting what could have been another in a string of deadly 
bombings that have terrorized Russia in recent weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Police did not say whether there was a link between the device,  
found Wednesday night in the city of Ryazan, and four apartment 
bomb blasts that killed some 300 people in Moscow and two other 
Russian cities this month. The device found in Ryazan and the 
location were similar to the earlier attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	The apartment bombings have been blamed on Islamic militants  
from breakaway Chechnya, who have twice invaded the neighboring 
region of Dagestan in southern Russia since the beginning of 
August. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities in Ryazan were alerted by a resident of the building  
who claimed to have seen people hauling large sacks from a car 
whose license plates were covered up, the ITAR-Tass news agency 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the Emergency Situations Ministry, the sacks  
contained sugar mixed with the explosive hexogen -- the material 
that police say was used in the previous blasts. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities found the explosives, with a timer set to go off at  
around dawn, and evacuated everyone from building. The device was 
safely defused, the ministry said. 
</P>
<P>
	Security has been stepped up around the country following the  
apartment bombings. People have been asked to alert authorities if 
they spot any unusual activities, unattended bags or other 
suspicious objects. 
</P>
<P>
	Police also have been raiding warehouses, apartment building  
basements and other nonresidential property, searching for 
explosives. 
</P>
<P>
	Police have found two stockpiles of explosives during raids in  
recent days in the restive southern region of Stavropol, near 
breakaway Chechnya, the ITAR-Tass news agency reported. Three more 
caches of explosives were found earlier in the region, the report 
said. It didn't say where the explosives were found, or specify the 
type. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a small explosion hit an elevator in an apartment  
building in northwest St. Petersburg on Wednesday. No one was hurt 
and no damage was reported, Emergencies Ministry spokesman Oleg 
Semionog said. Officials said it was likely a prank. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have no reason to qualify it as a terrorist act,'' Semionog  
said. ``No one would have noticed except that people's tensions are 
very high.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A poll conducted before the latest discoveries showed that 49  
percent of Russians believe the government hasn't done enough to 
prevent new bombings, and an overwhelming 86 percent of Russians 
said they expected more terrorist bombings. 
</P>
<P>
	Only four percent believed the bombings were over, according to  
the poll by the independent Regional Political Research Center. The 
survey had a margin of error of 2 percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	The Islamic militants, who have been blamed for the bombings,  
were driven out of Dagestan by Russian troops in heavy fighting, 
but smaller cross-border clashes have continued. Government troops 
were digging in along the border with Chechnya to prevent possible 
new attacks, and Russian jets bombed suspected militant bases 
inside the breakaway region. 
</P>
<P>
	Forty-nine percent of Russians approved of the air raids, while  
36 percent objected, according to the poll. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990923.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 08:23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Seeks Support From Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Yasser Arafat is looking for more support from  
one of his principal boosters, President Clinton, while American 
efforts to engineer a land-for-peace deal between Israel and Syria 
stumble. 
</P>
<P>
	At 70, Arafat is determined to see a Palestinian state  
established in his lifetime, either through negotiations with 
Israel that are now under way or unilaterally, if the talks fail to 
produce his desired results. 
</P>
<P>
	He also wants its capital in Jerusalem.  
</P>
<P>
	Clinton already has publicly endorsed Palestinian  
``aspirations,'' a thinly coded allusion to statehood, has declared 
that Palestinian refugees have the right to live wherever they 
wish, and blocked transfer of the U.S. Embassy from Tel Aviv to 
Jerusalem, which would have strengthened Israel's claim to the city 
as its eternal capital. 
</P>
<P>
	Arafat wants assurances Clinton will intervene if negotiations  
with Israel falter, and he wants promises of U.S. financial support 
and the kind of ties the United States usually reserves for 
established governments. 
</P>
<P>
	Arafat warmed up for his session today at the White House with  
Clinton with a meeting Wednesday night in New York with Secretary 
of State Madeleine Albright, who helped pull off a new agreement 
this month with Israel that gives the Palestinian Authority more 
land on the West Bank where Arafat intends to establish a state. 
</P>
<P>
	Arafat and the Clinton administration are pleased that Israel's  
promise to pull back is being implemented ``to the letter,'' 
Albright said, ``and I think he wants to give his assessment to the 
president about where things are going.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that he has obviously assessed the possibilities that  
are open,'' Albright told reporters in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, looking to his legacy, is hoping to preside at an  
overall Israeli-Palestinian accord and also one on the Syrian 
track. 
</P>
<P>
	Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa told Albright on  
Wednesday that his country remained interested in peace talks with 
Israel, but only on its terms for regaining control of the 
strategic Golan Heights. 
</P>
<P>
	He informed reporters that U.S. mediators had not found a  
formula to reopen negotiations. There is no breakthrough, he said. 
``I think progress has not been achieved yet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Albright said ``no one meeting is pivotal'' and that she would  
see al-Sharaa again while he is in New York attending the special 
session of the U.N. General Assembly. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is an intention to move forward on both sides. There is  
a seriousness of purpose that gives us a reason to push on with 
this,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Syria wants Israel to acknowledge that negotiations broken off  
three years ago should resume with an Israeli promise to relinquish 
all the land Syria lost in the 1967 Mideast War, along with a 
three-mile stretch that was once part of British-mandated 
Palestine. 
</P>
<P>
	That would advance Syria to within reach of the Sea of Galilee  
and its treasured water supply. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright, neither endorsing nor rejecting Syria's demands, said  
Damascus had taken this position ``over and over again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Syrian minister said the United States was serving as a  
go-between, holding talks with both sides in an attempt to narrow 
differences before negotiations could be reopened. 
</P>
<P>
	Al-Sharaa said the late Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin had  
agreed to relinquish the territory, and that his successor, Shimon 
Peres, had concurred. The moment Israel acknowledges that 
commitment, Syria is ready to negotiate peace and security terms, 
al-Sharaa said. 
</P>
<P>
	Syria has taken this position consistently. It is not clear  
where Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak stands, although he has 
spoken of a desire to retain certain areas on the lower slopes of 
the Golan, where some of Israel's water sources lie. 
</P>
<P>
	When he was Israel's top general, Barak said retaining the Golan  
Heights was essential for Israel's security. But as a minister in 
the Rabin and Peres governments, he supported their overtures to 
swap the high ground overlooking northeastern Israel for a solid 
peace treaty. 
</P>
<P>
	After his election in May, Barak said Israel was ready for  
``painful compromises,'' suggesting a willingness to pull back 
without saying specifically from all of the Golan Heights, 
especially near the shores of Galilee. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright subscribes to the idea that Israel should give up land  
for peace on the Syrian front as well as with the Palestinians. But 
she has not taken a position on how much. 
</P>
<P>
	Al-Sharaa said the United States was completely aware of  
Israel's commitment, and ``they can try to bridge the gap between 
the two sides.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Albright is due to meet with the Israeli foreign minister, David  
Levy, in New York on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	She also met Wednesday with the Egyptian foreign minister, Amr  
Moussa, and urged his government to lend support to cooperation on 
water supplies, economic development, curbs on weapons and on other 
topics between Israel and the Arab countries. 
</P>
<P>
	On the golf course, at the Camp David presidential retreat in  
Maryland, even after a funeral procession in Morocco, Clinton has 
made more than a dozen private contacts with Middle East leaders in 
recent months to push the peace process along, aides say. 
</P>
<P>
	The aides, reconstructing conversations that have been kept  
private, say the president made 10 telephone calls to Barak and 
Arafat as they worked out their revised West Bank agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton counseled both sides ``to try to get them to understand  
each other and to deal with one another in a way that overcame the 
years of distrust,'' said a White House official familiar with the 
conversations. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990923.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 23:40:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 2nd Supremacist Gets Death Penalty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRYAN, Texas (AP) -- White supremacist Lawrence Russell Brewer  
once told his prison cohort that a life sentence for a vicious hate 
killing would do ``no justice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A jury agreed Thursday, sentencing the 32-year-old career  
criminal to death for the June 7, 1998, dragging death of James 
Byrd Jr., 49. 
</P>
<P>
	Brewer's former prison pal, John William King, 24, is already on  
death row, convicted and condemned in February for murdering the 
black man, who was chained by his ankles to a pickup truck and 
dragged to his death 15 months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	A third man, Shawn Allen Berry, also 24, awaits a capital murder  
trial next month in his hometown of Jasper, where the killing took 
place. 
</P>
<P>
	Brewer wrote in a jailhouse letter to King that the two of them  
had become stars and that he was a ``hero of the day.'' In the same 
note, introduced as evidence and written after the two were 
arrested for Byrd's murder, Brewer mused that a lethal injection 
would be a ``little old sleeping medicine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both met in prison where they joined the Confederate Knights of  
America, a racist group, and adorned themselves with racist 
tattoos. 
</P>
<P>
	The death sentence for Brewer came as a relief to prosecutors,  
who weathered two days of deliberations and what appeared to be a 
near-miss for the punishment they sought. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not a death penalty fan,'' Jasper County District Attorney  
Guy James Gray said. ``But this is a situation where if you don't 
give the death penalty to this man, he'll hurt and kill again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A life sentence seemed close for Brewer, when the jury sent a  
note in their 13th hour of deliberations indicating they were 
unable to reach a conclusion for the third and final question they 
were tasked with answering: whether there were any mitigating 
circumstances to spare Brewer's life. 
</P>
<P>
	To reach that point, the jury had already answered affirmatively  
that Brewer planned to kill Byrd and was a future danger to 
society. State District Judge Monte Lawlis instructed the jurors to 
continue deliberating unless they were ``unequivocally'' certain 
they could not reach a unanimous decision, which is required to 
hand down the death penalty. 
</P>
<P>
	Less than an hour later, they had.  
</P>
<P>
	``They took their time looking for some mitigating  
circumstances, but they weren't going to find it,'' said Byrd's 
sister, Mary Verrett, as she hugged police and prosecutors just 
after the verdict. ``They dug for it. But there are no mitigating 
circumstances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The jury's answer was not a shock to Brewer, his lead attorney  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Russell had resigned himself to this,'' said Doug Barlow.  
</P>
<P>
	Brewer's family, speaking before the verdict came down, had also  
prepared for the worst. 
</P>
<P>
	``My son has been convicted of a horrible, horrible crime. I  
don't excuse his actions, though I honestly believe that when he 
took the stand he told the truth,'' Lawrence Russell Brewer Sr., 
Brewer's father, wrote in a statement. ``If he gets the death 
penalty, I can accept it. I know it would be God's will.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two hours after the punishment verdict, Brewer, in shackles and  
wearing an orange jail jumpsuit, was in the backseat of a silver 
police car for the 50-mile trip east to death row in Huntsville. 
</P>
<P>
	With a second death penalty secured, Gray said he is looking  
forward to trying Berry's case in late October. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got a lot of work to do on Shawn Berry's case. We're not  
exactly sure where it's going right now. He doesn't have the racist 
background King and Brewer did, none of the tattoos.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
