<HEADLINE> Texas Church Holds Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- Members of a church that lost seven  
parishoners to a gunman returned to their scarred sanctuary for the 
second service since the shooting last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Church member Chip Gillette, the first police officer on the  
scene after the shooting, displayed a hymnbook that stopped a 
bullet. 
</P>
<P>
	He said at the gathering Wednesday that the slug stopped at the  
words: ``He shall reign forever and ever, that he is Lord of Lords 
and King of Kings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Chills went up my spine 'cause I said, 'Lord, show me  
something out of that,''' Gillette said, ``and he said, 'I am Lord 
of Lords and King of Kings and I will reign forever; I will have 
this victory out of that, Chip.''' 
</P>
<P>
	The gunman, Larry Gene Ashbrook, killed himself after opening  
fire on Sept. 15 during a service at Wedgwood Baptist Church. 
</P>
<P>
	The church is still being repaired. Bloodstained carpet was  
pulled up, leaving bare floors, and blood-splattered pew cushions 
were carried away. 
</P>
<P>
	Medical examiners released test results Wednesday that showed  
Ashbrook, 47, had not been drinking or taking drugs. Police 
initially said Ashbrook might have taken anti-depressants but later 
said they were mistaken. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
