<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Couple Arrested in Minister's Murder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADISONVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Nancy Petty remembers her brother,  
the Rev. William Petty Jr., warning her not to pick up hitchhikers. 
But she said the man who strived to help others failed to follow 
his own advice. 
</P>
<P>
	It may have cost him his life, investigators say.  
</P>
<P>
	Nathan Hass, 30, was hitchhiking near Chattanooga when he  
accepted a ride from Petty, clubbed the 56-year-old minister with a 
piece of wood, set his body on fire and fled, investigators said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hass and his wife, Denise, 29, were arrested outside of St.  
Louis, Mo., early Wednesday and charged in the slaying. 
Investigators believe robbery was the motive. They also believe 
Mrs. Hass didn't participate in the murder. 
</P>
<P>
	``I truly hope they will be put away,'' Nancy Petty said. ``I am  
working on forgiveness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The couple were arrested after they called one of their  
relatives in North Carolina and the relative contacted police, 
Monroe County Sheriff Doug Watson said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The (Hass) family members were concerned that they were  
involved in this atrocious murder,'' said Tennessee Bureau of 
Investigation Agent Richard Brogan. ``They didn't want to see them 
running.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hass has been charged with first-degree murder, car theft and  
felony murder. Mrs. Hass is charged with accessory to arson. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel the minister just picked up this guy,'' Watson said.  
``We have no evidence of premeditation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Petty's body was discovered Saturday night burned beyond  
recognition on his property in the foothills of the East Tennessee 
mountains near the North Carolina line. 
</P>
<P>
	The weapon and clothing had been piled on top of him then set on  
fire. His car was found burned two days later about 30 miles away 
near Andrews, N.C., where the Hasses lived. 
</P>
<P>
	Hass is accused of using the stolen car to pick up his wife. The  
two then fled in her car, investigators say. 
</P>
<P>
	Hass has served prison sentences in North Carolina on several  
drunken driving and other motor vehicle charges, Brogan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Petty, who lived in Ooltewah, was a lawyer in Chattanooga for 30  
years, then left his practice to become a United Methodist 
minister, leading five small, struggling congregations in the Meigs 
County area. 
</P>
<P>
	``My brother was the type who would help out anyone,'' Nancy  
Petty said. ``We are very devastated.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
