<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kathie Lee Line Faulted on Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Former football star Frank Gifford defended  
his wife, Kathie Lee Gifford, during a heated Capitol Hill news 
conference Wednesday where labor activists said her clothing line 
is still produced in foreign sweatshops. 
</P>
<P>
	Gifford told members of the National Labor Committee that his  
wife was working hard to improve conditions at the factories and 
said he was unhappy the group released its findings before 
discussing them with her. 
</P>
<P>
	``Frank got kind of personal,'' Bob Adler, chairman of the  
Kellwood Co. division that licenses the Kathie Lee line, said after 
the confrontation. ``Frankly, she's the only celebrity who's 
stepped up to the plate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Charles Kernaghan, head of the National Labor Committee, said he  
told Gifford he was sorry Mrs. Gifford had become the brunt of talk 
show jokes and other criticism. But that discomfort cannot be 
likened to the plight of the sweatshop workers who earn as little 
as 50 cents an hour, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is nothing in comparison to the lives of the hundreds of  
thousands of young women locked in factories throughout the world, 
behind barbed wire and armed guards, who are stripped of their 
rights and paid starvation wages and who go home to one-room hovels 
without running water and raise their children on coffee because 
they can't afford milk,'' Kernaghan said after the news conference. 
``That is a real problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gifford said his children are sometimes driven to tears by  
people who criticize their mother even though she has devoted her 
life to standing up for human rights and the rights of children. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not nice to have people make fun of you,'' Kernaghan  
said. ``But she still comes home to a mansion in Connecticut and 
they're doing just fine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Three years after Kathie Lee Gifford pledged to help end labor  
abuse in the apparel industry, her own inspectors are looking into 
claims that thousands of Salvadoran women still endure brutal 
conditions to produce clothing for her line, sold through Wal-Mart, 
the National Labor Committee said. 
</P>
<P>
	Committee officials brought to Washington two employees who said  
they were fired after speaking up for workers' rights at a factory 
producing Kathie Lee clothing in Santa Ana, El Salvador. 
</P>
<P>
	The women described 11-hour, six-day work weeks in sweltering  
conditions for a base wage of 60 cents an hour. Workers were 
subjected to physical and verbal abuse and forced to work overtime 
and undergo unwanted pregnancy tests, Kernaghan said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need the jobs,'' said Blanca Ruth Palacios, 43. ``We are  
willing to work hard, but we want them to respect our rights.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Adler said monitors sent to the Caribbean Apparel factory in  
Santa Ana could not immediately substantiate the accusations. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're still trying to get to the bottom of these very serious  
allegations,'' Adler said. ``The controversy continues, but we are 
making progress. We want to get this thing solved.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, Mrs. Gifford released a statement expressing concern  
over the allegations. If they prove to be true, she said, ``we will 
not allow that facility to continue manufacturing goods bearing my 
name.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
