<HEADLINE> Asian Markets Close Mostly Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian markets closed mostly lower Thursday in  
the absence of fresh-market moving news, with the large Tokyo 
market closed for a national holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	But Hong Kong, the region's second largest, rose after a three  
day decline on selective buying in technology stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	The blue-chip Hang Seng Index rose 26.82 points, or 0.2 percent,  
to end at 13,214.44. On Wednesday, the index fell 1.7 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology stocks continued to rally on the back of gains on the  
technology-heavy Nasdaq, which gained 1.31 percent Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The market also got a bit of encouragement as the yen slowed its  
rise, since Japan's markets were closed for Autumnal Equinox Day. 
</P>
<P>
	In late afternoon trading, the U.S. dollar bought 103.77 yen,  
down 0.51 yen from late Wednesday in Tokyo and also below its New 
York level of 104.08 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Seoul was also on holiday, while Taipei remained closed for the  
third day after the island's worst earthquake this century. 
</P>
<P>
	ELSEWHERE:   	
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Shares hit a six-month low on a weakening baht. The SET  
index shed 9.69 points, or 2.4 percent, to end at 400.46. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Shares fell on heavy selling after police and students  
clashed outside parliament. The JSX Composite index fell 17.276 
points, or 3.2 percent, at 528.172 points. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Shares plunged 2 percent as investors cashed in on  
gains. The Composite Index was down 14.08 points to close at 
707.09. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Shares rose with Internet company Creative Technology  
surging on news of a joint venture with U.K.-based Cable and 
Wireless. The Straits Times Index rose 0.74 points, or 0.06 
percent, at 2,068.40. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Shares rose on optimism over the government's plan to  
cut corporate taxes. The All Ordinaries Index rose 25.60 points, or 
0.8 percent, at 2,927.30. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Shares dropped on Wall Street's losses. The PSE Index  
was down 12.87 points, or 0.6 percent, to close at 2,094.86. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: Shares dropped despite gains in heavyweight Telecom  
Corp. of New Zealand. The NZSE-40 Capital Index fell 1.15 points, 
or 0.05 percent, at 2,063.83. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
