<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.C. Utility Workers Called Heroes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENVILLE, N.C. (AP) -- When flooding from Hurricane Floyd  
covered a Greenville Utilities substation last Friday and blacked 
out all 56,000 people in town, Malcolm A. Green and his crew took a 
risk. 
</P>
<P>
	Green, the general manager, decided to use a circuit breaker  
outside the station. That put the power back on, but everything 
would have been shot if the rising Tar River, which runs through 
the middle of the city, reached the main cables. 
</P>
<P>
	A utility worker stationed in a boat provided constant reports  
on the water level. Flood waters came within 2 inches Wednesday but 
then went down. 
</P>
<P>
	So even though the substation was still under about 9 feet of  
water Thursday, Greenville had electricity. The waterlogged and 
weary utility workers who made it happen during the worst flooding 
ever to hit the state are being called heroes. 
</P>
<P>
	``The key thing I would say is that our customers had power all  
this time,'' Green said. ``We had people here doing work, basically 
untested, stuff that most people would say, `You can't do that.' 
But we found a way to make it work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wachovia Bank had prepared for Floyd by bringing in generators.  
It never needed them, thanks to the hard work of the utility crew. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've done an outstanding job, especially taking a  
significant amount of risk to keep everybody going as best they 
could,'' said Richard Jones, a bank executive. ``We're mighty proud 
of them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Utility employees also worked all weekend to protect the city's  
water and sewage plants. 
</P>
<P>
	They joined with volunteers and jail inmates to frantically  
stack 25,000 sandbags and formed a 6-foot wall around crucial 
equipment outside. They also stacked sandbags around indoor 
equipment and pumped water back outside, using hoses through the 
windows. 
</P>
<P>
	The city never had to shut off its water system, although  
clogged filters led to low pressure that caused thousands to be 
without water. But by Thursday, the system was close to normal 
after the utility finished cleaning the pipes. 
</P>
<P>
	Residents were still being urged to boil water before drinking  
it due to river contamination from raw sewage, chemical spills and 
dead animals. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been here 29 years, and that's my water system right  
there. Those pipes are mine,'' said Wayne Bryant, Greenville 
Utilities superintendent of water and sewer, who worked 100 hours 
in seven days. ``I'm not losing my pipes.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
