<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Sept. 23, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Republican $792B Tax Cut Vetoed  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton vetoed the Republicans' $792  
billion tax cut bill today, saying the measure ``would force 
drastic cuts'' in education and health care and would ``cripple'' 
the government's ability to pay down the national debt. In a remark 
echoed by GOP colleagues, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, 
R-Miss., said, ``I regret the president has stolen this tax cut 
from working American families.'' It appeared highly unlikely that 
Republicans would accept Clinton's suggestion to send him a smaller 
tax bill, in the $300 billion range that he had proposed. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Falls 205.48 on Interest Rate Fears  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks plummeted today as investors sold heavily  
amid continued worries about higher interest rates and the strength 
of the dollar. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 205.48 to 
close at 10,318.59, marking a 4.5 percent decline for the Dow over 
the past three sessions. Leading technology stocks took hits today 
after Microsoft president Steve Ballmer said at a conference that 
technology stocks -- including Microsoft -- are too highly priced. 
The Nasdaq composite index fell 108.33 to 2,749.83, its 
fourth-biggest decline ever. 

</P>
<P>
	NASA Spacecraft Disappears Near Mars  
</P>
<P>
	PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- For the second time in six years, a NASA  
spaceship was lost just as it reached Mars. The $125 million Mars 
Climate Orbiter, which was on a mission to study the planet's 
weather and look for signs of water, traveled 416 million miles 
before vanishing today as it was about to go into orbit around the 
Red Planet. The spacecraft apparently flew too close to the Martian 
atmosphere and broke apart or burned up, the space agency said. The 
$1 billion Mars Observer probe disappeared in 1993. 

</P>
<P>
	Dragging Defendant Sentenced To Die  
</P>
<P>
	BRYAN, Texas (AP) -- A jury decided today that racist ex-convict  
Lawrence Russell Brewer should pay with his life for the dragging 
death of a black man, sending him to death row to join an 
accomplice in the crime. James Byrd Jr., 49, was chained at the 
ankles to a pickup truck and dragged to pieces in the East Texas 
town of Jasper last year. John William King, 24, is already on 
death row, convicted in February in the murder of Byrd. A third 
man, Shawn Allen Berry, 24, goes on trial next month. 

</P>
<P>
	Moynihan Endorses Bradley for President  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- New York's most prominent Democrat, Sen. Daniel  
Patrick Moynihan, endorsed Bill Bradley for president today, saying 
Vice President Al Gore ``can't be elected.'' Bradley served three 
terms as a New Jersey senator, working with Moynihan -- who was 
first elected in 1976 -- on the Senate Finance Committee. At Gore's 
campaign headquarters, communications director Kiki Moore suggested 
Moynihan's imprimatur would make little difference: ``I'm sure 
President Bob Kerrey appreciated (Moynihan's) support in 1992.'' 

</P>
<P>
	400 Richest in U.S. Amass $1 Trillion  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The 400 richest Americans for the first time  
have collectively amassed $1 trillion, a figure greater than the 
gross domestic product of China, according to Forbes magazine, 
which issued its annual ranking of the nation's wealthiest people 
today. Microsoft Corp. chairman Bill Gates once again led the list 
with a net worth of $85 billion, up from last year's $59 billion. 

</P>
<P>
	$8.2B Utilities Merger Announced  
</P>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The corporate parent of Chicago's  
Commonweath Edison is merging with PECO Energy Co. of Philadelphia 
in an $8.2 billion deal that would create the nation's largest 
electric utility. Together, Chicago's Unicom Corp. and PECO control 
almost 20 percent of the country's nuclear generating capacity. 

</P>
<P>
	Actor George C. Scott Dead at 71  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- George C. Scott, the forbidding-looking,  
gravel-voiced actor who turned in an Oscar-winning performance as 
the profane and patriotic Gen. George S. Patton, and then declined 
the honor, has died at 71. Scott died yesterday of a ruptured 
abdominal aortic aneurysm. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Fall in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks fell in early trading Friday after  
a sharp decline on Wall Street. The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei 
Stock Average shed 363.90 points to 16,961.86 in the first 30 
minutes of trading. 

</P>
<P>
	Jordan's Restaurant Becomes Sosa's  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Michael Jordan's Restaurant will become Sammy  
Sosa's Restaurant, a move prompted by declining sales at the 
basketball star's eatery just north of downtown Chicago, said H. 
Gene Silverberg, a controlling partner in both restaurant ventures. 
Jordan apparently stopped eating at the restaurant after the owners 
rejected his ideas for making it more upscale, Silverberg said. 
Sosa donned a chef's hat at a news conference today to announce the 
restaurant and even swung a 4-foot-long red fork. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRAD FOSS  






  	   	
</P>
