<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Fall; Dow Down 20.26 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell today as investors found little  
reason to step back into a market battered by the dollar's weakness 
against the yen and continued fears of higher interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	In midday trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial  
average was down 20.26 at 10,503.81. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's  
500 index was down 5.91 at 1,304.60, and the Nasdaq composite index 
was down 18.81 at 2,839.35. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no new fundamental reason for the weak market, but  
there's a great deal of nervousness,'' said William Meehan, chief 
market analyst for Cantor Fitzgerald. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors remained unwilling to snap up stocks even as the  
dollar inched higher against the yen in New York. In late morning, 
the dollar was quoted at 104.01 yen, up from 103.93 yen late 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the U.S. currency is lingering near its lowest levels  
against the yen since 1996. The dollar's weakness has contributed 
to a sharp decline in U.S. stocks this week, pushing the Dow down 
nearly 300 points in the past two sessions. A weaker dollar makes 
imports more expensive, setting the stage for inflation. It also 
makes foreign investments more alluring. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks were also held back by a Labor Department report that  
showed the number of Americans filing new claims for unemployment 
benefits fell unexpectedly last week to the lowest level in 25 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	The extremely low U.S. jobless rate has fostered fears that  
companies will have to increase wages and benefits in order to 
attract skilled workers. That, too, could set the stage for a 
revival of inflation. Some economists believe any evidence of wage 
pressures will persuade the Federal Reserve to raise interest rates 
when its Open Market Committee meets Oct. 5. 
</P>
<P>
	United Technologies held the Dow lower, falling 1 1/16 to 57  
9/16, after announcing plans to eliminate 14,500 jobs -- or 10 
percent of its worldwide work force -- over the next three years 
because of a downturn in the aerospace industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading in technology stocks was stimulated by the merger of two  
Internet service providers, EarthLink and MindSpring. Earthlink 
rose 2 1/2 to 46 and MindSpring fell 3 5/8 to 29 1/4 after the companies 
said they will combine in an effort to compete better with industry 
leader America Online. 
</P>
<P>
	Meehan said the merger, combined with growing optimism over  
Internet companies' prospects during the holiday shopping season, 
boosted the Internet sector today. 
</P>
<P>
	``Strange as it seems, these stocks are coming to be viewed as  
safe havens,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by an 8-to-5 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 381.17 million 
shares, slightly ahead of Wednesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index fell 1.48 to 426.05.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
