<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DaimlerChrysler Shakeup Reported </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- The president of DaimlerChrysler AG's Chrysler  
division will resign as part of a shakeup that would mark a shift 
in the balance of power within the automaking company, published 
reports said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Detroit News reported Thursday that Thomas Stallkamp, 53,  
will leave as the head of DaimlerChrysler's North American unit and 
be replaced by James Holden, executive vice president for sales and 
marketing. 
</P>
<P>
	The move would come as DaimlerChrysler trims the size of its  
management board. Germany's Handelsblatt business daily said the 
merged group's supervisory board will decide on the management 
board's new makeup Friday. It said four members will leave the 
17-seat management board Oct. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler declined comment Thursday on the various  
reports. 
</P>
<P>
	The News said DaimlerChrysler co-chairman Robert Eaton will  
retain his seat on the management board. Of the seven former 
Chrysler Corp. executives on the DaimlerChrysler management board, 
five will reportedly remain. Eight board members would be former 
Daimler-Benz AG executives. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper said Stallkamp would leave the company, and  
Theodor R. Cunningham will relinquish his seat on the board but 
stay in charge of sales and marketing in North America. 
</P>
<P>
	Two Daimler executives, commercial truck head Kurt Lauk and  
human resources manager Heiner Tropitzsch, are also reportedly 
expected to step down from the board. 
</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler's stock hit a new low in trading Thursday  
afternoon falling $3.50 to $66.68 3/4 in dealings on the New York 
Stock Exchange. Shares closed up $3.31 1/4 to $66.25. 
</P>
<P>
	Auto industry analysts said the reports on Stallkamp's future  
could be playing a role in the stock price decline, along with 
concern that DaimlerChrysler might miss its financial goals. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think there are a lot of folks who still see this Chrysler  
dream team and all it's done to turn Chrysler around,'' said 
Lincoln Merrihew, an analyst with DRI/McGraw-Hill in Lexington, 
Mass. ``Stallkamp was part of that ... It may be that Chrysler is 
moving from a known team to an unknown team. Not good or bad, just 
unknown.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stallkamp had taken over as Chrysler Corp. president in January  
1998, just a week before Eaton, then the chairman of the U.S. 
automaker, began merger negotiations with Daimler-Benz AG. A 
Chrysler executive since 1980, Stallkamp had been credited with 
leading a drive to cut billions in costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Gregory L. Kagey, an analyst with Arnhold and S. Bleichroeder  
Inc. in New York, said Chrysler's cost-cutting expertise was billed 
as one of the major benefits to the DaimlerChrysler merger. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any cost cutting really goes to the bottom line,'' Kagey said.  
``To get rid of the father of Chrysler's supplier relationship is 
mystifying.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Several key executives, including co-chairman Juergen Schrempp,  
last month said the company was planning to reorganize and reduce 
the size of the company's board of management. 
</P>
<P>
	Eaton, the merged company's co-chairman with Schrempp, is  
scheduled to leave in two years. Merrihew said that Stallkamp's 
departure and the move to reduce the management board could move 
the company away from the ``merger of equals'' that Eaton billed 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's another sign that Chrysler is being blended into a  
Daimler-based company,'' Merrihew said. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
