<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990923.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 14:40:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Illinois, Pa. Utilities To Merge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The corporate parent of Chicago's  
Commonweath Edison is merging with PECO Energy Co. of Philadelphia 
in an $8.2 billion deal that would create the nation's largest 
electric utility. 
</P>
<P>
	Together, Chicago's Unicom Corp. and PECO control almost 20  
percent of the country's nuclear generating capacity. They have 
about 5 million customers, more than any other U.S. electric 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger is the latest in a wave of consolidations since  
federal deregulation has increased competition for electricity 
sales. PECO, for example, lost 16 percent of its electricity 
customers to competitors since deregulation began in Pennsylvania 
on Jan. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Utility analysts say the merger is a sign of more to come, and  
Unicom's chairman said the combined company, which has yet to 
select a name, plans on becoming even bigger. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that success in the future in the generation  
business requires very substantial scale,'' said John W. Rowe, 
Unicom's chairman, president and chief executive. ``We also believe 
by putting two companies of this size together and making them work 
efficiently, we will have the economic base to be an attractive 
acquirer of other companies in other metropolitan areas in the 
region.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The combined company will have total revenue of $12.4 billion  
and serve metropolitan areas including Chicago, the nation's 
third-largest city, where it will be based, and No. 5 Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	``These fairly large companies could have survived out there on  
their own,'' said Linda Byus, a Chicago-based analyst of Dresdner 
Kleinwort Benson. ``With these two good-size companies coming 
together ... it gives me a little more sense that there will be 
fewer energy companies out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The companies said they expect the deal to be approved by the  
end of next year, although it still needs approval from 
shareholders and from Pennsylvania and federal regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	Company officials said the merger could result in the loss of  
about 1,100 jobs, or about 5 percent of the combined work force, 
mostly administrative positions. 
</P>
<P>
	Unicom's and PECO's electric and gas utility operations will  
remain separate subsidiaries of the holding company, continuing to 
operate under the names Commonwealth Edison Co. and PECO Energy Co. 
Those companies will maintain their local headquarters, as well, 
Unicom and PECO said. 
</P>
<P>
	Commonweath Edison had a string of power outages over the summer  
that shut down the Chicago Board of Trade for a half a day, nearly 
spoiled frozen plant and animal tissue at the Field Museum of 
Natural History, and left about 100,000 customers without power for 
three days when the temperature was over 100. 
</P>
<P>
	The utility promised to spend more than $1.5 billion over the  
next two years to improve its distribution system. 
</P>
<P>
	Unicom's Rowe promised a management shakeup if necessary.  
</P>
<P>
	Corbin McNeill Jr., the chairman, president and CEO of PECO,  
said customers are not expected to see much change in electricity 
rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Chicago-based Unicom provides electric service across northern  
Illinois, serving about 3.4 million customers. It also has 10 
nuclear generating units at five sites. 
</P>
<P>
	PECO, based in Philadelphia, serves 1.5 million electric  
customers and 400,000 gas customers in the five-county Philadelphia 
region. 
</P>
<P>
	``They can save a lot of money with an operation on a larger  
scale,'' said Barbara Puklin, an analyst at Arnhold &AMP; S. 
Bleichroeder in New York. ``They can offer electricity at a lower 
price, provide a more efficient way of getting it and nuclear power 
looks good because it has lower costs and a low pollution factor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1997, PECO has turned its focus on increasing its nuclear  
power plants through a joint venture with British Energy Co. and 
purchasing the undamaged Unit 1 reactor at the Three Mile Island 
plant for $100 million in cash. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors were disappointed with terms of the cash-and-stock  
merger that valued Unicom at $42.75 a share and PECO at $45. 
</P>
<P>
	PECO fell 4.4 percent, or by $1.68 3/4, to close at $36.43 3/4 a share  
on the New York Stock Exchange, where Unicom fell 2.2 percent, or 
by 81 1/4 cents, to $36.25. 
</P>
<P>
	After a transition period during which they will share control  
of the new company, Rowe will become CEO of the new company and 
McNeill will serve on the board of directors and is expected to 
retire in four years. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
