<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ryder Cup Takes Off on TV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Ten years ago, hardly anyone cared about the Ryder Cup. The  
major TV networks passed, USA Network won the rights for a paltry 
$200,000 and then hired a public relations firm to explain the 
event. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC has no trouble explaining its success these days. They will  
have 16 1/2 hours of coverage this weekend and pay around $13 million. 
That's twice as many hours as the network showed in 1991 and 1993 
and that's not even counting USA's 10 1/2-hour Friday marathon. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's really taken on a life of its own,'' said CBS' Rob  
Correa, who made the deal to bring the Ryder Cup to USA in 1989. 
``We saw the potential back then and it's been incredible. There 
hasn't been a disappointing Ryder Cup since.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The entire complexion of the event has changed now that the  
Europeans are on top. 
</P>
<P>
	``The event has gotten so big that they want to show every  
hour,'' said NBC executive producer Tom Roy. ``From a ratings 
standpoint, we're probably shooting ourselves in the foot, ... but 
it's worth it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Americans won 21 of the first 25 events, and tied one other.  
In the last seven Ryder Cup matches, the United States has just two 
victories. 
</P>
<P>
	Roy has produced the Super Bowl, World Series, NBA Finals and  
the Olympics. But he expects this weekend to be the most difficult 
of his career. 
</P>
<P>
	Not just because of the abundance of coverage.  
</P>
<P>
	There are no breaks, or timeouts, in golf. The play never stops  
-- even during commercials. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every 20 seconds you have to decide where you're going next,''  
Roy said. 
</P>
<P>
	And even with so much air time, don't necessarily expect to see  
all of Tiger Woods' matches live. 
</P>
<P>
	``The way we typically show golf is to follow the leaders, but  
here we'll show the matches that are closest to ending or closest 
in competition,'' Roy said. ``If Tiger is blowing out his opponent 
in a match, you won't see much of him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, NBC will show mostly taped highlights.  
</P>
<P>
	Ratings for the Ryder Cup may not be quite to the level of the  
majors. However, the emotion displayed by the players surpasses all 
of them. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's certainly exploded inside of its sport unlike anything in  
the past 10 years,'' said CBS golf commentator Jim Nantz. ``It's 
huge, but it's still the fifth biggest event in golf.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *BEN'S BACK:* Ben Wright returned to TV in a golf role for the  
first time in four years Thursday and to no one's surprise, it 
wasn't with CBS. 
</P>
<P>
	The Golf Channel brought Wright on board for a series of  
90-second taped historical essays during its Ryder Cup coverage. 
</P>
<P>
	Wright made derogatory comments about women golfers in 1995 and  
was banned from CBS for the past four years. 
</P>
<P>
	``My contention is that Ben served his sentence,'' said Golf  
Channel host Peter Kessler. ``He is a serious historian whose whole 
career was harpooned by stupid things he said at the wrong time. 
It's time to move forward and give him another chance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kessler said that after filming the spots, Wright began crying  
because he was overwhelmed with emotion. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said he had no idea how much he missed and loved his  
work,'' Kessler said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *ICE TIME:* Hockey begins in one week, and ABC still hasn't  
announced its announcers for its debut NHL season. But expect Bill 
Clement and John Davidson to be involved. 
</P>
<P>
	Clement, the lead analyst for ESPN's hockey coverage, said he  
signed a five-year deal Saturday for the same position at ABC. 
</P>
<P>
	Davidson, who was the top game analyst for Fox until the  
network's deal ran out after last season, is expected to be the 
studio analyst. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Clement and Davidson favor the NHL's rule changes, which  
include a four-on-four overtime and give the loser one point. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *TUBE BITS:* CBS' Tennessee-Florida game posted a 7.5 rating and  
a 15 share, 32 percent higher than last year's game between the 
teams. ... San Antonio Spurs forward Sean Elliott, who had a kidney 
transplant last month, will be an analyst for the Spurs exhibition 
games while recovering. ... ESPN's Sunday night win by the Bills 
over the Jets had a 10.74 rating. ... ABC's ``Monday Night 
Football'' had a 15.2 national mark, up 20 percent from last 
season. ... Fishermen Terry Bradshaw and Bob Brenly will host the 
$3.5 million Ranger Millennium M1 Bass Fishing Tournament Nov. 7 on 
Fox. 



</P>
</TEXT>
