<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Teachers Seek Better Software </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) -- The nation's classrooms are full of wired  
boxes, but little attention is being paid to the quality of the 
software on classroom computers or how they're used, says a report 
released today. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't give many of the (software) titles a 9 or a 10,''  
says Ed Adshead, a network resource teacher who helps fellow 
teachers understand and use computers at Patrick Henry Elementary 
School just outside Washington. ``We have to hunt for it and then 
we find it isn't nearly as good as it looked like or what it was 
described as.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Teachers wade through thousands of CD-ROMS and computer  
diskettes just to find that the material doesn't match state or 
school district standardized tests, can't run on weak classroom 
computers, takes up too much classroom time to use or could cost 
too much, says the report, ``Technology Counts,'' a survey of the 
nation's teachers and state education technology policies published 
today by the newspaper Education Week. 
</P>
<P>
	``Politicians wire the classrooms and think they are done,''  
said Education Week publisher Virginia Edwards. ``But that's not 
the case at all. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're just looking at actual hardware and that is not going  
make a difference in what students learn,'' she said. ``When you 
get into the question of whether technology is effective, the 
research shows that it motivates kids when it is used well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The report, underwritten by The Milken Family Foundation of  
Santa Monica, Calif., is in its third year of tracking state 
policies and funding of school technology. 
</P>
<P>
	Armed with federal and state funds, many of the nation's 86,000  
schools have steadily brought in more computers. Now, 71 percent of 
schools can reach the Internet from at least one classroom. 
</P>
<P>
	Though all 53.2 million students aren't sitting in front of  
their very own terminals, on average, there are nearly six students 
for every ``instructional computer,'' which includes older models 
without extras such as sound cards and video, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	However, researchers cite a range of commitment to the other  
resources that make technology work: 
</P>
<P>
	--Less than a third of schools have a full-time technology  
coordinator. Another 27 percent just assign the task to a teacher 
or other staff member as part of his or her formal duties. 
</P>
<P>
	--Forty-two states require teacher preparation programs to  
include technology, but just four require technology in teacher 
re-certification. 
</P>
<P>
	--Twenty-three states have group-purchasing plans for schools to  
buy classroom software, which can cost $600 to $1,000 per title. 
</P>
<P>
	--Four states developed some software lessons to match the  
standards they've set for what children should know in certain 
subjects in grades. Eight states put such content on Web sites. 
</P>
<P>
	On the federal level, officials such as Vice President Al Gore  
have declared school technology a national mission, vowing to wire 
every classroom to the Internet. Software issues are not 
insurmountable, according to the Education Department, which awards 
grants to schools for technology projects. 
</P>
<P>
	``The whole landscape has changed,'' said Linda G. Roberts, the  
department's director of technology. ``Publishers are very serious 
about developing content for the schools. The challenge is in 
developing high quality content and that takes money and knowledge 
about how students learn, and it takes very clear signals from the 
buyers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This year, the Technology Counts report included the teacher  
survey, based on 1,407 responses from a representative sample of 
15,000 kindergarten-through 12th-grade teachers. The margin of 
error is plus or minus 3 percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	Teachers who do use computer software regularly found that  
expense is the largest barrier to using it even more: 48 percent 
say software costs are a ``big'' problem; 34 percent say expense is 
a ``moderate'' problem. 
</P>
<P>
	At Patrick Henry, which has a $4,000 annual computer software  
budget, teachers do everything from buying their own individual 
titles out of pocket to hitting the PTA up for ``bowlathons'' and 
bake sales to hauling 250 recently donated computers in their cars. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are at a distinct advantage when you look at what we do  
have,'' says fifth grade teacher Melinda Jones. ``We all attended 
the workshops, but it's all about taking time to find what we need 
and getting the support to do it really consistently.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the survey, 47 percent of teachers said their computers were  
too weak for the best software: ``It's more expensive to fix these 
than to buy new ones,'' says Adshead, pointing to a cart of 
assorted ancient computer parts. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
