<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cellist Makes Rare TV Appearance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Mstislav Rostropovich will be playing more than  
the cello when he makes a rare television appearance on PBS' ``Live 
from Lincoln Center.'' The acclaimed musician will be playing mind 
games as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hate TV!'' Rostropovich exclaims. ``It's only because of  
this occasion I'm doing it. When I see the camera, I immediately 
think how I look. Automatically. I lose the music. 
</P>
<P>
	``I must hypnotize myself for this particular concert.''  
</P>
<P>
	He's making the effort for the New York Philharmonic's opening  
night performance, which will air at 8 p.m. EDT Thursday on PBS 
stations. Kurt Masur conducts. 
</P>
<P>
	Rostropovich, a passionate performer who prefers bear hugs and  
kissing hands to handshakes with fellow musicians, will play 
Dvorak's ``Cello Concerto,'' which he first recorded in 1952. 
</P>
<P>
	His conductor then was Vaclav Talich, who had known Dvorak and  
gave the 25-year-old cellist pointers about how the composer wanted 
it played. Rostropovich, now 72, has been following Talich's 
guidelines for 47 years. Rostropovich has performed the premieres 
of 117 cello concertos which were written for him. 
</P>
<P>
	While he plays a concerto, he says, he feels it's the best  
possible music. ``I dedicate all my heart and spirit to it. If I 
criticize a concerto a little bit, I must stop playing this 
concerto. Some I play only once in my life. Some maybe twice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The other half of the Philharmonic's opening night program is  
Tchaikovsky's ``Fifth Symphony.'' Rostropovich considers 
Tchaikovsky a great composer but says his music can be made 
sentimental -- something he's confident will not happen in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Born in the Soviet republic of Azerbaijan, Rostropovich angered  
Soviet rulers when he helped dissident writer Alexander 
Solzhenitsyn. 
</P>
<P>
	``He lived five years in my home in Moscow,'' he said. ``That's  
why the government threw me out of the country. I was told, `You 
must put him out.' No. That's a human feeling; it's not about 
politics. He was my friend; he had no place to live.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The couple and their two daughters were given exit visas in 1974  
and left for the West. Their citizenship was revoked in 1978, later 
to be reinstated by Mikhail Gorbachev. 
</P>
<P>
	Rostropovich was amazed when the Berlin Wall came down.  
</P>
<P>
	``Until I was 47, I was in the Soviet Union, on one side of the  
Berlin Wall. I was sent out of my country without any hope I was 
ever coming back. When the Berlin Wall was crushed, I think maybe 
my two lives will come together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	They have. After giving a master class at the Curtis Institute  
in Philadelphia Oct. 1, Rostropovich will return to Paris only long 
enough to change suitcases and go to Russia to be a godfather at a 
christening, to receive an award and to hear some students. 
</P>
<P>
	Last March, after a Moscow concert was panned by a critic, he  
said he wouldn't perform in Russia any more. ``I'm still of that 
opinion,'' he says now. ``Of course, I'll still go there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His professional engagement calendar is full until 2003, about  
half playing cello, about half conducting. 
</P>
<P>
	Rostropovich plays a Stradivarius cello that has a scratch made  
by Napoleon's spur when he was looking at the instrument. ``It 
doesn't hurt the sound; it only makes the cello more famous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Was Napoleon a music lover? Rostropovich's eyes twinkle as he  
answers: ``I never spoke to him on this subject.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ....  
</P>
<P>
	XENA RETURNS: The fifth season premiere of ``Xena: Warrior  
Princess'' promises to be a whopper. When last seen, Xena (Lucy 
Lawless) and Gabrielle (Renee O'Connor) had been crucified by the 
Romans. ``Fallen Angel,'' the season opener airing in syndication 
next week (check local listings), puts the dynamic duo in league 
with the Archangel Michael to battle Callisto (Hudson Leick) and 
infernal forces -- with lots of appropriate special effects. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
