<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Sept. 23, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Sink; Dow Ends Down 205.48  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks plummeted today as investors sold heavily  
amid continued worries about higher interest rates and the strength 
of the dollar. A Microsoft executive's warning that technology 
stocks are overvalued robbed the market of a big source of 
strength. The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 205.48 at 
10,318.59. That brought the Dow's decline over the past three 
sessions to 505.31 points. Broader stock indicators also fell 
steeply. The Nasdaq composite index suffered one of its worst 
declines in its history. It fell 107.66 to 2,750.50. ``The market 
is under the weight of so many threats right now,'' said Scott 
Bleier, chief investment strategist at Prime Charter Ltd., citing 
rising interest rates, the tumbling dollar as the most pressing 
problems. ``It has deteriorated.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures at the close:  
Dow Industrials:        10,318.59 - 205.48
NYSE Issues:         Advances  892  Declines 2149  Unchgd  499
NYSE Volume:         856,269,980
Most Active NYSE issue:         Rite Aid Corp12       - 2
S&AMP;P 500:                 1278.76 - 31.75
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          778.51  -   3.94
Nasdaq Composite Index        2,750.50  - 107.66
Gold(final) -    $265.40    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Thu.
Silver(final) -   $5.220  troy oz., NY Comex spot month Thu.

</P>
<P>
	Jobless Claims at 25-Year Low  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- New claims for unemployment benefits dropped  
unexpectedly last week to the lowest level in a quarter of a 
century. But economists chalked up much of the decline to Hurricane 
Floyd, suggesting that the storm could have prevented some jobless 
people from getting to claims offices. Government officials 
acknowledged that Floyd could have had an influence on the figures. 
A total of 272,000 Americans filed new claims for jobless benefits 
for the week that ended Saturday, down 17,000 from the previous 
week, the Labor Department said today. Many economists had forecast 
a rise in last week's claims to 290,000. 

</P>
<P>
	Earthlink, Mindspring To Merge  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- EarthLink Network Inc. and MindSpring  
Enterprises Inc., two fast-growing providers of dial-up access to 
the Internet, are merging in a $1.4 billion stock swap to create a 
tough new rival to America Online Inc. The marriage of close 
competitors, each founded just 5 years ago, speeds the 
consolidation of a highly fragmented industry brimming with 
thousands of small Web access providers. The entity created by 
Thursday's transaction would have 3 million subscribers. MindSpring 
stock fell 17 percent, or $5.50 a share, to $27.37 1/2. EarthLink was 
up as much as 11 percent immediately after the deal's announcement 
but retreated by day's end, down 3 percent, or $1.12 1/2 at $42.37 1/2. 

</P>
<P>
	IMF Head Says Relief for Poor Near  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers and the  
head of the International Monetary Fund both expressed optimism 
today that agreement will soon be reached on how to finance greatly 
expanded debt relief for the world's poorest countries. Michel 
Camdessus, the IMF managing director, said finance officials were 
``within striking distance'' of a deal. One of the key elements of 
the revamped proposal is the sale of 14 million ounces of the IMF's 
gold reserves to IMF member countries, rather than on the open 
market. The sale will pay for the IMF's contribution to a program 
intended to forgive $90 billion in debt held by the world's 41 
poorest nations. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Fights Money-Laundering  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration today unveiled its  
first national money-laundering strategy, aimed at stanching the 
flow of billions of criminal dollars through the U.S. financial 
system. The package of proposed new laws and rules comes as federal 
investigators examine allegations of a huge money-laundering scheme 
involving Russians and the Bank of New York. The new strategy 
includes a requirement that storefront check cashiers, brokerage 
firms and casinos notify authorities of suspicious activities the 
way banks must do. The government would designate new 
high-intensity money-laundering zones. 

</P>
<P>
	CDC: State Health Depts. Y2K Ready  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- State health departments are ready for the  
millennium bug, the federal government reported. The Centers for 
Disease Control and Prevention reported that a survey conducted 
from June through August identified no ``significant'' 
vulnerabilities to the Y2K problem in state health department 
systems. Some experts fear the arrival of the year 2000 could 
result in shutdowns or other malfunctions by causing some older 
computers to think it is 1900. 

</P>
<P>
	Lehman Bros. Posts 92 Percent Jump  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Lehman Brothers Holdings Inc. today reported  
profits of $290 million for its fiscal third quarter, a 92 percent 
increase from last year's figure and well above analysts' 
predictions. Lehman attributed the strong earnings numbers to the 
company's increased focus on its highly profitable investment 
banking and stock trading units. Lehman earned $2.20 a share, 19 
cents more than analysts' expectations of $2.01 a share. The 
previous high was $2.12 a share, posted in the second quarter of 
1998. Shares of Lehman were at 53 3/8, down 1 7/8. 

</P>
<P>
	Reuters Shares Drop 15 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Shares in Reuters Group PLC tumbled 15 percent in  
heavy trading today in fallout from briefings to British and 
American analysts a day earlier by the media and financial 
information company. The selloff continued even after the company 
denied it had disclosed any profit warnings. Reuters ended a 
volatile session down the equivalent of $2.09 to close at $11.90 a 
share. With more than 55 million shares changing hands, it was the 
most active issue on the London Stock Exchange. Reuters U.S. shares 
were down nearly 11 percent Thursday on the Nasdaq Stock Market, 
dropping $8.75 to $71. 

</P>
<P>
	Chiquita To Cut Up to 200 Jobs  
</P>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Chiquita Brands International Inc. plans to  
eliminate as many as 200 jobs during the next several months to 
save at least $15 million a year in operating costs, management 
said today. The jobs are to be cut in corporate and staff ranks in 
the United States and Latin America, as well as banana operations 
in North America and Europe. The reductions will cost the company 
$6 million before taxes in the third quarter to cover severance 
expenses, benefits extensions and job placement services, the 
Cincinnati-based company said. Chiquita shares were at 5 5/8, up 1/8. 

</P>
<P>
	German Conglomerate To Split  
</P>
<P>
	DUESSELDORF, Germany (AP) -- German conglomerate Mannesmann said  
today it plans to split its fast-growing telecommunications 
business from its engineering and automotive divisions in a bid to 
boost profits. The announcement sent Mannesmann shares soaring on 
the Frankfurt stock exchange. Mannesmann's board of directors made 
the proposal to the supervisory board today, the company said. A 
decision was expected early next year. Mannesmann said it also aims 
to list the two companies separately on European capital markets in 
2001 and wants both companies to be components of Germany's DAX 30 
blue chip index. 

</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler Shakeup Reported  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- DaimlerChrysler declined comment today on various  
published reports of a shakeup that would mark a shift in the 
balance of power within the company. The Detroit News reported 
today that Thomas Stallkamp, 53, will leave as the head of 
DaimlerChrysler's North American unit and be replaced by James 
Holden, executive vice president for sales and marketing. Germany's 
Handelsblatt business daily said the merged group's supervisory 
board will decide on the management board's new makeup, It said 
four members will leave the 17-seat management board Oct. 1. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Eulogizes Labor's Kirkland  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton eulogized labor leader Lane  
Kirkland as a towering figure who defied political labels and 
fought tenaciously for ``the things he knew to be right.'' Clinton 
and well-wishers including Henry Kissinger and Polish labor 
reformer Lech Walesa attended a memorial service today at 
Georgetown University for Kirkland, who died of lung cancer month 
at 77. Kirkland, who reunited the major U.S. unions during his 
presidency of the AFL-CIO from 1979 to 1995, clung to the principle 
that ``the role of the trade unions was to try to keep the big guys 
from kicking the little guys around,'' Clinton said. 

</P>
<P>
	Economic Numbers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic reports:  
</P>
<P>
	Jobless claims: down 17,000 to 272,000  


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
