<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Webb Hopes To Regain LPGA Momentum  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Karrie Webb is rested, rejuvenated and  
ready to atone for one of her few mistakes of 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	Webb is the top money winner on the LPGA Tour with $1.4 million  
and six victories. But she let one slip away two weeks ago in the 
World Championship of Women's Golf in Minnesota. She led by three 
strokes after 14 holes, but double-bogeyed twice down the stretch 
as Se Ri Pak won by a stroke. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was hard for me to understand what happened,'' Webb said.  
``I have another 15 years to go on the tour, and can't sit and 
dwell on weeks like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 24-year-old Australian skipped last week's tournament at  
Kent, Wash., and is back for the three-day Safeway LPGA Golf 
Championship, one of the most popular tournaments on the tour. The 
beautiful par-72, 6,307-yard course at Columbia-Edgewater Country 
Club, squeezed between the Columbia River and industrial Portland, 
is in terrific shape. 
</P>
<P>
	``It always has been one of my favorites,'' said Danielle  
Ammaccapane, who won last year's tournament by one shot over Emilee 
Klein. ``There are a lot of different kinds of holes, it's pretty 
and it has great greens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures approaching 90 baked those greens earlier this  
week, and after a slight rain Thursday, conditions should be cool 
but comfortable for Friday's first round. 
</P>
<P>
	The tournament also is among the tour's most lucrative. The  
purse this year is $800,000, up $200,000 from 1998. The winner gets 
$129,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Juli Inkster is within one point of making the LPGA Hall of  
Fame, and a victory in the Safeway would qualify her. Inkster, 39, 
has four victories this season, including two majors -- the U.S. 
Women's Open and the LPGA Championship -- and is second to Webb on 
the money list with $1,143,703. 
</P>
<P>
	Webb could battle Inkster for player of the year for the rest of  
the tour circuit, which has six official events left after this 
weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I play well the rest of the year, she might not catch me,''  
Webb said. ``If I'm meant to win the player of the year and Vare 
Trophy (for best scoring average), then I'm meant to win. It's up 
to fate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ammaccapane's winning score of 12-under last year was three  
strokes better than her sister, Dina, who was third. It was the 
best combined finish ever for the sisters. Danielle is struggling 
this season, having missed 11 cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	But she couldn't be happier. She and her husband are expecting a  
baby -- ultrasound says it's almost certainly a girl -- on Feb. 29. 
</P>
<P>
	``Golf is not going all that great,'' Ammaccapane said.  
``Everything else is going real well.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
