<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 07:50:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Crafting Minimun Wage Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Bipartisan legislation is bubbling to the  
surface in the House to raise the minimum wage by $1.30 an hour 
over four years and grant several tax breaks and other sweeteners 
for small businesses and the self-employed. 
</P>
<P>
	Congressional officials, speaking on condition of anonymity,  
said Wednesday that a group of moderate Republicans and 
business-oriented Democrats hoped to unveil the measure formally by 
week's end. 
</P>
<P>
	The principals involved in the discussions, who include  
Republican Rick Lazio of New York and Democrat Gary Condit of 
California, declined to comment on the substance of the measure. 
</P>
<P>
	Numerous officials provided these details, while cautioning that  
no final decisions had been made and stressing that the prospects 
for passage in the narrowly divided House were uncertain: 
</P>
<P>
	-- The current $5.15 federal minimum wage would rise by 35 cents  
an hour in each of the next two years, followed by two annual 
increases of 30 cents an hour. That is more than the $1 an hour 
increase over four years that the GOP leadership had been 
discussing, but less than the $1 over two years that the White 
House and organized labor's allies in the House favor and are 
expected to press for beginning in the next day or two. 
</P>
<P>
	-- The cost of health care would be made fully deductible for the  
self-employed. 
</P>
<P>
	-- There would be an increase in the deductibility of the cost of  
business meals, a provision backed by the restaurant industry that 
would apply to small businesses and the self-employed. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Reduction in the unemployment tax surtax.  
</P>
<P>
	-- Extension of the Work Opportunity Tax Credit, which offsets  
the first $6,000 in wages paid to certain workers. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Increased asset depreciation for small business.  
</P>
<P>
	-- Pension changes, which are part of House-passed legislation  
co-sponsored by Reps. Rob Portman, R-Ohio, and Ben Cardin, D-Md., 
and favored by the life insurance industry. These include increased 
permissible contributions for 401(k) plans, and a provision 
allowing workers over 50 to save additional funds for retirements. 
Other pension changes include greater portability for pensions and 
faster vesting rights. 
</P>
<P>
	The Congressional Budget Office has estimated that a $1 increase  
in the minimum wage over two years would cost business roughly $16 
billion over five years. The tax breaks are designed to more than 
offset that, although no formal estimates were available. 
</P>
<P>
	Efforts to pass a minimum wage increase are stalled in the  
Senate, where Democrats want to attach the issue to a bill 
overhauling bankruptcy laws. 
</P>
<P>
	The political currents are tricky in the House, as well.  
</P>
<P>
	Many Republicans traditionally have opposed increases in the  
minimum wage, but the leadership is under pressure from the 
Democratic minority as well as a pivotal group of GOP lawmakers 
from swing districts who court union support. 
</P>
<P>
	On the other hand, while many Democrats favor a $1 minimum wage  
increase over two years, conservative members of the rank and file 
want measures to assist businesses likely to feel the effects of an 
increase. 
</P>
<P>
	House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, told reporters  
earlier in the week that a vote would be allowed if moderate 
Republicans asked for it. 
</P>
<P>
	At a GOP leadership meeting Wednesday, Rep. Roy Blunt of  
Missouri, the chief deputy whip, was assigned to oversee the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a general sense that if we are going to have this vote  
in the next couple of years, we might as well have it now,'' he 
said. He added that business groups also have a chance to win tax 
relief they would otherwise lose because of President Clinton's 
pending veto of a broader GOP tax cut. 
</P>
<P>
	Among Democrats, Rep. David Bonior of Michigan, the party whip,  
is spearheading an effort to force a vote on the costlier White 
House-backed bill that calls for a $1 an hour increase over two 
years. Through a spokesman, he called the bipartisan bill ``a good 
start.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990923.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 21:06:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Blissfull Hall Wins Brown Jug Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DELAWARE, Ohio (AP) -- Less than an hour after fading down the  
stretch to lose his first shot at winning, Blissfull Hall redeemed 
himself with a strong closing quarter to take the Little Brown Jug 
in a raceoff Thursday and move within a win of capturing pacing's 
triple crown. 
</P>
<P>
	Blissfull Hall, winner of the Cane Pace earlier this month at  
Freehold, N.J., shoots for the triple crown and a $250,000 bonus in 
the Messenger Stakes on Oct. 16 at The Meadows at Meadow Lands, Pa. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second year in a row Ron Pierce drove the Little  
Brown Jug winner. A year ago, he got a late gift when Mike Lachance 
elected to drive Artiscape in the second heat instead of favored 
Shady Character. Pierce was given the ride and ended up winning 
while Artiscape finished fourth. 
</P>
<P>
	Blissfull Hall coasted to victory in the first elimination in  
1:53, winning a showdown with leading money-winner The Panderosa. 
The Panderosa broke stride in the first few seconds and finished 
last. 
</P>
<P>
	In the second heat, which in the Little Brown Jug format brings  
back the top three finishers in each of the first three 
eliminations, Pierce took Blissfull Hall to the rail early and 
appeared to be in command heading into the stretch of the one-mile 
race at Delaware County Fairgrounds. 
</P>
<P>
	But Blissfull Hall faded badly and dropped to third behind upset  
winner Looking For Art, driven by Ohio native Eric Ledford in his 
Jug debut. Ledford and his wife, Tammy, are expecting their first 
child and he carried a pager with him throughout the day in case he 
was summoned back to his home in Chicago for the birth. 
</P>
<P>
	A horse must win two heats in the Jug's quirky format and  
Looking For Art's stunning victory forced the four horses who had 
won races to come back in a raceoff to decide the Jug winner. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first raceoff since Fake Left needed a third heat to  
win in 1992 and only the second in the last 21 years. There have 
been eight raceoffs in the Jug's 54 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Pierce bided his time, holding Blissfull Hall in third or fourth  
place until going wide on the last turn. The Cambest colt, who had 
lost the lead at the same spot an hour earlier in the second heat, 
pulled away down the stretch to win in 1:55 3-5 by a length over 
Looking For Art. The victory was worth $127,834 to owner Daniel 
Plouffe. Ohio Gov. Robert Taft presented the Little Brown Jug 
trophy to Plouffe, who owns a string of grocery stores in Quebec. 
</P>
<P>
	Blissfull Hall has won 10 races, with two seconds and a third in  
14 starts. 
</P>
<P>
	A victory in the Messenger would make Blissfull Hall the ninth  
winner of the triple crown for pacing 3-year-olds and the second 
since Ralph Hanover in 1983. Western Dreamer won all three legs in 
1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jug was again a huge disappointment for owner Jeffrey S.  
Snyder. 
</P>
<P>
	Snyder had to scratch Jug favorite Cam's Card Shark moments  
before post time five years ago. He erased some of that hurt by 
sending all three of his entries to the second heat -- each with Luc 
Ouellette in the sulky -- and even had half of the four-horse field 
in the raceoff. Yet he still came up empty. 
</P>
<P>
	Ledford qualified three horses for the second heat -- one from  
each elimination -- before winning behind Looking For Art. Looking 
For Art actually won more money on the day than Blissfull Hall 
($202,904) because the second heat had the biggest purse. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990923.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 21:06:01 </DATE_TIME>
