<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hornets Owner Won't Be Charged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	YORK, S.C. (AP) -- Charlotte Hornets owner George Shinn, accused  
by a woman of sexual assault at his suburban home, no longer risks 
criminal charges after a grand jury chose not to indict him 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel as comfortable with this decision that it wasn't a  
whitewash, wasn't a railroad one way or another,'' prosecutor Tommy 
Pope said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pope originally said in November 1997 that there was not enough  
evidence to charge Shinn. Since then, however, there have been new 
revelations, including a former Hornets cheerleader who said Shinn 
coerced her into a two-year sexual relationship by threatening her 
job, so Pope sent the case to the grand jury. 
</P>
<P>
	He said it took an investigator 3 1/2 hours to present the case and  
about an hour for the grand jury, which meets in secret, to decide 
against indicting Shinn. 
</P>
<P>
	After the announcement, Leslie Price, who accused Shinn of the  
assault at his Tega Cay home, said she was disappointed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I fought for two years and I may not have done the smartest  
things, but I did the right things,'' she said. She would not 
answer questions. Her North Carolina lawyer, David Bland, did not 
return phone calls. 
</P>
<P>
	Her South Carolina lawyer, Dick Harpootlian, said he had  
withdrawn from the case, but wouldn't say why. 
</P>
<P>
	Price thanked her supporters and said ``I pray, justice is going  
to be served at some point.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pope wouldn't say why grand jurors didn't indict Shinn. Maybe  
``the same factors that gave me so much trouble were the same that 
kept this so nebulous'' for them, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, Pope said he thought that ``something did in fact  
transpire'' between Shinn and Price at the lakeside Tega Cay house, 
but there wasn't enough evidence to make a case. 
</P>
<P>
	Price still has a lawsuit pending in Columbia scheduled for a  
Dec. 6 retrial. The first trial last week was disrupted by 
Hurricane Floyd. Shinn was focusing on that and on the upcoming NBA 
season, his lawyer, Bill Diehl, said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're delighted that once and for all, it's behind us,'' Diehl  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're looking forward to trying the civil case unencumbered by  
the previous threat that she constantly pounded us with,'' that 
Shinn could face criminal charges, the lawyer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pope said he wanted to get the case to the grand jurors so they  
could rule without a civil trial to influence them. 
</P>
<P>
	Price, who was in a drug- and alcohol-treatment center outside  
Charlotte, N.C., at the time, said she met Shinn in September 1997 
through a man who identified himself as Shinn's nephew. 
</P>
<P>
	She alleged that Shinn lured her to his suburban lake home on  
the premise of meeting Diehl to discuss her legal problems, but 
Diehl was not there and once at the house Shinn forced her to give 
him oral sex. Shinn has denied that and has a slander lawsuit 
against her pending in North Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	He has since been divorced by his wife, has moved to Florida and  
has made a deal to sell as much as half of the Hornets to Atlanta 
businessman Ray Wooldridge. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
