<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Angry Cruise Passengers Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PALMETTO, Fla. (AP) -- No running water, raw sewage floating in  
the halls and a fire on the ship. It's hardly the dream vacation 
passengers expected when they boarded a Carnival Cruise Line ship. 
</P>
<P>
	Passengers on Carnival's 660-foot Tropicale say they endured a  
weeklong nightmare after an engine fire left the vessel stranded in 
the Gulf of Mexico as Tropical Storm Harvey swept through. 
</P>
<P>
	As they finally disembarked from the ship Wednesday, some  
accused Carnival of trying to cover up what happened. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right before the Coast Guard got on board, (cruise officials)  
opened all the bars, they started all the music, they filled all 
the pools, they started replacing the carpet, fixing the toilets 
and they were putting up brand new fire extinguishers that never 
existed,'' said Beth Haynie of Clinton, Mich. 
</P>
<P>
	A Carnival executive, however, denied the allegations and said  
the cruise line tried its best to accommodate passengers during the 
crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	``We understand that a lot of our guests were very frustrated by  
this,'' spokesman Tim Gallagher said. ``Once that fire occurred, 
our objective was to return our guests to Tampa in a safe and 
secure way with a minimum of inconvenience.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About 1,700 passengers and crew left Tampa a week ago on what  
was supposed to be a four-day cruise with stops in Key West and 
Cozumel, Mexico. The fire on Sunday was extinguished quickly but 
temporarily left the ship without power. 
</P>
<P>
	Passengers reported panic during the fire and complained they  
received little direction from the crew and were confused about 
where to assemble. 
</P>
<P>
	``People were running around like maniacs,'' said David Rizzo, a  
U.S. Airways employee from Clearwater. 
</P>
<P>
	Gallagher said despite the fire, cabins had drinking water, air  
conditioning and electricity, and most had working toilets. But 
passengers painted a different picture. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Haynie was one of many who complained of scarce drinking  
water, and taps either without water or spewing dark gray fluid. 
Plumbing problems were said to have started even before the fire. 
Some passengers videotaped their troubles. 
</P>
<P>
	Rizzo said there was no running water in toilets and sinks for  
some time, and raw sewage overflowed into hallways. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was horrible,'' Rizzo said. ``I've never seen stuff like  
that in my life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The cruise line has promised all passengers a full refund, a  
free ticket for a future cruise and paid for new flights home. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990923.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 08:20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ripken To Undergo Back Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- In a year in which Cal Ripken went on the  
disabled list for the first time in his career, back surgery will 
end his season early and delay his pursuit of 3,000 hits. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken, nine hits shy of 3,000, was scheduled for back surgery  
today at University Hospitals in Cleveland and will miss the final 
12 games for the Baltimore Orioles. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel bad that Cal's hurt because I wanted him to get 3,000,  
but he'll get it next year,'' Baltimore Orioles manager Ray Miller 
said Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	University Hospitals of Cleveland spokeswoman Eileen Korey  
confirmed that Ripken was being prepared for surgery this morning 
at about 10 a.m., and she said the surgery would likely last two to 
three hours. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken visited specialist Dr. Henry Bohlman on Wednesday after  
experiencing back spasms overnight. The surgery will relieve 
pressure on a nerve that has been causing him pain. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is in a lot of discomfort and felt that it was time to get  
it done,'' general manager Frank Wren said. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball's Iron Man, who played in 2,632 straight games before  
voluntarily ending the streak a year ago, twice was placed on the 
DL this season because of back pain. 
</P>
<P>
	``You expect him to come back and play well because of who he  
is,'' teammate Mike Timlin said. ``It says a lot about the guy that 
he went this long without surgery. You see a guy in pain and yet 
continue to play at the level he was, you admire that. He's an iron 
guy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 39-year-old Ripken, whose career began in 1981, went on the  
disabled list on April 20 because of a bad back, missing three 
weeks. He was again forced out of action after experiencing more 
back pain Aug. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	``To have it reoccur was disappointing and frustrating. I was  
down for a long time,'' he said recently. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken returned on Sept. 1 and hit his 400th career homer the  
next day. He has since been on a binge at the plate, upping his 
batting average to a career-high .340. 
</P>
<P>
	He appeared on his way to joining Tony Gwynn and Wade Boggs this  
year as members of the 3,000-hit club. It would have been the first 
time three players reached the milestone in the same season. 
</P>
<P>
	Getting there this year was not a priority for Ripken, who has  
always put team goals ahead of personal accomplishments. 
</P>
<P>
	``If 3,000 hits happen, it happens. But it hasn't been a goal to  
do it in a certain period of time and it hasn't been a goal to do 
it in a certain year,'' he said the night he hit his 400th homer. 
``You just play, and things happen when they happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But because the Orioles long ago fell out of playoff contention,  
Ripken didn't have much to play for except personal goals -- 
although Baltimore won its 13th straight Wednesday by beating Texas 
7-4. 
</P>
<P>
	``The true satisfaction out of the game of baseball is to win,''  
Ripken said earlier this month. ``It's a whole lot more fun playing 
on a winner and having a chance to go to the playoffs. It's been a 
frustrating season in that regard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Probably not nearly as frustrating as the time he's missed  
because of back pain. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
