<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Ryder Cup Team Wants Cheers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BROOKLINE, Mass. (AP) -- On the eve of the last Ryder Cup in  
Spain, Tom Kite gathered his team together and urged them to keep 
things quiet. 
</P>
<P>
	Let the crowd into the matches, he warned, and the cup is lost.  
</P>
<P>
	``If it starts going their way and they start feeding off their  
fans roaring all over the golf course, it's going to kill us,'' 
Kite said. 
</P>
<P>
	Just the opposite holds true beginning Friday at The Country  
Club, where it will be the Europeans trying to keep the noise down 
and the U.S. team hoping to ride the cheers of the crowd to 
victory. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Ryder Cup, momentum is important, and the reaction of the  
approximately 35,000 spectators who line the fairways this week 
could spell the difference in who wins the cup Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``If things get quiet, we're going to be in trouble,'' Davis  
Love III said. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike most golf tournaments, the crowd plays a big part in the  
Ryder Cup, where national pride can be at stake outside the ropes 
just as much as it is inside. 
</P>
<P>
	The roaring throngs can't make putts or hit long drives, but  
they can help change the momentum of the matches. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's all the crowds out there that are just going bananas  
for one team or another, and you feel their desire and you feel the 
desire of your teammates,'' Tom Lehman said. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton is expected to be part of that crowd Sunday,  
and the king and queen of Spain will be on hand to cheer for the 
Europeans. 
</P>
<P>
	The noises that roll across the hilly fairways of The Country  
Club will be so unmistakable that players won't need a scoreboard 
to figure out what is going on. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's going to be cheers for the Europeans, but the cheers  
for the Americans are going to be a lot louder,'' Payne Stewart 
said. ``So, if you're playing in a match and you hear a big cheer 
behind you, you're going to know who it's for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Justin Leonard found that out at Valderrama where he hit a poor  
shot on the first tee, and heard the crowd cheer. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's something you don't hear too much on a golf course,''  
Leonard said. ``It can be intimidating.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Europeans discovered that in 1991 at Kiawah Island, S.C.,  
where boisterous fans chanted ``USA, USA'' and acted so badly that 
even some of the American players were embarrassed. 
</P>
<P>
	Scotland's Colin Montgomerie, a Ryder Cup rookie that year,  
might have had that in mind at the U.S. Open last year, when fans 
heckled him briefly. 
</P>
<P>
	``Save it for the Ryder Cup,'' Montgomerie said.  
</P>
<P>
	Montgomerie is a player Americans love to hate, though he played  
the 1995 Ryder Cup at Oak Hill in Rochester, N.Y., without problems 
and expects the same this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't foresee any problems this week,'' Montgomerie said.  
</P>
<P>
	Teammate Darren Clarke agreed.  
</P>
<P>
	``What hostile crowd?'' Clarke said. ``Who said the crowd was  
going to be hostile?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Europeans might want to heed the words of 1997 team member  
Scott Hoch, who was paired with Jeff Maggert against Nick Faldo and 
Lee Westwood at Valderrama. 
</P>
<P>
	On the first tee, the crowd was cheering the European team and  
heckling the Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said, `You guys aren't used to this, but I'm used to people  
rooting against me every week on the PGA Tour,' '' Maggert said. 
``It took the nerves out of the day and we had a great day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Tiger Woods, having a home crowd is long overdue.  
</P>
<P>
	Woods played on his first Ryder Cup team in Spain, and has  
played the Presidents Cup in Australia, the Eisenhower Cup in 
France and the Walker Cup in Wales. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's nice to have some fans cheering for us for some good  
shots,'' Woods said. ``I don't have to hear boos all day.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
