<HEADLINE> Croatian Telecom Receives Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ZAGREB, Croatia (AP) -- A Scandinavian company, Telia-Telenor,  
appeared to be the sole bidder Thursday for a 35 percent stake in 
Croatia's Telecom, the country's only telecommunications firm and 
its most important privatization target yet. 
</P>
<P>
	Deutsche Telekom, the only other company that had been expected  
to make an offer, failed to submit its bid by Thursday's deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	The government now has seven days to accept or reject the bid by  
Telia-Telenor, which offered $611 million for the stake. 
</P>
<P>
	The government will make further consultations before reaching a  
decision, said Igor Mrduljas, a government spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	According to independent newspaper reports, Deutsche Telekom had  
unsuccessfully requested an extension of the deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	Media reports had speculated the government would change the  
deadline to accomodate the Germans, who have close ties with the 
Croats. 
</P>
<P>
	Telia-Telenor's bid came in well below reports earlier this year  
that the whole company might be worth up to $3 billion. More 
recently, there was speculation that Deutsche Telekom considered 
offering about $800 million for the stake. 



</P>
</TEXT>
