<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Misery in N.C.After Floyd </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINDSOR, N.C. (AP) -- The soggy devastation left by Hurricane  
Floyd hit hard for Robin Ray as she realized it was her son Joey's 
15th birthday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He doesn't have anything,'' she said. ``It just doesn't seem  
right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Their home was destroyed when the Cashie River spilled over its  
banks after 20 inches of rain fell during last week's storm. 
Furniture and carpets were ruined and have been hauled off to the 
dump. 
</P>
<P>
	State Sen. Marc Basnight gave Ms. Ray a hug Wednesday and  
promised: ``It's going to be better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Basnight was among a group of legislators touring eastern North  
Carolina, where Floyd has created the worst disaster in state 
history. 
</P>
<P>
	The misery includes rivers fouled by human waste, hog waste and  
debris of all kinds; a wrecked shrimp harvest; farm losses expected 
to exceed $1 billion; and millions in uninsured home and car 
losses. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 42 people in North Carolina have been killed. The  
latest victim was a National Guardsman killed when his vehicle 
overturned late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Altogether, the storm killed at least 70 people from the Bahamas  
to New England -- and that toll is expected to rise once floodwaters 
recede. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no doubt there are individuals out there who were  
swept off roadways and whose bodies have not been recovered,'' said 
Dr. John Butts, the state's chief medical examiner. 
</P>
<P>
	About 3,100 people remain in shelters, though some in Rocky  
Mount and Greenville have moved into camping trailers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We lost everything we had, but we've still got our health and  
now we've got a place to stay,'' said Carolyn Whitehead of 
Greenville, who moved into one of the trailers with her husband and 
four children. ``I just want to take a hot bath.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But for many others, the problems continue. Statewide, officials  
estimate at least 100,000 hogs, 2.4 million chickens and 500,000 
turkeys drowned. Early estimates of crop and farm structure losses 
totaled $333 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The threat of disease from rotting carcasses led state officials  
to send portable incinerators into counties with the most extensive 
livestock deaths. 
</P>
<P>
	Floyd wiped out the prized breeding operation that Allen McCoy,  
57, and his cousin Phillip, 65, built from the ground up, killing 
more than 3,000 hogs. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is sweat and blood you're talking about,'' said McCoy,  
who estimated his losses at more than $500,000 from flooding on the 
Trent River. ``I've lost basically what I've worked for the last 40 
years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, volunteers from the Emergency Animal Rescue Service  
continued their efforts to save hundreds of pets left behind as 
their owners evacuated. Volunteers have rescued 260 animals, mostly 
dogs, says Terri Crisp, director of EARS, part of the nonprofit 
United Animal Network advocacy group. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've seen dogs swimming out to boats, almost literally jumping  
into the boats,'' said Crisp, who has responded to about 40 
disasters, including fires, earthquakes and tornadoes. ``One almost 
licked me to death, he was so happy just to have human 
companionship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Damage from Floyd is expected to surpass the $6 billion cost  
caused by Hurricane Fran in 1996. Gov. Jim Hunt scheduled a trip to 
Washington today to lobby for more federal money. 
</P>
<P>
	Farther south, in Conway, S.C., officials say rising floodwaters  
are threatening to wipe out parts of Highway 90, cutting off 
thousands of people between Conway and North Myrtle Beach. 
</P>
<P>
	``If these three places flood, we will have islands of people  
out there,'' said acting Horry County administrator Danny Knight. 
</P>
<P>
	The Waccamaw River was expected to crest close at about 17 feet  
-- about 10 feet above flood stage -- this week. State transportation 
officials said they expect to complete work on a dike by Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In hard-hit New Jersey, about 6,000 people had applied for  
relief grants to the Federal Emergency Management Agency by 
Wednesday, said agency spokeswoman Carol Hector-Harris. 
</P>
<P>
	A total damage estimate for the state will not be available for  
at least a week, State Police spokesman John Hagerty said, but the 
town of Manville already has claimed $500 million in damages for 
home, businesses and cleanup costs. More than 200 homes were 
condemned and 1,200 were damaged, Mayor Angelo Corradino said. 
</P>
<P>
	``My knees shake when I think about it,'' Corradino said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
