<DOCNO> APW19990923.0313 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 23:40:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stations Turn to Web Broadcasts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- This past summer, if you were a baseball fan in  
search of Florida Marlins' highlights, you might tune in to WPEC's 
11 p.m. newscast -- or log on to its Web site to watch a simulcast. 
</P>
<P>
	Not anymore. Major League Baseball has cried ``Foul!'' -- and  
copyright infringement -- forcing the station in West Palm Beach, 
Fla., and others around the country to stop broadcasting on the 
Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Disputes over Internet programming rights, though still rare,  
are on the rise as more radio and TV stations run their 
over-the-air feeds on the Web as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``The problem is technology is always way ahead of the law,''  
said Kathleen Kirby, a lawyer for the Radio-Television News 
Directors Association, a Washington-based industry group. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet broadcasts generally mirror those sent over the  
airwaves, so some stations do not see the need for additional 
rights. But distributors of sports and entertainment programming 
say their contracts spell out permitted uses and automatically 
prohibit everything else. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball contracts go a step further and include a clause that  
specifically bans Internet broadcasts, even Internet broadcasts of 
highlights. The baseball league found several violators, and 
lawyers stopped the Web broadcasts. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's starting to come up this season,'' said Michael Mellis,  
new media counsel for Major League Baseball Enterprises, the 
licensing division. ``Our game footage is copyrighted, and our 
intellectual property is valuable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	WPEC, which started Web simulcasts of local news shows on June  
21, has since eliminated its entire sports segment from the Web 
version. The station also disabled the Internet archives of past 
news shows because they contain baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	``To me, it's no different than re-broadcasting your news on  
cable,'' said Doreen Wade, WPEC's general manager. ``I don't see 
what the big deal is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A sister station, WWMT in Kalamazoo, Mich., initially stopped  
running baseball highlights on its over-the-air newscasts after 
learning of the Internet restriction. The station has since 
restored baseball to regular broadcast but keeps footage off the 
Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm really surprised that it became an issue because it's not  
a revenue-driven thing at all here,'' said Al Forist, the station's 
operations manager. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the Web service costs more money than it generates, so  
WWMT does not want to pay for separate rights. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Football League currently permits Web simulcasts of  
highlights for one-time usage but prohibits video broadcasts of 
entire games on the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Pro basketball officials found a few radio stations that carried  
live feeds of games over the Internet but the stations stopped 
after they were contacted by the National Basketball Association. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Adam Silver, president of NBA Entertainment, said given  
the scope of the Internet, ``it's so difficult to police.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Restrictions extend to non-sports programming as well.  
</P>
<P>
	Premiere Radio Networks, a syndicator of radio programming,  
allows Web simulcasts for some shows, but not for lucrative 
holdings such as Rush Limbaugh and Dr. Laura Schlessinger. Premiere 
worked out a licensing agreement with broadcast.com, a site through 
which stations offer simulcasts. 
</P>
<P>
	Radio feeds through broadcast.com began in 1995. The site now  
has programming from 500 radio and 65 TV stations. Yahoo! Inc., 
which runs the site, expects continued growth as better technology 
makes quality feeds possible. 
</P>
<P>
	The company routinely checks with stations to make sure they  
have the proper rights. Difficulties primarily arise, Yahoo! Vice 
President Kevin Parke said, when the contract says nothing on the 
scope of the rights. 
</P>
<P>
	``If there's a question, we try to go ahead and work with the  
rights holder,'' Parke said. ``The last thing we want to do is 
violate anyone's copyright.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dennis Wharton, spokesman for the Washington-based National  
Association of Broadcasters, said broadcasters are sorting through 
the legal ramifications. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a brave new world we're entering.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990923.0314 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 14:50:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Independent Counsel Law Reviewed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Four people who were put on trial by  
independent counsels appeared before Congress Thursday to mark the 
death of the law that gave prosecutors almost unlimited power of 
pursuit. They did not mourn. 
</P>
<P>
	``I went from a Cabinet secretary to basically an unemployed  
person,'' said Mike Espy, a former agriculture secretary to 
President Clinton who was the subject of a four-year $17 million 
investigation. In the end, Espy was acquitted of all 30 corruption 
charges brought against him. 
</P>
<P>
	At a House subcommittee hearing long sought by Democrats,  
Whitewater figure Susan McDougal accused Kenneth Starr and the 
``right-wing judge'' who appointed him of turning the just-expired 
independent counsel statute into a ``political hammer'' against 
President and Mrs. Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington lawyer Robert Bennett said if you give a prosecutor  
only one case, a reporter one story or a congressman one piece of 
legislation, ``it's a formula for trouble.'' Bennett represented 
Clinton in the Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit and former 
Reagan administration Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger in the 
Iran-Contra scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr himself opposed renewal of the independent counsel law,  
which Congress allowed to expire June 30, saying it violates the 
constitutional separation of powers between the branches of 
government and leaves the investigator vulnerable to political 
attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	The law was written after the Watergate scandal to establish a  
fully independent prosecutor outside the Justice Department, which 
is led by presidential appointees, to investigate high-level 
wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal said the statute ``can be effective ... but only  
if operated as envisioned and not as a political hammer. Redefine 
the selection criteria and the oversight process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said Starr's office was ``out of control'' in a desire to  
``get the Clintons'' and that the three-judge panel that appointed 
independent counsels is ``led by a noted right-wing judge, David 
Sentelle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There was no immediate response to her testimony from Starr or  
Sentelle. 
</P>
<P>
	The subcommittee chairman, Rep. George Gekas, R-Pa., pointed to  
Mrs. McDougal's four felony convictions regarding a fraudulent 
$300,000 federally backed loan. 
</P>
<P>
	``I sit here a convicted felon due to Mr. Starr,'' declared Mrs.  
McDougal, who said she was prosecuted because she would not tell 
``lies'' to implicate the Clintons in wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	A Virginia woman unsuccessfully prosecuted by Starr's office,  
Julie Hiatt Steele, said she was indicted for failure ``to endorse 
Starr's version of the truth.'' Ms. Steele disputed the account of 
presidential accuser Kathleen Willey who said she had confided to 
her friend Ms. Steele an unwanted sexual advance by Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Steele said Starr's office gave her ``several choices.'' She  
could say that Clinton's alleged sexual advance ``was consensual or 
that it was nonconsensual; or I could choose my own day, week, 
month and year to claim that I had been told about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Espy said that after just nine hours of jury deliberations, he  
was called in by jurors who told him that he was as innocent ``as 
anyone they had ever seen.'' He said one juror told him, ``Don't 
feel bad that we took nine hours. We're frequent smokers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lyn Nofziger, White House political director during President  
Reagan's first term, said he was ``the target of an independent 
counsel who had nothing better to do with nearly three years of his 
time -- and mine -- than to try to put me in prison.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The process ``cost me more than $1.5 million. It also destroyed  
my business,'' he said. Nofziger was convicted of committing ethics 
violations in lobbying. His conviction was overturned on appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington attorney Robert Plotkin, who represented Reagan-era  
HUD Secretary Samuel Pierce, said Pierce ``was ruined and his 
retirement funds sapped by legal fees, not because he did anything 
wrong, but because he was in the political bulls-eye of the 
Independent Counsel Act.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990923.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 12:40:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Paducah Worries About Radiation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PADUCAH, Ky. (AP) -- The way the employees tell it, the Paducah  
Gaseous Diffusion Plant sometimes operated as if Homer Simpson were 
running the place. Except that what happened there wasn't funny. 
</P>
<P>
	Workers used to wipe ``green salt'' off the plant lunch tables,  
fully aware it was a radioactive byproduct of the plant's main task 
-- enriching uranium for use as fuel in nuclear reactors. 
</P>
<P>
	They would bury truckloads of uranium shavings that ignited and  
burned upon being exposed to the air. They would dump thousands of 
barrels filled with radioactive contaminants into ponds and bury 
them in the ground. All the while, they were told they were working 
with materials that were ``safe enough to eat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now the employees and many other people in Paducah fear they are  
dying because of what happened at the 47-year-old plant, McCracken 
County's biggest source of jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Naas, a heavy-equipment operator who has worked at the  
plant for 25 years, told Senate investigators this week that he was 
taken off a job in 1974 after being told he was ``hot'' -- meaning, 
he assumed, that he had been exposed to too much radiation. 
</P>
<P>
	Naas said his father turned up ``hot'' on several occasions  
during the 20 years he worked at the plant. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today, he has a form of terminal cancer -- lymphoma. We will  
never know what was the cause,'' Naas said. ``My question is: Will 
I turn up the same, and what recourse will I have?'' 
</P>
<P>
	In June, three plant employees filed a federal lawsuit alleging  
that workers unwittingly were exposed to plutonium and other highly 
toxic substances from 1953 to 1976. The lawsuit is sealed. 
</P>
<P>
	The Energy Department, which owns the plant and is overseeing a  
$1 billion cleanup, later acknowledged that 103,000 tons of 
recycled uranium containing a total of 12 ounces of plutonium were 
handled in Paducah during the period. 
</P>
<P>
	Plutonium is much more potent than uranium -- it can cause cancer  
if ingested in quantities as small as one-millionth of an ounce. 
The Energy Department is investigating why workers were exposed to 
plutonium and whether contractors who operated the plant covered it 
up. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were told that the uranium substances we were working with  
were safe and posed no threat to our health, or to the health of 
our families,'' Garland ``Bud'' Jenkins, who worked there for 30 
years, told a House committee Wednesday in Washington. ``We were 
even told the materials were safe enough to eat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The plant site, with its combined enrichment and cleanup  
operations, is the county's largest employer with 2,000 workers. 
</P>
<P>
	But plant workers are not the only people in this rural area in  
western Kentucky who are questioning whether their health has been 
compromised. 
</P>
<P>
	Ronald Lamb's family has lived and worked for years down the  
road from the Gaseous Diffusion Plant. His father, William, who 
opened the family's auto repair shop in 1961, died five years ago 
after being diagnosed with prostate and bone cancer. Lamb said the 
well at the family's house was found to have a trace of plutonium 
in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	Lamb, 47, sued the contractor that operated the plant at the  
time, but a federal judge dismissed the case, saying there was no 
evidence the well was contaminated. The Energy Department told Lamb 
that the positive test for plutonium in the well water was 
erroneous, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Lamb isn't convinced. He said he suspects contaminated well  
water is responsible for a long series of illnesses he has endured 
for 10 years, including nerve damage, an ulcer and intestinal 
problems. But he can't prove that, either. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just my own belief,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Energy Secretary Bill Richardson apologized for the government's  
secrecy about the plutonium during a recent town hall meeting in 
Paducah, and has proposed $20 million in compensation for plant 
workers with certain radiation-related cancers. 
</P>
<P>
	Some in Paducah are skeptical the secretary's plan will ever  
adequately reimburse them, both for the contamination and the 
cover-up. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he does it, OK. It's been a long time coming,'' said Nita  
Bean Rose, whose father, Charles Arvil Bean, retired from the plant 
with anemia and heart trouble in February 1977. 
</P>
<P>
	That April, he was found to have acute leukemia. He died the  
following year, at 65. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilma Kelley runs a T-shirt and sports clothing shop a half-mile  
up the road from the school. Her husband worked at the plant for 31 
years before retiring in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Kelley said she remains optimistic the government will do  
the right thing. 
</P>
<P>
	``If bad stuff is here, then they will clean it up,'' she said.  
``That's all we can hope.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990923.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 05:50:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Misery in N.C.After Floyd </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINDSOR, N.C. (AP) -- The soggy devastation left by Hurricane  
Floyd hit hard for Robin Ray as she realized it was her son Joey's 
15th birthday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He doesn't have anything,'' she said. ``It just doesn't seem  
right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Their home was destroyed when the Cashie River spilled over its  
banks after 20 inches of rain fell during last week's storm. 
Furniture and carpets were ruined and have been hauled off to the 
dump. 
</P>
