Trent River. ``I've lost basically what I've worked for the last 40 
years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, volunteers from the Emergency Animal Rescue Service  
continued their efforts to save hundreds of pets left behind as 
their owners evacuated. Volunteers have rescued 260 animals, mostly 
dogs, says Terri Crisp, director of EARS, part of the nonprofit 
United Animal Network advocacy group. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've seen dogs swimming out to boats, almost literally jumping  
into the boats,'' said Crisp, who has responded to about 40 
disasters, including fires, earthquakes and tornadoes. ``One almost 
licked me to death, he was so happy just to have human 
companionship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Damage from Floyd is expected to surpass the $6 billion cost  
caused by Hurricane Fran in 1996. Gov. Jim Hunt scheduled a trip to 
Washington today to lobby for more federal money. 
</P>
<P>
	Farther south, in Conway, S.C., officials say rising floodwaters  
are threatening to wipe out parts of Highway 90, cutting off 
thousands of people between Conway and North Myrtle Beach. 
</P>
<P>
	``If these three places flood, we will have islands of people  
out there,'' said acting Horry County administrator Danny Knight. 
</P>
<P>
	The Waccamaw River was expected to crest close at about 17 feet  
-- about 10 feet above flood stage -- this week. State transportation 
officials said they expect to complete work on a dike by Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In hard-hit New Jersey, about 6,000 people had applied for  
relief grants to the Federal Emergency Management Agency by 
Wednesday, said agency spokeswoman Carol Hector-Harris. 
</P>
<P>
	A total damage estimate for the state will not be available for  
at least a week, State Police spokesman John Hagerty said, but the 
town of Manville already has claimed $500 million in damages for 
home, businesses and cleanup costs. More than 200 homes were 
condemned and 1,200 were damaged, Mayor Angelo Corradino said. 
</P>
<P>
	``My knees shake when I think about it,'' Corradino said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
