<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 18:30:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> F-22 Compromise Still Elusive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Under heavy lobbying by the Pentagon and a  
defense contractor, congressional negotiators inched toward a 
compromise expected to keep alive the F-22 stealth fighter program. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Air Force may have to accept a production delay or fewer  
of the prized new $200 million-apiece aircraft in exchange for the 
reprieve. 
</P>
<P>
	Talks were going on behind the scenes Thursday after  
House-Senate negotiators worked until midnight Wednesday without 
reaching agreement on the fate of the most expensive aircraft ever. 
</P>
<P>
	Still a compromise appeared to be taking shape under which  
Senate negotiators were retreating from their insistence that the 
aircraft, manufactured by Lockheed Martin Corp., be fully funded. 
</P>
<P>
	And House negotiators were prepared to accept something less  
than the suspension of production voted by the House in July, aides 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	One proposal on the table, offered by Senate negotiators, called  
for putting much of the $1.8 billion that had been earmarked by the 
Pentagon for buying the first six F-22s into more testing and 
research. 
</P>
<P>
	That could delay production by a year.  
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Jerry Lewis, R-Calif., the leading congressional advocate  
for cutting the program, suggested conferees were close to an 
agreement that would result in ``a pause'' in production. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis is chairman of the House Appropriations defense  
subcommittee. The panel's decision in July to halt work on the Air 
Force's prized $65 billion next-generation fighter jet stunned the 
Pentagon and Lockheed. 
</P>
<P>
	But Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, said Thursday that an agreement  
had not yet jelled. Stevens is chairman of the Senate 
Appropriations Committee and head of the Senate negotiating team. 
</P>
<P>
	The House-Senate conference committee is working on a $267  
billion military spending bill for the fiscal year that begins Oct. 
1. Congressional leaders had hoped to have the measure completed by 
week's end. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the House voted to halt the program in July as too costly,  
both the Pentagon and Lockheed have waged a furious lobbying 
campaign to save it. 
</P>
<P>
	But at the same time, ``the opposition has toughened in many  
ways,'' said Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., one of the negotiators. 
</P>
<P>
	Leahy said he expects the final compromise to at least save part  
of the program, which he likens to ``that second mortage you never 
can quite get rid of.'' 
</P>
<P>
	House leaders have urged Lewis to restore at least some of the  
$1.8 billion for the F-22. House negotiators earlier this week 
offered to put back enough money to buy two of the aircraft in the 
upcoming fiscal year, aides said. 
</P>
<P>
	But support in the Senate for the jet is strong, and senators  
rejected the notion of building only two. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm confident the appropriators will work out some compromise  
that will keep the program alive,'' said Sen. John Warner, R-Va., 
chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee. ``It is essential 
that we keep the program alive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While not formally on the negotiating team -- made up of members  
of the House and Senate Appropriations committees -- Warner, a 
strong supporter of the F-22, is influential in the process. 
</P>
<P>
	The Air Force already has spent $25 billion to develop the F-22  
and plans to spend an additional $40 billion to build 339 of them. 
That would have a price tag of nearly $200 million per plane, the 
most expensive fighter ever built. 
</P>
<P>
	The debate is taking place in negotiations over a compromise  
$267 billion defense bill for the fiscal year that begins Oct. 1. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
