<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ky. Workers Told Uranium Was Safe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Managers at a federal uranium plant in  
Paducah, Ky., for years withheld information from employees that 
they were being exposed to highly dangerous plutonium, workers told 
a congressional hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	A union representing the workers on Wednesday provided the House  
Commerce subcommittee documents -- one as early as 1952 and another 
from 1985 -- suggesting special precautions might have to be taken 
because of exposure to ``transuranic'' materials, including 
plutonium. 
</P>
<P>
	``What is clear is that (government) contractors knew of the  
need to protect workers from plutonium and other transuranics with 
special safeguards as early as 1952,'' Jim Key, an official of the 
union representing atomic workers, told the lawmakers. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said no additional precautions were taken until much more  
recently. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Tom Cochran of the Natural Resources Defense Council,  
said documents obtained as part of a lawsuit on behalf of Paducah 
workers shows that managers of the plant also were aware for years 
that radioactive material was being buried on land outside the 
plant fences in violation of the law. 
</P>
<P>
	Cochran produced a memo from a Kentucky state police  
investigator in 1991 complaining that radioactive and toxic 
material was being buried outside the plant fence, including at a 
state police firing range. Plant workers were directed to dump the 
wastes outside plant property or be fired, the memo said. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not known what action, if any, resulted from the  
investigator's memo to a superior. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just stunned,'' Rep. Fred Upton, R-Mich., the  
subcommittee's chairman, said after hearing several employees 
describe working conditions at the Paducah plant in western 
Kentucky during much of the Cold War years. 
</P>
<P>
	A recent Energy Department investigation concluded that while  
some improvements still need to be made, there is no imminent 
danger to plant workers today. 
</P>
<P>
		   However, a draft report from the Centers For Disease Control and  
Prevention obtained by The Courier-Journal in Louisville, Ky., says 
a host of chemicals and radioactive materials -- reflected in 
groundwater samples containing trichloroethylene and lead -- ``posed 
a public health hazard for children.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wells near the Department of Energy plant are not being used,  
but the CDC summary states that parents who believe their children 
may have ingested significant levels of lead in drinking water 
should alert their pediatricians. 
</P>
<P>
	The CDC's Agency for Toxic Substances and Disease Registry is to  
release its full report on Paducah soon. 
</P>
<P>
	The draft says people who live near the plant do not face any  
health hazards from current operations. 
</P>
<P>
	``Based on the data reviewed and under normal site operating  
conditions, the Paducah Gaseous Diffusion Plant does not currently 
pose a health hazard to offsite populations,'' the draft said. 
</P>
<P>
	James Miller, executive vice president of the United Enrichment  
Corp., which took over operation of the plant in 1993, said the 
government paid $220 million for nuclear safety upgrades at the 
time of the ownership transfer. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the improvements have ``significantly reduced workers'  
potential exposure to radioactive material'' and that ``procedures 
and training are in place to ensure proper protection of 
individuals entering radiological areas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In graphic testimony, Garland ``Bud'' Jenkins described how he  
had worked at the uranium dust-filled plant for 30 years under 
private contractors and was never told some of the uranium had been 
laced with highly dangerous plutonium. 
</P>
<P>
	``We constantly inhaled the dust and fumes. There were no  
devices to measure radioactivity in the air,'' said Jenkins. He 
said workers would wear contaminated clothing home and even after 
taking showers some mornings their bed linens ``would be green or 
black from the black oxide and greensalt'' of the uranium powder. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were told that the uranium substances we were working with  
were safe and posed no threat to our health, or to the health of 
our families,'' continued Jenkins. ``We were even told the 
materials were safe enough to eat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ronald Fowler, who was hired in 1991 as a health physicist at  
the plant, told lawmakers he repeatedly was rebuffed when he raised 
concern about workers' contamination and even today has been 
targeted for harassment and intimidation. 
</P>
<P>
	The Energy Department plans to ask Congress for money to  
compensate Paducah workers who have become ill because of radiation 
exposure. 
</P>
<P>
	Built in 1952 to produce enriched uranium, the Paducah plant has  
been managed by a number of private contractors over the years, 
including Union Carbide and Martin Marietta Energy Systems. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
