<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SEC Supports Stock Market Overseer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Securities and Exchange Commission Chairman  
Arthur Levitt expressed support Thursday for the creation of a 
single, independent agency to police the nation's stock markets. 
</P>
<P>
	In speech delivered at Columbia University on Thursday night,  
Levitt gave mild support to a plan in which each exchange would 
police its own trading, but an umbrella agency would monitor member 
activities, sales practices and trading between the various 
markets. 
</P>
<P>
	``While I certainly am not wedded to any particular model at  
this point -- a great deal more thinking needs to be done -- this 
latter approach is intriguing,'' Levitt said. 
</P>
<P>
	The idea of a single, independent agency has been gaining steam  
amid a proliferation of smaller alternative markets and the 
likelihood that the self-regulating New York Stock Exchange and 
Nasdaq Stock Market may change into for-profit businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Competition from new ECNs, or electronic communications  
networks, has pressured more traditional, non-for-profit exchanges 
like the NYSE and Nasdaq to consider selling stock to the public to 
raise money and allow for greater flexibility in their operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Both, however, would need SEC approval for changes to their  
business or regulatory units. And concerns have been raised that 
the NYSE's and Nasdaq's regulatory units would face endless 
conflicts of interest if the two exchanges became profit-driven 
operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked how that would change the SEC's role, Levitt said the  
agency would act not as an enforcer, but rather as a sort of 
arbitrator, getting the various exchanges to remove 
anti-competitive practices and put in place measures that protect 
the public. 
</P>
<P>
	Levitt said the new ECNs provide needed competition in the  
markets, calling them ``one of the most important developments in 
our markets in years -- perhaps decades.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the SEC chairman also said the growing rivalry among markets  
has heightened the need to find a compromise between the benefits 
of competition and the problems created by fragmented markets, 
which can make it hard for investors to obtain information and find 
the best stock price. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of the securities industry also expressed support  
Thursday for an umbrella regulatory body. 
</P>
<P>
	``The securities industry would like to see one regulator for  
the entire industry,'' said Bernard Madoff, president of Madoff 
Securities in New York, asserting that the SEC would need to ensure 
that such a body remains independent from any of the dozen or so 
stock markets now operating in this country. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading firms such as Madoff's would save money under a single  
regulatory body because they are currently required to help pay 
regulatory costs at each of the exchanges where they are members. 
</P>
<P>
	Madoff said the industry needs Levitt's leadership on the issue  
because neither the NYSE or the Nasdaq has provided any details on 
how they plan to police their markets should they become for-profit 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Some were critical of Levitt Thursday for not moving fast enough  
to address the rapid changes washing over the markets. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's been way behind the curve on this,'' said Junius Peake,  
an economics professor at the University of Northern Colorado and a 
former member of the board of governors at the National Association 
of Securities Dealers, which oversees the Nasdaq market. 
</P>
<P>
	Peake said support for a single, independent regulator has been  
building for 25 years. Such an agency should regulate any aspect of 
an exchange that produces income because, ``That's where everybody 
gets caught up and everybody has a terrible time staying neutral.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990923.0323 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 09:40:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., China To Resume Trade Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States and China will resume  
negotiations next week on a trade agreement which could clear the 
way for China's entry into the World Trade Organization, the 
Clinton administration said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The talks will take place Monday and Tuesday in Washington and  
will involve delegations led by U.S. Trade Representative Charlene 
Barshefsky and Chinese Trade Minister Shi Guangsheng. 
</P>
<P>
	The fact that the talks are taking place at such a high level  
was certain to increase expectations that a long-sought deal could 
be imminent. 
</P>
<P>
	But Helaine Klaskey, a spokeswoman for Barshefsky, refused to  
speculate on whether an agreement can be reached during next week's 
discussions. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think it is quite premature to say when we may conclude a  
deal,'' Ms. Klaskey said. 
</P>
<P>
	She also refused comment on a report in Thursday's Wall Street  
Journal that quoted unnamed members of China's negotiating team as 
saying China's last offer, made in April, was back on the table. 
</P>
<P>
	The two countries came close to agreement in April during a  
visit to Washington by Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji. Many U.S. 
business interests have been critical of President Clinton for 
rejecting that proposal, which contained a number of Chinese offers 
to lower trade barriers that American companies have been 
complaining about for years. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chinese, miffed that they could not get an agreement in  
April, had previously said that offers on the table at that time 
had been withdrawn. The chance of getting an agreement faded 
further after the mistaken NATO bombing of the Chinese Embassy in 
Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	But Clinton and Chinese President Jiang Zemin agreed during a  
meeting two weeks ago in New Zealand to restart the talks with an 
aim of getting China into the WTO before late November, when the 
Geneva-based organization will hold a ministerial meeting in 
Seattle to launch a new round of global trade talks. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart accused  
Republican congressional leaders of jeopardizing the possibility of 
a deal with China with ``quite irresponsible'' comments that 
Congress might not have time to take up the proposal before 
adjourning this year. 
</P>
<P>
	House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, and Senate Majority  
Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., have both said there is little or no 
chance that Congress would vote this year for China's admission to 
the 134-nation WTO. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard to understand why the Republican leader of the  
Senate and the Republican leader of the House would oppose the 
Chamber of Commerce and oppose every business group around and say 
we shouldn't have China in WTO,'' Lockhart told reporters at the 
White House. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990923.0324 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 05:10:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Editorial Roundup  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers in the  
United States and abroad: 

</P>
<P>
	Sept. 21  
</P>
<P>
	The Washington Post, on Congress and managed care:  
</P>
<P>
	The majority leadership of both houses of Congress increasingly  
find themselves in the anomalous position of trying to suppress 
majority will. The House last week passed by 75 votes a campaign 
finance reform bill that the Republican leadership opposed and 
agreed to bring to a vote only when a majority threatened to seize 
control of the floor. ... Friday the leadership acquiesced and 
announced it will likewise permit debate next month on a bill it 
opposes regulating managed care. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Senate, the leadership was able to fend off a strong  
managed care bill only by passing a shell. It will likely take part 
in a filibuster next month to head off a campaign finance bill that 
it agreed to schedule only under duress. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Speaker Dennis Hastert has promised a House vote the week of  
Oct. 4 on a managed care bill that he has been trying to deflect 
for months. ... 
</P>
<P>
	For all the claims made for and against, this is actually rather  
modest legislation. The country wants quality health care at 
minimal cost; the managed care industry sits astride that tension. 
...
</P>
<P>
	The major fight is over liability. ... Lest medicine be consumed  
even more by law, we would rather try a strong appeals process 
first. If a right to sue is granted, as the majority seems bent on 
doing in the House, it ought to be heavily qualified. But there 
ought to be a serious bill, not token legislation such as passed 
the Senate. ... 

</P>
<P>
	Sept. 16  
</P>
<P>
	The Seattle Times, on Northern Ireland:  
</P>
<P>
	Sensitive, creative ideas for reforming the Royal Ulster  
Constabulary, Northern Ireland's police force, must not be allowed 
to wither along with the stunted promise of the Good Friday 
Agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the 175 recommendations made public recently go to the  
heart of the real and symbolic impediments to peace. 
</P>
<P>
	For all of the pragmatism and insight behind the proposals, they  
are at the mercy of parties who are masters at creating excuses not 
to act. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1998 Good Friday plan, which won Nobel Prizes for key  
negotiators, was a meticulously drawn schematic for Protestant and 
Catholic governance and power sharing. Virtually nothing has 
happened, with one exception. 
</P>
<P>
	Part of the plan created a commission to look at the overhaul of  
the RUC, long perceived as the visible sign of British and 
Protestant oppression of Northern Ireland Catholics. 
</P>
<P>
	Rethinking the RUC is not new. But previous government studies  
documented the RUC's failings as a law-enforcement agency. The 
commission, chaired by former Hong Kong governor Chris Patten, 
focused on integration of the police into a peace-seeking society. 
...
</P>
<P>
	Changing the RUC is basic to a reformed society in Northern  
Ireland. 

</P>
<P>
	Sept. 20  
</P>
<P>
	Star Tribune of Minneapolis, on conflicts in American culture:  
</P>
<P>
	Often the headlines are disturbing: A man opens fire on  
teen-agers gathered in a Texas church. Jessica Swanson, age 3, 
murdered, dumped in shallow grave. Katie Poirier, age 19, abducted, 
strangled, burned. Sickos threaten Denver-area schools, saying 
Columbine was ``just the beginning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's tempting to see the world in a downward spiral and to  
blame, in the absence of a more precise target, the culture. 
</P>
<P>
	There's plausibility to this assessment. Surely American culture  
has become more vulgar: the language, the messages on T-shirts, the 
loutish talk shows, the crude movies and music, the rowdy audiences 
at sporting events, the road rage, the gun worship, the gruesome 
video games, the sex-obsessed sitcoms, the general meanness that 
seems to escalate to domestic abuse and to verbal and physical 
assault. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet this is not the entire picture. Violent crimes -- including  
school murders -- are actually down nationwide. While some TV is 
vulgar, other TV has never been better. Museums flourish. Music has 
rediscovered melody. The same culture that created two mass 
murderers in Littleton also created two girls who, even at 
gunpoint, refused to renounce their religious faith. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, what we have are cultural trains headed in opposite  
directions. Writing in the conservative journal American Outlook, 
S.T. Karnick describes ``not a simple vulgarization or decay of 
American culture but a polarization. The good is better than it has 
often been, and the evil is very wicked indeed. And the twain 
seldom meet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anything can be found in today's ``Everything Culture,'' he  
continues, ``no shortage of altruism, nor of egotism. There is no 
unified culture, really, and that is part of the problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Karnick goes on to suggest that America must soon chose between  
the Judeo-Christian tradition and an emerging multiculturalism in 
which all values are relative and tolerance (of anything) is the 
greatest virtue. 
</P>
<P>
	The choice is probably not so urgent or so clear-cut. But his  
description of a polarized culture is strikingly accurate. These 
are some of the best, and worst, of times. 

</P>
<P>
	Sept. 18.  
</P>
<P>
	The Greenville (S.C.) News, on church shooting in Texas:  
</P>
<P>
	(The) violent episode at Fort Worth continued a string of  
indiscriminate killings that are particularly horrible for 
targeting young people. And this one seemed worse for violating a 
religious sanctuary and Wednesday night service for teen-agers. 
</P>
<P>
	Moreover, this latest horror seemed particularly bewildering for  
the killer being neither mentally deranged nor immature and 
confused. ... 
</P>
<P>
	It added to the horror of his rampage that he appeared to have  
no reason for choosing Fort Worth's Wedgwood Baptist Church, and no 
motive for invading it with deadly intentions. The church was seven 
miles from his home. No one there knew him, and no one could think 
of a grievance he held against the church. He claimed none during 
his movement through the sanctuary firing two pistols and 
denouncing religion. ... 
</P>
<P>
	This terrible event will likely add to the political momentum  
for tighter gun controls. The pattern of violence it extends is bad 
enough to look for any relief from nearly any quarter. But no one 
should think that guns either cause or nurture anger or are even a 
trivial reason for its hateful expression. 

</P>
<P>
	Sept. 20  
</P>
<P>
	Stillwater (Okla.) NewsPress, on John Danforth:  
</P>
<P>
	John Danforth has an impossible job. The former senator from  
Missouri has been appointed to probe the government's handling of 
the standoff at the Branch Davidian compound in Waco where more 
than 80 people died. 
</P>
<P>
	Danforth's job is impossible because, no matter what his final  
report says, he will never be able to silence the conspiracy 
theorists -- possibly for good reason. 
</P>
<P>
	As with much of the Clinton administration, the public has been  
fed a steady diet of lies about the government's actions. At this 
point, it's hard to know what to believe. 
</P>
<P>
	But Danforth could still do some good. The majority of Americans  
are still willing to listen to reason, and Danforth may be able to 
present a well-balanced report that convinces the majority in the 
middle that it is a thorough documentation of what happened at 
Waco. ... 
</P>
<P>
	All Americans -- including extremists -- deserve a full accounting  
of government actions in Waco, no matter who gets a black eye. 
Until we receive one, we have nothing to believe but the conspiracy 
theories. 

</P>
<P>
	Sept. 14  
</P>
<P>
	Clarksburg (W.Va.) Exponent-Telegram, on student athlete  
injuries: 
</P>
<P>
	Recent reports in the Journal of the American Medical  
Association should serve as a wake-up call to parents and high 
school, middle school and youth league sports officials -- even 
minor head injuries among young athletes can have a negative effect 
on the learning process. 
</P>
<P>
	While one study indicated that football players suffer more than  
63 percent of all mild traumatic brain injuries among their peers, 
other sports also present danger. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Another study in the same edition indicates that ``participating  
in amateur soccer is associated with lower scores on tests used to 
measure performance in memory and planning functions; repeated head 
injuries may be a contributing factor.'' ... 
</P>
<P>
	Does these mean we should ban all athletics?  
</P>
<P>
	Of course not. The lessons learned on the various playing fields  
are valuable and encourage physical and social development. 
</P>
<P>
	But organizers should heed some worthwhile advice: Work harder  
to make the games safer with improved instruction, rules that 
lessen the chance for head-to-head contact, and better equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	While athletics provide many worthwhile lessons, they are only  
valuable if the student-athlete can remember them later in life. 

</P>
<P>
	Sept. 19  
</P>
<P>
	Houston Chronicle, on misbehaving politicians:  
</P>
<P>
	This dispiriting era of political scandal seemed to crest with  
President Clinton's impeachment, but since then there has been a 
steady tide of misbehavior by public officials, and not limited to 
the party of the president. 
</P>
<P>
	Recently it was revealed that former House Speaker Newt  
Gingrich, one of the nation's principal champions of morality and 
traditional values, and one of Clinton's loudest accusers, has not 
been devoted to his second wife, whom he is now seeking to divorce. 
Gingrich has been linked romantically (if that is the right word) 
to a woman who worked for the House when Gingrich was House 
Speaker. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Politicians are only human. Some serve with distinction and live  
by a code of person honor; some do not. All are imperfect. 
</P>
<P>
	If nothing else, the last couple of years should have convinced  
most voters that the political arena is not a useful source for 
moral guidance and certainly not a font of good example. With the 
campaign for next year's primary elections already under way, 
perhaps the politicians will concentrate their rhetoric on public 
policy and spare the voters their protestations of personal honor 
and aspersions on the honor of opponents. As Ralph Waldo Emerson 
said in an earlier era, ``The louder he talked of his honor, the 
faster we counted our spoons.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Sept. 15  
</P>
<P>
	The Lima (Ohio) News, on courts and parents:  
</P>
<P>
	In another blatant abuse of judicial resources, the  
Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court on Monday was forced to listen 
to arguments concerning a child's spanking. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, minister Donald Cobble's then 9-year-old son brought  
home a bad report card. Cobble, believing in stern discipline, 
administered a spanking on his son with a leather belt. 
</P>
<P>
	By most accounts, Cobble's discipline was far from crossing the  
line into child abuse and should never have gone this far in the 
court system. 
</P>
<P>
	Deciding whether to spank a child should be a decision left up  
to the parents, not the social workers or courts. 

</P>
<P>
	Sept. 21  
</P>
<P>
	The Australian, on East Timor:  
</P>
<P>
	The humanitarian nature of the peacekeeping force in East Timor  
created a high level of support for the Australian troops. However, 
the newspaper said public opinion can ``just as quickly'' turn the 
other way, when troops are harmed and costs accumulated. 
</P>
<P>
	Australia has taken on the role of regional policeman and  
peacemaker, and must be in no doubt the commitment is for as long 
as it takes and as much as it costs. 
</P>
<P>
	The support for our operation now fueled by the urgent need to  
right the injustices being committed on our doorstep must not wane 
as time and costs mount. 
</P>
<P>
	We are in East Timor for the long haul.  

</P>
<P>
	Sept. 21  
</P>
<P>
	The Daily Telegraph of London, on exposure of spies in Britain:  
</P>
<P>
	A decade after the fall of the Berlin Wall, it is easy to  
dismiss the exposure of former KGB and Stasi agents as a pointless 
exercise, serving no purpose other than to humiliate Left-wing 
academics and journalists, most of them now elderly and infirm. We 
are even less inclined to be vindictive towards those who had been 
Soviet ``agents of influence'' during the Cold War than we were 
after 1945 towards those, such as P.G. Wodehouse, who had been 
useful to the Germans. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet such charity must not be allowed to obscure the historical  
truth. Not every indiscretion is treachery, but there is no other 
word for the systematic collusion of Britons with hostile 
intelligence services which -- whatever its subjective motive -- 
objectively helped to undermine the defense of democracy and 
disseminate lies. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cold War may not have cost many British lives, but winning  
it was no less vital to our survival than our victory in the two 
world wars. 

</P>
<P>
	Sept. 22  
</P>
<P>
	Frankfurter Rundschau of Germany, on Taiwan, the earthquake and  
China: 
</P>
<P>
	The People's Republic of China has offered help for the victims  
of the Taiwan earthquake. In addition to President Jiang Zemin, the 
semiofficial organization Arats, which is aware of the relationship 
between Beijing and Taipei, did also. While the tone was subdued, 
the message indicates a joint sadness by all Chinese. The 
rhetorical One-China-Course became superfluous. After the exchange 
of harsh words since July, it was fathomable that the undertone 
carried a `the motherland helps the province,'' possibility. But 
one doesn't pound political capital out of a catastrophe. 
</P>
<P>
	Taiwan should accept the offer of help and with the opportunity  
knot together the threads of dialogue between the two contact 
agencies. After the comments of President Lee Denghui about the 
intrastate character of the relationship across the ocean strait 
and Beijing's responding cannonade of words, its time for 
reflection, in addition the terrible opportunity arises -- the most 
devastating earthquake for a long time -- such contacts rouse 
suspicions it has to do with upcoming elections or so-called higher 
politics. But humanitarian aid builds trust, Greece and Turkey have 
shown this just recently. 

</P>
<P>
	Sept. 21  
</P>
<P>
	Haaretz of Israel, on Jerusalem:  
</P>
<P>
	The episode of the pavilion in Orlando shows once more that  
Jerusalem is a subject fraught with emotions. ... The status of 
Israel's capital is not enhanced by scuffles of this kind. 
</P>
<P>
	Declarations of loyalty to the unity and centrality of Jerusalem  
cannot cover up the city's weaknesses. Despite the policy pursued 
by successive Israeli governments to buttress the Jewish population 
in the capital, Jews are leaving the city in massive numbers. 
Pavilions and telephone cards will not induce them to return. 
</P>
<P>
	The discrimination that has been practiced during the 32 years  
of Israeli rule in the ``united'' city has not succeeded in 
removing the Arab presence from the city. Victories at Disney World 
will not make the Arabs drop their demand for the permanent peace 
settlement to include the area of east Jerusalem, where 200,000 
Palestinians reside and where there are dozens of Islamic and 
Christian holy places. 

</P>
