<P>
	Asahi Shimbun of Japan, on Algeria's referendum:  
</P>
<P>
	The gravity of guilt in disregarding the result of a democratic  
election, in whatever country, is felt anew. And in this 
connection, responses that the Western countries took may also be 
held accountable. 
</P>
<P>
	France, Algeria's former metropolitan country, and other West  
European countries failed to take effective steps to end the 
confusion in Africa. No doubt they feared the emergence of Islamic 
fundamentalism rather than the compromising of democracy. There is 
a strongly held view that Algeria's example led part of the 
wide-ranging Islamic forces in the world to abandon attempts at 
democratic politics, giving them an impetus to go to the extreme. 
The developed world must feel remorse over the way they have 
treated Algeria. 
</P>
<P>
	The reconstruction of Algeria requires assistance from  
neighboring countries. And a preliminary step is for the 
international community to learn from eight years of hideous 
tragedies in that country. 
  	   	
</P>
