<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 14:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bauer Proposes 16 Percent Flat Tax </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican presidential hopeful Gary Bauer on  
Thursday proposed eliminating most tax breaks for businesses and 
individuals and imposing a 16 percent flat tax on income. 
</P>
<P>
	In a National Press Club speech, Bauer also called for reducing  
the payroll tax, which funds Social Security, by 20 percent, while 
cutting the projected increases in benefits for future retirees. 
</P>
<P>
	Families would get a $1,400 per person tax credit and could  
continue to deduct mortgage interest payments and charitable 
contributions. Those are the only deductions Bauer would allow. 
</P>
<P>
	He contrasted his 16 percent flat tax proposal with the 17  
percent flat tax offered by publisher Steve Forbes, a competitor 
for the GOP presidential nomination who is vying with Bauer for the 
support of social conservatives. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, Bauer would no longer let businesses deduct the  
cost of new equipment, while Forbes' plan would let them write off 
those purchases immediately rather than spread out the deductions 
over several years. Bauer contended Forbes' plan would let 
companies escape paying taxes altogether. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is an idea that will destroy the GOP,'' Bauer said.  
``Let's allow our corporate friends to pay zero while secretaries, 
cab drivers, waitresses, farmers and schoolteachers pay 17 
percent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Bauer would tax capital gains -- profits from the  
sale of stock or other investments -- at 16 percent while Forbes 
would not tax them. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes' campaign manager Bill Dal Col, while welcoming Bauer's  
support of a flat tax, questioned the complexity of his plan. 
</P>
<P>
	``What he continues to do is empower the bureaucracy and the  
lobbyists with its minutiae,'' Dal Col said. ``Our plan is simple, 
honest and fair and takes working people off the income tax 
rolls.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer also asked when Texas Gov. George W. Bush would offer a  
tax plan. ``When he does, it will reflect yet more conventional 
Republican thinking,'' Bauer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said the Republican front-runner  
would propose a tax cut. 
</P>
<P>
	``Gov. Bush has a record of cutting taxes in Texas and intends  
to lay out a plan to cut taxes on the federal level as well,'' 
Tucker said. ``He wants to reduce marginal rates to create jobs and 
make sure that we help struggling families on the outskirts of 
poverty.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
