<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Not So Mighty' Gators Take on KU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- When he sees how many yards and turnovers  
Florida is giving up, coach Steve Spurrier can't believe his team 
is 3-0 and ranked third in the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not as mighty as a lot of people think,'' Spurrier said  
this week. ``It's sort of scary when you look at it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, the Gators (1-0 Southeastern Conference) may not need  
to be mighty to beat Kentucky (2-1, 0-0) on Saturday at 
Commonwealth Stadium. It's been 13 years since the Wildcats beat 
the Gators and six since Florida won by less than double digits. 
</P>
<P>
	Kentucky has come a long way since 1996, when a 65-0 loss at  
Florida helped end Bill Curry's tenure as coach. Nevertheless, 
coach Hal Mumme's teams have been beaten soundly in their two 
meetings with the Gators, 55-28 in 1997 and 51-35 last year. 
</P>
<P>
	To stop Florida's streak before it reaches 13, ``It's got to be  
a really good football game for us,'' Mumme said. 
</P>
<P>
	After preserving their nation's-best home winning streak with a  
23-21 win over Tennessee, Spurrier wants his Gators to show better 
form in their first road game. 
</P>
<P>
	``Offensively, we need to score some points,'' he said. ``We can  
play a lot better than we played last week. Eliminate some 
turnovers, hold onto the ball better and eliminate some 
penalties.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Florida has SEC-high 12 turnovers, including six interceptions  
by quarterback Doug Johnson. Johnson also will be without his top 
receiver, Travis Taylor, who's out for three to four weeks with a 
severe right ankle sprain. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully, some of those younger players who have not done  
much yet can step forward and become ballplayers,'' Spurrier said. 
</P>
<P>
	Though Florida's all-sophomore secondary is giving up 325  
passing yards a game and should be tested by Mumme's ``Air Raid'' 
offense, they will get a boost if Alex Brown can duplicate his 
dominating performance against Tennessee. The sophomore end 
deflected a pair of passes, forced a fumble, made an interception 
and sacked Volunteers' quarterback Tee Martin five times. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never thought I'd get five sacks in a game,'' said Brown,  
who counted them on his fingers at one point in the game. ``It 
really surprised me to actually go out and do it. Then to do it 
against Tennessee, on a nationally televised game. It was a really 
big game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Days later, Brown's teammates were still impressed.  
</P>
<P>
	``I've been watching college football since I was a kid, and  
been in games here,'' tailback Earnest Graham said. ``I've never 
seen a guy take over a game like that or do as much as he did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mumme joked that he initially considered a kamikaze defense  
against Brown, sending a walk-on outfitted with a dynamite vest out 
to block him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know one thing,'' Mumme said, ``I don't want him to hit  
(quarterback) Dusty (Bonner) like he hit Tee Martin,'' Mumme said. 
``I don't know what we'll do. We'll have a plan. Whether or not 
it'll work, I don't know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coming off a 44-35 win at Indiana, the Wildcats are looking a  
lot like last year's team, with an efficient, high-scoring offense 
and a vulnerable defense. Though not as strong-armed as the 
departed Tim Couch, the sophomore Bonner has picked up where Couch 
left off statistically, throwing for at least 300 yards and three 
touchdowns in each of his first three games. 
</P>
<P>
	Former walk-on James Whalen Jr. ranks as the nation's leading  
tight end, with 25 catches for 306 yards and five touchdowns. 
</P>
<P>
	The defense, widely expected to take some of the pressure of a  
young offensive unit, has disappointed so far, though, allowing an 
SEC-worst 35 points per game. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
