<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Packers Duo Fill Chmura Void </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- The Green Bay Packers won't find one man  
who can replace Mark Chmura. Luckily, they don't have to. 
</P>
<P>
	Chmura, the Packers' Pro Bowl tight end, is out for Sunday's  
game against the Minnesota Vikings -- and perhaps forever -- after 
three incidents of temporary numbness and partial paralysis 
resulting from a bulging disc in his neck. 
</P>
<P>
	The team announced on Thursday that Chmura will undergo two  
additional weeks of tests before he makes a decision on his future. 
His wife and agent have urged him to retire, and the Packers are 
preparing for a season without his contributions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mark Chmura continues to be a member of our active roster,''  
GM Ron Wolf said. ``He wants to play, and we would like him to 
play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before Chmura's injuries, the Packers had enviable depth at  
tight end. With the nonpareil blocking of Chmura, the pass 
receiving skills of Tyrone Davis and the toughness of Jeff 
Thomason, Green Bay had perhaps the best three-man combination in 
the league. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, Davis and Thomason will be sharing time and will often be  
on the field together in some of offensive coordinator Sherman 
Lewis' sets. Green Bay also signed Lamont Hall as a third tight end 
after waiving him earlier in the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the last way I want to get in there and play,''  
Thomason said. ``Chewy is a good friend of mine, and you never want 
to succeed at the expense of your friends -- at least, I don't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both Davis and Thomason must have strong games against the  
Vikings, coach Ray Rhodes said. Thomason's blocking will be 
particularly important, because Chmura made three Pro Bowls largely 
on the strength of his blocking skills before evolving into a more 
complete tight end later in his seven-year career. 
</P>
<P>
	``The guys that take his place have got to step up, and you've  
got to get the same production,'' Rhodes said. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis is a big, capable passing target, with excellent hands and  
decent speed. He was a wide receiver at Virginia and during his 
first NFL season, but he bulked up to 255 pounds last year, when he 
caught 18 passes for 250 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody can do the things Mark can do. That's why he's probably  
the best tight end in the game,'' Davis said. ``I can do some 
things, and Jeff can do some things, and we should be fine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thomason also has hands, which he uses almost exclusively for  
catching touchdowns. He scored twice in the preseason, and he 
caught the game-winner with 11 seconds to play in Green Bay's 28-24 
season-opening win over Oakland. 
</P>
<P>
	He was Chmura's primary backup the last two seasons, and he and  
Davis also play important roles on special teams. Both will likely 
cut back their special teams roles in anticipation of more 
offensive snaps. 
</P>
<P>
	Chmura will be missed most by quarterback Brett Favre, who has  
used his good friend as a safety valve on offense for seven 
seasons. Nobody on the Green Bay roster knows Favre's thoughts as 
well as Chmura. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's sort of a crutch for me,'' Favre said. ``That's from  
playing together for a long time, practicing together, talking. I 
could be at the line of scrimmage and just call out his name, and 
he knew exactly what I was thinking. You just don't replace that.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
