<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 22:20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grace Battling for '90s Hit Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Lou Boudreau. Richie Ashburn. Roberto Clemente.  
Pete Rose. Robin Yount. And in a few weeks, maybe, Mark Grace. 
</P>
<P>
	With 1,744 hits so far in the 1990s and nine games left, Grace  
has a chance to join the Hit King and the four Hall of Famers on 
that list of decade hits leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to get it. I'd like to get the most hits, the most  
doubles. That'd be nice,'' said Grace, who led Rafael Palmeiro of 
the Texas Rangers by one hit after Thursday's games. ``Robin Yount 
was the '80s, Pete Rose the '70s -- that's some pretty good 
company.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's certainly not a group Grace expected to join. He was the  
Chicago Cubs' 24th-round draft pick in 1985, not exactly the place 
where teams find the future of their franchises 
</P>
<P>
	But he won the Midwest League batting title in 1986, hitting  
.342. The next year, he was the Eastern League's MVP with a 
league-high 101 RBIs. On May 2, 1988, he was called up to the Cubs. 
</P>
<P>
	``They probably thought I'd help them in A ball for a couple of  
years and then send me back to San Diego or something,'' Grace 
said. ``My expectations were, `Hey, here's my opportunity and I've 
got to take advantage of it.' Twenty-fourth-rounders don't get the 
breaks that the high picks get. We've got to make our own breaks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had to make it happen and make it happen fast,'' he said.  
``I just drove myself to do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Grace may not have the gaudy numbers of Tony Gwynn or the talent  
of Ken Griffey Jr., but does have amazing consistency and a work 
ethic that constantly drives him. 
</P>
<P>
	He got his 2,000th hit on Aug. 2. He's hitting .300 for the  
ninth time in 11 seasons. He has 1,233 singles and 360 doubles in 
the 1990s, both second-highest in the decade. He's won four Gold 
Gloves. He's only the second Cub to be the opening-day starter at 
the same position for an entire decade. 
</P>
<P>
	On the mornings after a night game, he's one of the first Cubs  
to make the trek across the field to the batting cages. He's 
usually one of the last to leave the clubhouse, sitting around with 
a few teammates to rehash the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's nothing I'm doing that other guys probably aren't  
doing. I just love to play,'' Grace said. ``What drives me is 
competing. The best players in the world, you get to play against 
them every day and that's what drives me. I want to be one of the 
best of the best. That's it, pretty much, in a nutshell.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So what does make Grace such a good hitter? He's got a natural  
swing, teammate Gary Gaetti said. And like Gwynn and Wade Boggs, 
who both reached 3,000 hits this season, Grace watches the ball 
longer than most players, Cubs manager Jim Riggleman said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They stay inside the ball a long time to evaluate ball and  
strike,'' Riggleman said. ``They make good decisions about what to 
swing at and what not to swing at.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Riggleman calls the decade hits record as significant as  
the home run or batting titles, Grace's run at the '90s mark has 
been overshadowed by The Great Home Run Race, Part II. With the 
Cubs so far down in the standings it's not even worth talking 
about, most fans go to games just to see if Sammy Sosa will hit 
another home run. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mark is tied for the most hits in the decade and people aren't  
sticking around to see if he's getting that hit,'' Riggleman said. 
``I don't think that they're quite aware of the magnitude of this 
feat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Added teammate Glenallen Hill, ``I can't put it into words. To  
actually get a major league hit is tough. To put together the most 
hits in the 1990s is just incredible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Equally incredible is that Grace has managed to do it all in one  
uniform. While Sosa may be the heart of the Cubs these days, Grace 
is their soul. He's Mr. Cub of the '90s, right down to the Wrigley 
Field ivy painted on his Harley-Davidson. 
</P>
<P>
	He's played for six managers and watched dozens of teammates  
come and go. He played with Greg Maddux, Rick Sutcliffe, Andre 
Dawson, Shawon Dunston and Ryne Sandberg. Only equipment manager 
Yosh Kawano has been with the Cubs longer. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a little, small fraternity that I'm in, and there's  
some awfully, awfully good players in that fraternity: Gwynn, (Cal) 
Ripken, (Barry) Larkin, Chuck Finley, (Craig) Biggio,'' Grace said. 
``It's not so much one team, it's this team. This is my home. This 
is where I belong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And maybe soon, he'll belong with Boudreau, Ashburn, Clemente,  
Rose and Yount. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990923.0336 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 13:10:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Urges Nuclear Test Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- On the eve of the third anniversary of President  
Clinton's signing of a treaty to ban all nuclear weapons tests, 
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright appealed Thursday to the 
Senate to join the 45 nations that have approved the pact. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking at the Association of the City Bar of New York,  
Albright said the ban helps curb the spread of nuclear weapons by 
putting explosive tests ``out of bounds for good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The United States can maintain a safe and reliable nuclear  
weapons defense without tests, Albright said, and is capable of 
detecting tests conducted by other countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``Americans and people around the world do not want to live in a  
world in which nuclear testing is business as usual,'' Albright 
said. ``They do not want to make it easy or acceptable for nuclear 
weapons to spread further.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Three years ago on Friday, Clinton became the first world leader  
to sign the treaty. It banned underground weapons tests, the only 
kind permitted after the late President John F. Kennedy signed a 
treaty in 1963 to outlaw nuclear testing in the atmosphere or under 
water. 
</P>
<P>
	Ratification requires the approval of tow-thirds of the Senate.  
</P>
<P>
	A leader in the drive, former Sen. James Exon, D-Neb., pledged  
to do all he could to secure the required votes. But, in an 
interview, he said Clinton had to do more ``and give this some 
additional visibility from the bully pulpit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton approved the treaty after some debate within the  
administration over whether there should be an exemption for very 
limited testing to keep the U.S. nuclear arsenal up to date. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990923.0337 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-23 10:10:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Flooding Causing Hurricane Deaths </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The way hurricanes kill has changed, with the  
majority of lives now being claimed by inland flooding rather than 
the long-feared coastal storm surges. 
</P>
<P>
	The nearly 70 U.S. fatalities attributed to Hurricane Floyd so  
far make it the deadliest hurricane since Agnes, 27 years ago. And 
``it will again be freshwater flooding that was the cause of the 
majority of the deaths,'' said hurricane forecaster Ed Rappaport. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, inland flooding is most evident in North Carolina and New  
Jersey, where heavy hurricane rains overwhelmed rivers and drainage 
systems inundating large areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the era of modern warnings and evacuations, the  
wind-driven waves known as storm surges were the greatest killers, 
claiming thousands of lives along coastlines. 
</P>
<P>
	Of 415 drownings blamed on hurricanes since 1970, a total of  
292, or 71 percent, occurred in inland freshwater floods, Rappaport 
reports in a study being prepared for publication later this year. 
By contrast, just 62 were shoreline drownings and five were in the 
storm surges. 
</P>
<P>
	That's a far cry from decades earlier when powerful storms often  
caused hundreds of deaths with the storm surge, a massive wall of 
water driven ashore by the hurricane. Indeed, the greatest natural 
disaster in U.S. history took place 99 years ago when a hurricane 
storm surge swept over Galveston, Texas, claiming an estimated 
8,000 lives. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that the greatest potential for a loss of large  
magnitude is still the coast,'' Rappaport said, attributing the 
decline in storm surge deaths to improved forecasts and storm 
warnings and the willingness of people to move away from the coast 
when threatened. 
</P>
<P>
	And there has been some luck along the way too. For example,  
last year's Hurricane Georges was forecast to cross the Florida 
Keys as a category 3 storm, but weakened to a category 2. If it had 
strengthened instead, there could have been many fatalities, 
Rappaport said. 
</P>
<P>
	While people are increasingly aware of the storm surge danger at  
the coast, they know less of the hazard of inland flooding, he 
said, often waiting too long to react and then driving into danger. 
</P>
<P>
	``At least 20 percent of the (drownings) were people who were  
in, or attempting to abandon, their vehicles. Almost all of these 
were on, or near, freshwater-flooded roads,'' Rappaport noted in 
his study. 
</P>
<P>
	In his paper, Rappaport estimated that hurricanes have killed a  
total of about 25,000 people in the United States since the 
American Revolution, mostly in storm surges. 
</P>
<P>
	He focused closely on the period from 1970 to 1998, however, and  
found the shift to inland flooding as the greatest hazard. During 
that period, he found 517 deaths directly attributable to 59 
different tropical storms and hurricanes 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 517 fatalities, 295 died in inland counties, 128 in  
coastal counties, 55 offshore and 39 in locations that could not be 
determined. Besides those who drowned, others died of wind-related 
injuries, were killed by tornadoes associated with the hurricanes 
or from building failures, lightning, hypothermia or in downed 
aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
	``Large losses occurred in several tropical cyclones, with more  
than 100 fatalities in Agnes, mostly due to inland flooding in the 
Northeastern states. In numerous instances, loss of life was large 
even after the storm had little or no remaining surface 
circulation,'' he reported, including Charley in 1998, 13 deaths; 
Alberto in 1994, 34 deaths, and Amelia in 1978, 33 deaths. ``For 
these systems, like Agnes, inland flooding from rain was the 
culprit,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
