<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Blocks Oil Royalty Overhaul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Over objections that oil companies are ripping  
off taxpayers, the Senate voted Thursday to block the Interior 
Department from revamping the way it collects royalties on oil and 
gas taken from federal land. 
</P>
<P>
	By a 51-47 vote, oil-state senators won a weeklong struggle to  
put a provision into a $14 billion Interior Department spending 
bill that directs the department not to impose the proposed fee 
changes for a year. 
</P>
<P>
	For nearly two years, the department has tried to change the way  
royalties are calculated, arguing that the government is being 
shortchanged by $5.6 million a month. The government collects about 
$1.2 billion annually from the 12.5 percent oil royalty. 
</P>
<P>
	Oil-state senators argued the fee change amounts to an  
additional tax at a time oil companies are in economic trouble. 
``What is being proposed is unfair,'' declared Sen. Kay Bailey 
Hutchison, R-Texas., who led the campaign block the Interior 
proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote on Hutchison's amendment cleared the way for a final  
approval of the spending bill that provides money for the Interior 
Department as well as energy conservation, forest programs and 
subsidies for the arts. The bill was passed 89-10 and now must be 
reconciled with a House-approved version. 
</P>
<P>
	The oil royalty issue had stymied action on the bill for a week  
as a group of Democrats, led by Sen. Barbara Boxer of California, 
refused to allow a vote. After failing to cut off debate last week, 
supporters mustered the 60 votes earlier Thursday to move the 
matter forward. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., said the Interior proposal is ``a  
scheme that is unnecessarily complicated, unworkable and absurd. 
... It's federal government mooching.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Currently the value of oil taken from federal land is determined  
at the wellhead by the oil companies themselves. The Interior 
proposal would peg the value to the oil's fair market price, taking 
into account certain costs. Critics of the current system say oil 
companies now undervalue the oil by as much as $4 to $5 a barrel. 
</P>
<P>
	But Hutchison said the higher royalties amount to a new tax and  
will raise the cost to oil companies, increasing the price of oil. 
``Who is going to pay? It's going to be the hard working Americans 
who fills up his or her gas tank,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Boxer maintained that the oil companies themselves have  
acknowledged manipulating the numbers and undervaluing the oil and 
gas they take from federal land and from offshore wells. 
</P>
<P>
	A half dozen oil companies in a lawsuit being heard in Texas  
have settled to avoid trial, paying $230 million, she noted. States 
have also collected millions of dollars because of underpayments 
for oil take from state lands, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This allows the oil companies to continue this cozy  
arrangement where they decide what they're going to pay the federal 
government,'' said Boxer. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Russell Feingold, D-Wis., a staunch advocate for campaign  
finance reform, noted that senators leading the fight against the 
royalty proposal also are the top recipients of oil industry 
campaign contributions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody's attempting to do anybody a favor,'' said Domenici.  
``What we're talking about is simple, plain fairness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hutchison has received $1.2 million in oil and gas industry  
contributions since 1993, more than any other senator, and Domenici 
$186,289, sixth highest, according to the Center for Responsive 
Politics. 
</P>
<P>
	The spending measure includes $658 million for energy  
conservation programs, $154 million less than what the Clinton 
administration had requested and $34 million less than provided 
this year. Some senators objected to conservation programs being 
used to push climate change programs. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill also would block an executive order issued by President  
Clinton earlier this year that requires federal agencies to 
significantly cut energy use because of a dispute over fuels to be 
used. 
</P>
<P>
	An attempt by Sen. Conrad Burns, R-Mont., to permanently bar  
introduction of grizzly bears in the Bitterroot Wilderness in Idaho 
and Montana was rejected. But the bill blocks any bears from being 
put into the area before Oct. 1, 2000. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
