<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Memphis Has Tough Task vs. Vols </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- For Memphis, the timing probably  
couldn't be worse. 
</P>
<P>
	It's bad enough that the unranked Tigers (1-2) arrive Saturday  
to face No. 7 Tennessee (1-1) for the first time since Memphis 
broke a string of 15 straight losses to the Vols with a 21-17 upset 
in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Tigers also come seven days after Tennessee's 23-21 loss  
to Southeastern Conference rival Florida, a defeat that could 
severely hurt its chances of repeating as national champion. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not sure that there is a good time'' to play Tennessee,  
Memphis coach Rip Scherer said. ``I didn't know there was a good 
time. I'd just as soon be playing James Madison or somebody. ... I 
mean, I am sure they are upset about losing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee coach Phillip Fulmer sets his jaw, tries to put his  
sixth loss in seven games to the Gators behind him and looks to 
Saturday's contest. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's not going to be a letdown, ain't going to happen,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Volunteers coaches reviewed the Florida game, in which the  
Vols' fourth-quarter comeback fell short, and judged it a success 
in effort if not execution. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whenever you have 13 penalties called on you as an offense and  
you give up seven sacks, it is hard to win,'' offensive coordinator 
Randy Sanders said. ``We can't beat many folks playing like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Quarterback Tee Martin, who is ready to play despite a shoulder  
injury against Florida, said he is eager to see how the Vols bounce 
back. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can only go up,'' he said. ``As bad as we played we only  
lost by two points. That shows you how good we were, and I know how 
good we are. The rest of the year, we are just going to have to 
have better concentration.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fulmer is impressed that even in losses, Memphis held  
Mississippi and Mississippi State to a combined 16 points. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tigers have ``a very challenging (defensive) scheme that we  
don't see typically. They have a multitude of movement and blitzes 
and potential for problems out there,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tigers coordinator John Thompson threw a similar scheme at the  
Vols when he ran the defense at Southern Miss. The Vols won those 
games handily in 1995 and 1997, but it still posed a challenge. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders said the Tigers ``at times will look like minnows in a  
bucket, moving around everywhere. It is one of those schemes that 
if you don't make your plays and you don't stay aggressive, you can 
look ugly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee hasn't lost two consecutive games since 1994.  
</P>
<P>
	``They are a prideful team and a team that does not lose very  
often,'' Scherer said. ``So I would anticipate that their mentality 
will not be real positive. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's something we have no control over. We are coming up  
there to play our tails off and to try to win the football game, 
and whatever Tennessee's mentality is -- we respect the daylights 
out of them -- but we really can't worry that much about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Tigers' 1996 upset of the then sixth-ranked Vols in Memphis  
still haunts Tennessee. At the time, Fulmer called it ``the most 
disappointing game I've coached'' and Vols coaches still point to 
it as an example of why no opponent should ever be overlooked. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of guys have that Memphis game lingering in the back of  
their head,'' Tennessee linebacker Raynoch Thompson said. ``They're 
not putting what happened behind them.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
