<HEADLINE> Village Voice Put Up for Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Village Voice and seven other alternative  
weekly newspapers owned by real estate billionaire Leonard Stern 
are on the block. 
</P>
<P>
	Stern said in a statement Wednesday that he was selling Stern  
Publishing ``after consulting with my children and discussing their 
future career plans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	stable of seven alternative weekly newspapers, including  
</P>
<P>
	Stern has enlisted the media banking firm Veronis, Suhler &AMP;  
Associates Inc. to help with the sale. Bob Broadwater, the bank's 
managing director, would not comment on potential buyers or an 
asking price but said Stern might be willing to sell the papers 
individually if necessary. 
</P>
<P>
	Broadwater said the papers are very profitable, but he declined  
to disclose figures. Stern Publishing has revenues of more than $80 
million and 500 employees nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the Voice, which has a weekly circulation of  
250,000, Stern Publishing also owns LA Weekly, Orange County 
Weekly, Seattle Weekly, City Pages in Minneapolis, the Cleveland 
Free Times and the Long Island Voice. 
</P>
<P>
	The Village Voice was founded in 1955 by Norman Mailer and two  
colleagues. Stern bought it 14 years ago from Rupert Murdoch. 
</P>
<P>
	Stern also is involved in real estate and owns Hartz Mountain  
pet products. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
