<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Va. Tech May Be Asked To Leave A-10 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BLACKSBURG, Va. (AP) -- Virginia Tech, which plans to join the  
Big East Conference as a full-time member in 2001, may be asked to 
leave the Atlantic 10 Conference next summer, according to A-10 
commissioner Linda Bruno. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't want to cut Tech loose with no place to go, but two  
years is a long time,'' Bruno told The Roanoke Times on Wednesday. 
``We want to help Tech, but there's also concern for the league.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tech had planned to remain in the A-10 until its Big East  
membership started in July 2001. If Tech has to leave the A-10 next 
year, it would either move into the Big East early, pending 
approval by other Big East member schools, or spend the 2000-01 
season as an independent in all sports but football and wrestling. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Weaver, Tech's athletic director, said he was unaware of the  
possibility of an early exit from the A-10. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know nothing about it,'' he said. ``... Obviously, the  
league doesn't feel strongly enough about it yet to let Virginia 
Tech know what's going on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Big East deal, announced Aug. 24, is contingent on the  
league's current football membership remaining intact for 2001-02. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
