<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Neuheisel To Face Old School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- It's time for Rick Neuheisel to face the  
situation. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, some old friends arrive in town to play Neuheisel's  
new football team, the Washington Huskies. Only this time, his old 
friends, the Colorado Buffaloes, are enemies. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to have to watch it because I'm going to be  
emotional,'' said Colorado linebacker Ty Gregorak, recruited from 
Spokane to play football in Boulder. ``It's a big game for me 
personally.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's a big game for Colorado, which feels Neuheisel betrayed the  
Buffaloes for big bucks after a 51-43 victory over Oregon in the 
Aloha Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington was on that same bowl doubleheader in Honolulu last  
Christmas. The Huskies lost to Air Force 45-25 in the Oahu Bowl, a 
loss that probably cost coach Jim Lambright his job. 
</P>
<P>
	When Washington athletic director Barbara Hedges received  
permission from Colorado AD Dick Tharp to talk to Neuheisel in 
January, she sold him on the Huskies with a $997,000-a-season, 
five-year contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Many Colorado players felt Neuheisel had led them to believe he  
had made a lifetime commitment to stay in Boulder. 
</P>
<P>
	After accepting the Washington job, Neuheisel flew back to  
Colorado to talk to his former players. They were shook up. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the end of the speech, he said, `Does anyone have anything  
to say?' It was silent for about a minute. I just said, `See you 
the 25th,''' Gregorak said. ``I can't believe it's already here. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt like it just flew by. I can't wait for it to come.''  
</P>
<P>
	The players Neuheisel recruited to Colorado could make  
Washington's worst start since 1985 even worse. A victory by the 
Buffaloes would make the Huskies 0-3 for the first time since 1969, 
when they lost their first nine games. 
</P>
<P>
	The Huskies, short on talent and depth, lost to Air Force 31-21  
last Saturday for their first defeat in a home opener since 1985. 
They were beaten 35-28 in their opening game at BYU. 
</P>
<P>
	Colorado was upset by Colorado State 41-14 in its opener in  
Denver, then beat San Jose State 63-35 and Kansas 51-17. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew it was coming,'' Neuheisel said. ``If it helps them  
prepare for the game using a revenge factor or anything like that, 
`Let's get the coach, he left us, that kind of a thing,' then I'm 
sure they'll try to use it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neuheisel remembers Gregorak's promise.  
</P>
<P>
	``That was a very emotional day,'' he said. ``I'm sure he's  
looking forward to the contest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neuheisel defended his decision to bolt Colorado, where he  
replaced Bill McCartney in 1995, and go to Washington, where the 
program began to unravel last season when the Huskies were 6-6. 
</P>
<P>
	Colorado replaced Neuheisel by luring Gary Barnett from  
Northwestern. Like Neuheisel, Barnett had said he didn't intend to 
leave. Like Neuheisel, he left. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think both of us fully believed that,'' Neuheisel said. ``I  
don't think there's any question that both of us fully believed 
that we could stay at those particular institutions for a long time 
and be very happy. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was not unhappy at Colorado. That wasn't why I left. I was  
given a fantastic opportunity at a fantastic university that forced 
me to explore and upon exploration I made the best decision for 
myself and for my family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Colorado's players aren't happy with Neuheisel's decision,  
Neuheisel isn't happy with Barnett's remarks about minor recruiting 
violations that occurred after he arrived in Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	Neuheisel says Barnett insinuated on TV that Neuheisel lied  
about having no knowledge he was violating NCAA rules when he sent 
five coaches to visit prospects during a mandated quiet period 
shortly after both coaches were hired. 
</P>
<P>
	``He never directly called me a liar,'' Neuheisel said, ``but  
anyone looking at that footage would come to that conclusion that 
he thinks that. And that bothers me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Self-imposed penalties by Washington satisfied the Pac-10, which  
took no further action. The penalties include loss of recruiting 
time later this year. 
</P>
<P>
	With all the sniping between the coaches, one could be led to  
believe a feud has developed. Asked if there was any bad blood 
between them, Barnett said, ``No ... Does that shock everybody?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barnett even went as far as to say that time has caused the game  
to lose its emotional edge. 
</P>
<P>
	``If this game was played six months ago, it would have been an  
issue,'' Barnett said. ``I don't think it's an issue now. I think 
us losing to Colorado State has taken most of all that out of this 
team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That will be seen Saturday.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
