<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Has Money-Laundering Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration today unveiled its  
first national money-laundering strategy, aimed at stanching the 
flow of billions of criminal dollars through the U.S. financial 
system. 
</P>
<P>
	The package of proposed new laws and rules comes as federal  
investigators examine allegations of a huge money-laundering scheme 
involving Russians and the Bank of New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``Money laundering is a very sophisticated crime and we must be  
equally sophisticated,'' Attorney General Janet Reno said at a news 
conference. Money laundering, she said, ``directly impacts each and 
every hard-working American.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The scheme of cleansing criminal (money) through legitimate  
bank accounts of hard-working Americans must be stopped,'' said 
Reno, who was joined by Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers. 
</P>
<P>
	The new strategy seeks to bolster international cooperation in  
investigating money laundering and strengthen U.S. enforcement 
through tighter regulation of banks and other financial 
institutions. It includes a requirement that storefront check 
cashiers, brokerage firms and casinos notify authorities of 
suspicious activities the way banks must do. The government would 
designate new high-intensity money-laundering zones. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposals are aimed at combating the cleaning of  
drug-trafficking profits and other illicit gains by cycling them 
through the financial system. Congress directed the Treasury and 
Justice departments to submit the new strategy early this year, 
before the case involving the Bank of New York broke. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration is ``on the same path we're on,'' said Rep.  
Spencer Bachus, R-Ala., chairman of the House Banking subcommittee 
on monetary policy and a key author of legislation to fight money 
laundering. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of New York episode ``certainly brought it home to  
everyone,'' Bachus said Wednesday in a telephone interview. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal investigators, meanwhile, are working hard to unravel  
the alleged money-laundering scheme involving the bank, James 
Robinson, assistant attorney general in charge of the Justice 
Department's criminal division, testified Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian businesses and individuals -- including organized crime  
groups -- are suspected of illegally channeling as much as $10 
billion through the Bank of New York, the nation's 15th-largest and 
said to be its oldest. 
</P>
<P>
	No one has been charged. On Tuesday, Switzerland's government  
announced that Swiss banks have frozen $16.8 million in accounts 
suspected to be linked to the case. Authorities in Britain, Russia, 
France and Austria also have been dissecting the complex case. 
</P>
<P>
	USA Today reported today that investigators now believe as many  
as 10 U.S. banks might have been used in the money laundering 
scheme. But it said none have been accused of wrongdoing and that 
all are cooperating with the investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has been and will continue to be a complex and  
painstaking investigation,'' Robinson said at a House Banking 
Committee hearing. ``Significant investigative resources have been 
and will continue to be expended in an effort to ensure that we 
uncover the full story behind those transactions and bring any 
merited criminal charges.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In recent years, Robinson noted, ``we have seen with increasing  
frequency suspicious financial transactions emanating from (Russia) 
..., which naturally raise the question of money laundering.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also at Wednesday's hearing, the Bank of New York's chairman  
defended his institution's reputation but acknowledged ``a lapse'' 
by its internal supervisors in allowing questionable accounts to 
stay open. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas A. Renyi, who also is the bank's chief executive officer,  
stressed that no charges have been filed against the bank. 
</P>
<P>
	In response to questions, Renyi confirmed that the son-in-law of  
Russian President Boris Yeltsin maintained accounts at an offshore 
branch of the bank in the Cayman Islands. 
</P>
<P>
	The accounts were in the name of Leonid Dyanchenko, an oil  
trader who is married to Yeltsin's daughter, Tatyana. The 
Washington Post quoted sources in today's editions as saying the 
accounts contained more than $2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Manhattan-based Bank of New York, founded in 1784 by Alexander  
Hamilton, has been buffeted by the allegations since they surfaced 
in news reports on Aug. 19. 
</P>
<P>
	``Neither the bank nor any of its customers have lost any money  
as a result of the activities in question,'' Renyi said. ``We have 
cooperated fully with the ongoing investigations.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
